Description:
One minute I’ve got an itty bitty waist.. next minute my stomach sticks out more than my butt 😳😅
-
In the nicest way possible before experts diagnose my very own bod let me just state this: 
1. I don’t suffer from IBS
2. I’m not in any physical discomfort 3. I don’t binge/ this was not a result of eating loads of ‘crap food’ 
4. I’m not intolerant to any type of food, except slightly allergic to bs 
-
Let me also just point out that for sure, on the left I’m standing in a way to accentuate my body (let me work the angles ok xx). The right, I’m just straight up taking a pic to show you that I too look like this at certain points in the day. Now if you are perplexed by these photos, this is a result of consuming a high volume of (healthy*) food - oh & alot of drink. I’m making this post because people assume I look the way I do in my posts 24/7 or misinterpret these posts of mine. When you eat food it has to go somewhere *meet the food baby*. Also, the leaner a person is, the more visible said food baby becomes. Infact, upon taking these (after food) pics my bf often mocks me for how visible the meal is, as if he can make out the smoked salmon & grains are slowly making their way down my bod 😂😂 but then in contrast you’d never be able to tell if he’s eaten or not if we were to compare even straight after eating the same meal. I guess I just wanted to remind you that our body’s fluctuate throughout the day & it’s normal so don’t feel bogged down for looking different at the end of the day Vs the morning. 💕
Ps. Of course if you experience discomfort / other symptoms upon eating certain foods, get this checked. I’m only sharing my personal experience as we are all different. But food does have to still go somewhere.. xxxxxxxx

I started my personal training course as an 18 year old who fucking loved the gym.

When I started training clients, most of the other personal trainers I knew were in the same boat. They already had the basics nailed down and were looking at fine tuning the little details to get the most from their fitness plan.

If something was "optimal", we wanted to know. Was there a “best” time of the day to train? Did organic vegetables have a higher micronutrient content than conventional? Is consuming 1.8g/kg/day protein better than 1.6g/kg/day?

One day, I was training a client and they said "I will never get good results in the gym. I don't want to be as meticulous as you are. I still want to go out for drinks and pizza with my friends. I still want to have a social life".

Right then I had the big slap in the face I needed to realise that I worried about a lot of shit that just didn't matter for most people.

On social media, we are constantly discussing "optimal" macronutrient splits, whether HIIT is "better" than low intensity cardio, whether eating 6 meals per day might offer a teeny tiny bit of a "metabolic advantage" than eating 3 meals per day and other shit like that.

For a lot of people, nutrition and training advice is confusing as fuck and they just need to know where to begin.

While we sometimes engage in mental masturbation over the finer details, ask yourself these questions?

- What percentage of people exercise more than 3 times per week?
- What percentage of people are not eating enough fruits and vegetables?
- What percentage of people would benefit from just eating more protein, without worrying about whether they should spread their meals out to optimally raise muscle protein synthesis levels or whether their last meal hit the magical leucine threshold?
- What percentage of people would benefit from focusing more on unprocessed foods, rather than getting scalded for eating a single Krispy Kreme doughnut

Let’s not focus so much on what is “best” if it comes at the expense of just telling people what is “better”.
Image Text: Ben Carpenter @bdccarpenter Theory: Lots of people enter the fitness industry because they are hardcore exercise enthusiasts, not realising they have no fucking idea on how to empathise with people who aren't hardcore exercise enthusiasts.

Tomorrow will be my 100th day without a drink and I’ve also grown 100,000 Instagram followers in the same period. 

2020 I experienced all kinds of emotions and learned that anything that interferes with my productivity plays havoc with my headspace. 

From pandemics to hangovers I decided to take some variables that influenced that into my own hands and give up something that gave me pleasure for a lifestyle that may make me happier as a byproduct. 

I don’t have a booze problem at all, I just set out to lift my self-standards a bit and I’ve enjoyed it to be honest, it’s not been easy at all. 

I’m not setting a time frame on this gap from  drinking but it’s nice only living with one personality for a few months 😂 (the other personality being the fucking idiot version of yourself when you drink.)

P.s for the record it only takes about 3 weeks before you become all high and mighty and say stuff like “drunk people are so annoying.” 😂😂😂 

Cheers. 🥤

Description:
Same girl. Same weight. Totally different mindset 💪🏻
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
On the left I was around 16. I hated my body and over the next few years everything I did was centred around striving to lose — lose weight, lose a dress side, lose calories from my day, lose something I didn’t like about my body and so on. I learned the hard way that if you’re always trying to LOSE, how are you ever going to truly WIN?
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I don’t recognise the me on the left anymore. Not because of how much I’ve physically changed, but because of how I know I felt and treated my body. I didn’t get here through focusing on what I had to lose but instead chasing ALL there was to gain. A lifestyle to love which makes me feel strong and powerful, a body to cherish and respect, an appetite to feed and fuel — and so so much more.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I know ‘transformation photos’ can have a bit of a stigma attached to them but I will never not show my starting point. Because if you only ever see me now — you miss out on the journey it took to get there. Never compare your day 1 to somebody else’s day 7,564. It’s your journey, at your pace!! ❤️
POV: Your parents go on vacation 👩🏼‍🤝‍👨🏽

How to stay busy when you’re in a caloric deficit 🤣

#neatup247

From wishing my legs smaller, to wishing them STRONGER 💪🏻 I honestly can’t believe how much my mindset has shifted towards my body over the last few years. I used to be so obsessed on ‘smaller’ — smaller number in my waistband, smaller number on the scales, smaller this, smaller that. Now honestly my goal is STRONG. Whatever that looks and feels like for me 🙌🏻
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Making small progress each and every day to show up as my strongest self, inside and out. It’s not the actions you do occasionally that matter but those small everyday habits and choices that add up to something much bigger & more powerful 💥
Summer goal: strong AF 💪🏻 because nobody should be made to feel like a season determines their size, scale weight or beauty 👊🏻

Fat shaming is NOT ok. Shaming people for wanting to lose weight is also NOT OK! 😤⁣
⁣
I think the health at every size (HAES) movement has several positive aspects to it. They are right in that diet culture can be very harmful & dangerous for certain people. They are right in that you can still practice healthy habits even if you are overweight or obese (btw if you practice health y habits, the likelyhood or losing weight increases... just saying). And there is evidence you can be overweight & still be healthy so long as you lose a small amount of weight & exercise frequently & practice other health lifestyle habits⁣
⁣
But then some HAES extemeists say shit like “calorie deficits don’t work” or “long term weight loss is impossible” 🙄 or that obesity has absolutely NO negative health ramifications 🙄. Listen, I’m not for making people feel bad about their weight. But I’m also against utter bullshit. Hell, I had a HAES extremist chew me out for being a nutrition coach & “part of diet culture.” Never mind I’ve helped contribute to eating disorder research, been an advocate for those with eating disorders, & routinely convince people NOT to diet 🤷🏼‍♂️
⁣
This just demonstrates that small minded people can become extremists about ANYTHING. Losing weight is difficult & keeping it off more difficult? TRUE? Calorie deficits don’t work? Absolute horseshit 🤨🙄. Shaming people helps no one. Bullshitting also helps no one⁣
⁣
Here’s an idea, how about some of you mind your own fucking business & not insert your opinion when people don’t ask you 🤷🏼‍♂️

In fact, most people who ‘shame’ are doing so out of their own insecurity. You hate diet culture? Great. That doesn’t make it ok to shit on someone who wants to lose weight. Mind yo damned business
Image Text: Layne Norton, PhD @BioLayne Wanting to ose weight doesn't make you a bad person Tracking your food or restricting your food in some way is not an eating disorder Fat shaming is terrible. Diet shaming is no better If you are happy with your body composition, great Don't shame those that wish to change

Description:
Once upon a time, there was a boy called Ben.

Ben was a very gullible teenager and believed what some "trusted" people told him. He was not familiar with researching things himself, which later in life he found quite a joyous hobby.

He frequently succumbed to fitness industry misinformation, and before he knew it, he was avoiding a long list of foods for reasons that had been very strongly exaggerated.

People selling the damaging effects of sugar, as if one teaspoon in your coffee would make you store body fat and give you instant type 2 diabetes.

Ben did not understand that something could result in deleterious effects *in excess* yet be benign in moderated quantities. Just because chocolate isn't the healthiest food in the world, doesn't mean that you have to strictly avoid it for the rest of your life.

Ben was inadvertently caught in a dangerous spiral where he avoided lots of foods temporarily, only to find himself periodically wanting to binge eat on them again. He realised life was a lot better when he didn't have unnecessary food paranoia, and could eat foods he wanted in moderation without feeling the urge to commit compensatory-death-by-chocolate after avoiding it for the past month.

He decided to make it his mission to stop people falling for the same traps he did, so they could understand that "fitness" didn't have to come at the expense of mental health or actually having a fucking social life.

You can simultaneously acknowledge that you probably shouldn't eat massive quantities of particular foods yet still not feel the need to strictly avoid them, they are not synonymous.

Happy Easter ❤️
.
.
.

This will be one of THOSE meet recaps that @omarisuf makes fun of. So, I was having the best build up of my life, and 12 days out I had a minor adductor/medial ham strain. No warning signs, I was feeling great and it was with a back off set. It felt better daily, but forced me to more aggressively taper than I normally do on squat and deadlift. I kept pushing bench and hit a lifetime PB paused 155 eight days out...and strained my pec 😑. Again, no warning signs, feeling great. This bummed me out, reminded me how little control we actually have. I backed off, got an ultrasound that confirmed it was as minor as I thought (but still a small tear) and took it day by day going by pain. I hit 110 pain free 3 days out, so I decided on game day to do 120 then go by feel. But the wind was out of my sails, I wanted to skip the meet. 
I’m glad I didn’t. My ham/adductor was totally back to normal, and the aggressive taper worked. The heaviest squat in my build up was 212.5 and just 200 after the strain. Squats flew on the platform, but we played it safe and I smoked 220kg (I have no idea what I said in the video lol). Bench also was a pleasant surprise, 120 was pain free, as was 130, and then 140! I got back up to my planned opener and most importantly, my pec is still attached lol. At this point I knew I was safe to let rip on deadlifts. After I pulled 230 and 245 the fastest I ever had, we loaded 260 for a 10kg PB deadlift, which I barely got and unbelievably also got a 2.5kg PB total. I went from not wanting to compete to having the best meet of my life, even with a conservative squat, and leaving 15kg off bench🤯 
So, lessons learned, shit happens. Sometimes unpredictably (not sure how to prevent it in the future, maybe slower build up in load?), I benefit from more aggressive tapers, and I’m not done improving. Huge thanks to @aucklandpowerlifting officials, refs, spotters and loaders, congrats to all the lifters, and huge thanks to my awesome handlers @colby.sousa and @alyssajoyable 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻 looking forward to nationals!

Description:
Let’s not overcomplicate this whole fitness thing.
.
Quit wasting your money on fat burners, diarrhea teas and detox bullshit.
.
Start doing the obvious things you probably aren’t spending enough time on.
.
Most importantly, remove the negative people from your life.
.
Immediately.
.
Someone recently asked me how much I think genetics impact your ability to lose body fat.
.
I said genetics impact everything in life.
.
But when it comes to fat loss, genetics are no where near as important as your environment.
.
I think this holds true for pretty much everything.
.
Yes, your genetics play a role in determining your ceiling for potential.
.
But most people never get anywhere close to that ceiling and much of it has to do with who you choose to surround yourself with.
.
You owe nothing to no one except yourself.
.
Put yourself in a situation and environment that allows you to achieve everything you’ve ever wanted.
.
Have a great weekend.
.
.
.
.
.

Description:
I was wrong about keto and fasting 😔

HAHA JUST KIDDING! But seriously though don’t feel bad. There are people who actually believe the law of thermodynamics isn’t a thing 🤣

Or that insulin makes you gain body fat in a calorie deficit 🤣

Or that fasting is the secret to longevity 🤣

Or people like @marksissonprimal using the word ‘metabolic flexibility’ repeatedly without really understanding it

Let’s take that last one since it’s hot. Metabolic flexibility is the ability to use both carbohydrates and fats as fuel. You know what low carb diets do? Make you LESS metabolically flexible. In fact, just a short duration of a ketogenic diet will impair glucose tolerance as assessed by an oral glucose tolerance test PMID: 32109885

You know what increases metabolic flexibility? Eating a balanced diet, exercising, and not having excess adipose tissue 🤷🏼‍♂️

Don’t buy into hucksters using nebulous terms they don’t understand. Always ask yourself the following questions when someone makes a claim:

1) Compared to what?

2) What is the cost? (Everything is a trade off)

3) Where is your HARD, DIRECT evidence to support your claim.

The bigger the claim, the more rigid these 3 must be fulfilled. 

Shoutout to @thethomassowell for those 3 pillars

Don’t buy into hype bullshit. There are no hacks. No quick fixes. Not unless you want to take drugs & then there is another cost that will have to be paid

Consistency. Hard work. Dedication. 

The magic you are looking for is in the WORK you keep trying to avoid

Get to fucking work & KEEP GOING❤️

Cheers to another trip around the sun ☀️

Wishing my beautiful firstborn Jeremiah Thomas a happy 5th birthday!
My boy you're one in a million, you make me so proud each and every day and there are so many wonderful things I want to say about you.

Instead, I want to share one of our most recent car chats because your little innocent mind has a wonderful way of making the weight of the world seem ok. I hope this brightens everyone's day as it did mine.

Miah asked, “Mum, is your cup empty?”
I replied “My cup? What do you mean?”
Miah replied “Your cup in your heart. Everyone's heart has a cup. When somebody doesn't like you or say nice things to you, your cup in your heart empties & you become sad. But when people like you & say nice things to you, it fills your cup up and you are happy.”

I stopped for a second and thought, how simple and perfect was this little boys motive to being kind & friendly. If we all thought about how our actions affect others “heart-cups” we would think before we speak and make time to potentially fill as many cups as we can. Eventually, this would become second nature, a habit I personally think is valuable to have.

Jeremiah, thank you for making me a mum, I love you ❤️ @the.duncan.family_

Things that can fuck up your appetite signals; a lesson in food processing.

Let's take the humble potato. On it's own when it is plain, it has a very high satiety score (actually the highest out of all the foods studied) which means that talented little bugger fills you up more than most foods on the planet. Great news for people trying to regulate their appetite when dieting.

But things change with processing, once you fry that little bugger in some oil or butter and add some seasonings, it definitely gets more delicious, less satiating and more calorie dense meaning there is a strong likelihood you will want to eat more.

When you take that processing further and deep fry it in oil, what started out as a humble satiety-promoting potato can turn into some of the most "addictive-like" foods on the planet.

Same potato, but now it has a higher fat content, a completely different texture, less fibre and more flavour.

Whilst everyone is pointing the finger exclusively at sugary foods for being bad for appetite regulation, they may overlook the bazillion other factors that can transform even the most boring food into something that is super fucking tasty and seemingly impossible to stop eating.

Thanks for coming to my TED talk.

Any questions?

Apparently, potatoes WILL make you fat.

There is so much wrong with this, I am not quite sure where to begin.

In the Minnesota Starvation Experiment, subjects were rationed on a low-calorie diet coming from foods that were typically available in war-torn areas of Europe, consisting of potatoes, bread, turnips, macaroni and rutabaga (swede). In this extreme experiment, subjects lost a quarter of their body weight, despite it being a very carbohydrate heavy diet. (PMID of secondary paper: 15930436).

One guy, called Andrew Taylor (cc @spudfit), decided to eat nothing but potatoes for a year and lost 117lbs.

Potatoes, when served plain, have a high "satiety index". When given isocaloric portions of 38 different foods before being given access to a buffet, eating boiled potatoes resulted in the lowest subsequent intake of food, indicating that potatoes were more filling and therefore good for regulating appetite. (PMID 7498104).

People sometimes focus so much on blood sugar and insulin levels they completely overlook the role of calorie balance. Even sugar consumption doesn't result in weight gain when consumed in the context of a calorie controlled diet. (PMID 9094871).

I don't believe I actually need to clarify this but no, potatoes will not automatically "make you fat".

Can we please stop this unnecessary food paranoia?
.
.
.

Description: ¡Buenos días! 🌞

This Bill Burr quote changed my life. 

I was 27, no mortgage, no savings and off backpacking to Australia as my mates were settling down and doing ‘the right thing’.

I felt like I was a bit broken, unsettled almost. But reading this quote backed what I already felt for so much of my adult life.

That it’s better to be in a bunkbed figuring it out, than in a shared bed with someone wishing I hadn’t. 

There’s nothing wrong with settling down in your twenties, but there’s also nothing wrong with doing nothing but figuring out who you are and what you want to do in your twenties. 

I’m 31 years old. I’ve only had a job I love for 7 of those, I have another 30-40 years left of working. 

The point I’m trying to make is that you have to construct your life to how you want to live it; not what is the ‘right thing to do’ by societal norms. 

Ultimately you need to do what you want to do. 

Not where you think you should be at this stage in your life. 

If you’re on the fence, remember. 

‘Don’t cling on to a mistake just because you spent a long time making it.’

James

Description:
No, you aren’t eating in a calorie deficit and not losing weight 🙄

I make many posts talking about why calories in vs calories out (CICO) & why it matters, so let’s talk about why people THINK they are eating in a calorie deficit & not losing weight🤔

First, CICO is what is. Conservation of energy is a FUNDAMENTAL LAW of nature/physics. If you aren’t losing weight (over the LONG TERM, not talking short term fluid fluctuations) that means you aren’t in a calorie deficit. If you believe you should be that means you are either taking in more calories than you think or expending less energy than you think, or both. Swipe right 👉🏼

1st let’s talk calories in. Research shows that in people who claim they eat low kcal (~1200/d) & couldn’t lose weight were actually underestimating their intake by 50%! They also overestimate their activity by 50% as well! 😱 This can feel very attacking to people but check out my 2nd slide. I’m not saying people are lying. People are just really shit at estimating & also forget to account for foods that they think don’t matter. But these untracked or incorrectly tracked foods can wind up as hundreds of kcal/d if not MORE. If you think you are on low kcal not losing weight, try weighing & tracking every single thing you put in your mouth for 2 weeks. You’ll be shocked

3rd slide is from my book, Fat Loss Forever & is those who are weekend over eaters. Sorry guys, calories still matter on the weekend 🤷🏼‍♂️. Not saying you can’t have higher calorie days on fat loss so long as you budget for them, you can but you must understand how it affects your weekly calorie budget. This is why we created the calorie planner feature in @carbondietcoach to make it easy to map out your weekly intake. This doesn’t even touch on the fact many people drink on the weekend & don’t track the kcal from alcohol which itself has 7 kcal/g & 5 drinks can EASILY rack up 800+ kcal you didn’t account for

Finally, many people claim they burn thousands of calories per day in activity based on their activity monitors, but these devices have been shown to overestimate energy expenditure by 30-93%! Just because your watch says you burned it don't mean shit!

Yesterday someone asked in my Q&A, “do you really never miss having a 6-pack?”
.
No.
.
Not at all.
.
I’ll tell you why.
.
Maintaining that level of leanness was purely for my ego.
.
➡️ I didn’t perform better when I had a six pack.
.
➡️ I didn’t feel better when I had a six pack.
.
➡️ I didn’t have more energy when I had a six pack.
.
➡️ I wasn’t healthier when I had a six pack.
.
I had to be way more strict with my nutrition.
.
I was, ironically, more self conscious and critical of my physique.
.
And the sole purpose of maintaining such a low level of body fat was to feed my ego when I took my shirt off in public or shared pics on IG.
.
I’m not gonna say that’s the “wrong” way to live.
.
But I am gonna say that’s no longer what I value and definitely not how I choose to live anymore.
.
Fuck. My. Ego.
.
And fuck anyone who gives a shit if I’m 8% body fat or 15% body fat.
.
No, I don’t miss being that lean.
.
At all.
.
Because I’m much happier with a slightly higher body fat percentage, significantly more energy, more pizza, more fun out with friends, and less feeding my ego over shit that, candidly, doesn’t fucking matter.
.
So, yeah.
.
That’s why I don’t miss having a 6-pack.
.
.
.
.

Stop.

Seriously.

Stop trying to lose a quick 10lbs three days before Joe Fuckstick’s annual weenie roast.

Stop creating and forcing yourself into arbitrary deadlines by which you convince yourself you “need” to lose x amount of weight.

Stop putting so much pressure on yourself to lose an obscene amount of weight as quickly as possible.

Stop perpetuating this false idea that makes it seem like you need to lose it now or never.

It’s not “now or never.”

It’s not a “one and done” process.

It takes time.

A lot of time.

This is a “forever” kind of thing.

And the more you try to speed things up or lose weight faster or take magical fat burning pills or invest in motherfucking Fit Tea for fucks sake...the further you drive yourself away from reaching your goal.

Listen.

It’s not sexy or marketable or fun or easy...but it’s the truth.

This. Game. Is. Forever.

It never ends.

You will get better at it. It will get easier. You will get to a point where you don’t have to consciously think about it all the time.

But when it’s all said and done, this game never ends.

So enjoy it. Invest in the process. Give yourself the best opportunity to succeed.

And remember...if you aren’t having fun, what’s the point?

Description:
People say dieting doesn’t work. 

Well it worked for me, about ten years ago I decided to sort my life out now do the same for tens of thousands of people a year. 

I didn’t gain it all back.
I didn’t have a poor relationship with food.
I feel better at 31 than I did at 21.

Health is your responsibility and people need to step up. Not everyone has equal access to health as others, sure. 

But blanket prescribing ‘dieting doesn’t work’ is like saying no one should ever do anal because someone had a bad experience. 

Maybe I’m bias because “diet culture” was the best fucking thing that ever happened to me. 

Maybe I’m bias because I meet people and hug people who have changed their identity and daily habits after periods of dieting and training.

Maybe I’m bias because I love my life way more with weights and moderation in the middle of it. 

Diets do work, if you work with them. 

If you don’t do the work required, I can see as to why you may have a different conclusion to I do. 

I’ll give you the same advice I would to any objective in life; don’t be fucking daft. 

Also, Fuck keto. 
James

I’ve seen some madness in my time over zero calorie drinks.

“But James, you always see obese people drinking diet coke, what do you make of that?”

Association is not causation. 

Diet drinks are a great part of a fat loss strategy. But before you say “not as good as water.” 

Shut the fuck up for a minute and realise familiarity is a big player in adherence and sustainability. 

“Swaps” within someone’s existing diet is a strategy I’ve used with clients for years. Too many coaches sell their own diet to their clients. 

They wonder why the wheels fall off a couple weeks in when the client can’t even look at a plain chicken breast let alone broccoli. 🥦

People say dumb shit, remember, you can still be a fucking moron with a 6pac.

Low calorie alternatives are harmless and play a fantastic part in calorie reductions when striving for a calorie deficit. 

The end.

Description:
10km Breakfast 🔱 Slow, steady, aerobic and impeccably paced as per the teachings of #TheArtOfResilience (see link in bio for YOUR copy) since, “The brain (and body) craves consistency and sustainability. 

As a result, pacing was so important to every day, tide and swim. It’s (again) related to homeostasis and the Psychobiological Model of Fatigue, but scientists believe the brain monitors cardiac integrity through myriad factors including heart rate.

They go on to say maintaining a consistent heart rate during race performance is critical in keeping the Psychobiological Model of Fatigue in balance. A heart rate that is too high, too early and for too long will signal to the brain the pace is unsustainable and we should shut down. This is why every swim would only start once I was happy to settle into a rhythmic style of swimming that consisted of a stroke rate you could set your watch to”🐳

It still amazes me realizing what our bodies are capable of... ⁣
⁣
I owe this amazement to something called NSV.⁣
⁣
When you learn how to acknowledge NSV, you can improve your confidence and quality of life exponentially. So, take notes and let this sink in!⁣
⁣
NSV is a little abbreviation for something called a Non-Scale Victory. ⁣
⁣
These are victories in health, fitness, and life that have NOTHING to do with body weight.⁣
⁣
It’s easy to get caught up in measures that are seemingly quantifiable (like your weight on the scale) because it’s specific and measurable.⁣
⁣
However...⁣
✔️What is specific doesn’t always see context.⁣
👉Will a certain number actually = more happiness, confidence, and the desired look? Not necessarily and probably not. You are more than a number.⁣
⁣
⁣
✔️What is measurable doesn’t always read accurately. ⁣
👉Just because the scale goes up or doesn’t move, doesn’t mean you aren’t making progress. It could be temporary water retention or more sweet, sweet muscle!⁣
⁣
💡It’s important to open up the mindset into a world that sees context, understands nuance, and builds a strong, flexible foundation. ⁣
⁣
Goal setting is great, but also understanding goals from a more holistic perspective will make ALL the difference.⁣
⁣
💕That’s why I love NSV. Every time I can do one heavier rep, finish a workout a little faster, eat pizza without guilt or shame, give someone encouragement in their own journey... I know that I am making myself a little bit better than I was yesterday.⁣
⁣
We are unique, strong, and special for so many reasons outside of how our bodies look and the weight of our gravitational pull.⁣
⁣
It’s important to see and celebrate everything that we accomplish.⁣
⁣
There are so many types of Non-Scale Victories to be celebrated. Nothing is to small or insignificant. Celebrate every victory because you are worth it!⁣
⁣
💛What are some NSV for you? Comment below!👇⁣
#thedailykelsey⁣

Sorry but resistance training > pretty much everything 🤷🏼‍♂️

I’ve got a PhD in nutrition. I LOVE nutrition. I, like many others thought for a long time that nutrition was the most important factor for building muscle & overall health

WRONG

Try to build muscle just with nutrition & let me know how that goes. You can add very modest amounts of lean body mass through nutrition & only by adding body weight typically.

If you’ve never resistance trained you can add muscle & lose fat while doing nothing else. Nutrition can’t do that

And yet, I can’t tell you how many people I see online who want to pick apart every nuance with nutrition but do not even resistance train or exercise. 🤦🏼‍♂️. Stepping over dollars to pick up pennies

I’m not saying they are mutually exclusive. They aren’t. They work best together. But resistance training is amazing for

-Building muscle
-Improving strength
-Preventing sarcopenia
-Decreases cancer risk
-Decreases CVD risk
-Increases bone mineral density
-Decreases risk of several other diseases
-Muscle mass is also a predictor of mortality after age 65, people with more muscle live longer
-May have cognitive benefits

It ain’t just for meatheads and vain people. It’s for overall health too. It’s one of the best, if not the best thing you can do for your health

Newsflash: sugar is not fattening independent of calories. 🤷🏼‍♂️

That’s right, I said it. Evidence for this comes from several meta-analysis showing zero difference in fat loss or gain when calories are equated between low sugar and high sugar diets.

In fact Surwit et al 2001 demonstrated in a tightly controlled multi month randomized controlled trial that sugar didn’t make one iota ie difference in fat loss. They had 2 groups: one low sugar (~10g/d) and another at over 100g per day. Same macros. Same calories. 

Know what they found? BOTH groups LOST ALMOST THE EXACT SAME AMOUNT OF FAT 🤷🏼‍♂️. 

Not only that but both groups had nearly identical improvements in markers of health (blood lipids, glucose, blood pressure). The only thing that improved more in the low sugar group was LDL cholesterol which improved slightly more on the low sugar group. Likely due to the low sugar group eating significantly more fiber, but the difference was quite small in LDL reduction. 

Now I don’t think eating a ton of sugar is a great idea for fat loss because sugar is not very satiating and some people have a hard time limiting it.

Further, there is no evidence for sugar addiction in humans (please see scientific review paper of the same title). Foods that fit the definition of causing ‘food dependence’ have high sugar AND fat AND are usually ultra processed. Sugar alone does not rank high on the food dependence scale. In fact of single(ish) macronutrient foods, foods high in fat like nuts & seeds rank much higher than sugar alone 🤷🏼‍♂️

Long story short: sugar doesn’t make you fat in absence of over consuming total calories. 

Facts > Feelings

Ketogenic diet (KD) for high intensity exercise or resistance training?🤔

When the KD began gaining popularity years ago, besides all the magical diet claims that circulated the internet, many folks also postulated that exercise performance could be improved due to people being ‘fat adapted.’

So what does the research say? When it comes to ultra endurance work & endurance work at lower intensities, the KD does not seem to impair performance, but also doesn’t seem to enhance it, with no differences at 60% of VO2 Max but significant decreases in time to exhaustion (TTE) at 70% of VO2 Max on the KD (Shaw et al 2019)

This makes sense because we know that higher intensity exercise relies more on carbohydrate (CHO) oxidation & in the case of anaerobic exercise like strength training & high intensity exercise, CHO MUST be used as fatty acid metabolism requires oxygen

When it comes to resistance training & gaining LBM, there are only a few studies examining this. The two best are from Vargas et al (2019 & 2020) comparing protein matched KD vs non ketogenic diets (NKD) & looking at body composition & strength outcomes after several months. In both studies, the KD group gained less LBM than the NKD groups (was only statistically significant in 2019 study) & in the 2020 study the subjects increases in strength on the squat & bench press were significantly impaired by the KD (swipe for a figure from the 2020 study) 👉🏼

Burke et al 2017 found that a KD impaired exercise performance in competitive race walkers. Even though fatty acid oxidation was significantly enhanced by the KD diet, it also increased the oxygen cost of exercise. Makes sense because they were at 90% of VO2 Max

Zinn et al showed performance reductions in endurance athletes following a KD despite increased fat oxidation & improvements in body composition. Athletes subjectedly reported more fatigue initially, but even after reporting their energy had returned, their mean TTE was reduced by ~2 minutes from the KD

What does it mean? It means that if strength or speed is your goal, a KD diet is likely suboptimal. You can get stronger & faster on one, but likely not as much as a diet that contains CHO

Description:
Suicide takes more lives than sharks by THOUSANDFOLDS in Australia and outside of it. 

It’s mad how people worry about sharks and spiders yet work jobs that don’t fulfil them, live a life without meaning and endure huge amounts of stress on a daily basis.

Rather than worrying about the water you swim in, worry about the environment you exist in. You wouldn’t put a plant in the shade and neglect watering it if you cared about it. 

Sleep well, be active, don’t engage in activities that negate your mental wellbeing for a short hit of pleasure. 

Be selfish when you need to be, share how you’re feeling with close friends and do what’s right for you - not what everyone else seems to be doing. 

Mad how you’d be worried in a statistically safe place (the sea) where drowning is more of a threat than sharks. 

Your biggest fears should be constructing a life you don’t love living. It’s never too late to change who you are or what you want to do each day. 

Let sharks live. 😂

You should be worried about your daily actions and habits more than an apex predator lurking in the sea. 

Change my mind. ❤️🦈
Image Text: Ask me a questior Scared of sharks more living in Aus? Nah. Either way you're way more likely to commit suicide than get eaten by a shark. I think it's important we protect our mental health rather than avoid swimming in the sea.

There’s a logical fallacy among muggles that leads them to believe if they can’t do a big, hairy, hour-long workout that’s wicked intense and makes you sweat like a One Eyed Hippogriff, it’s not worth working out at all.
.
Codswallop.
.
Something is better than nothing.
.
I don’t care if it’s a 10sec hamstring stretch, 5min hop scotch or a quickie naked partner hip thrust.
.
Something is better than nothing.
.
And more often than not, doing one small thing is enough to keep your motivation going so you keep crushing it tomorrow rather than falling off track altogether.
.
Don’t give yourself an excuse to quit.
.
It’s not worth it and you’ll never look back and be happy you gave yourself the easy way out.
.
You will, however, look back and always be glad you held yourself to your own highest standard and did something rather than nothing.
.
.
.
.

I’d ask you how you are but you’d probs say fine on auto pilot & we won’t have even got anywhere close to cracking the shell of that monkey nut. Let me give you my nutty take on this. Life = a constant blending of nut butters. It’s loud. It’s fast paced. As a result of the noise it’s very easy to miss your blender amongst the others. Especially as we are all trying so hard to keep up to speed with the others. What we don’t realise is that if we were to turn ours off, readjust the nuts that go into the mix, we’d most definitely be overall more efficient in the long run. Less cloggy. We forget to stop to question what we are putting in & end up settling with whatever the output. Why are we keeping in those nuts that are way too far gone to call a ‘deep roast’ & are actually sitting there, bitter & stale confusing the flavours we actually like & work for *us*. Why aren’t we spending more time on getting the consistency correct if smooth is what we personally like? Yeah, you get to the crunchy faster, but what’s the point if that’s not what *you* like. I was going to de-nut-afy everything I just typed but I shan’t. I’m going to leave it here. Actually that’s outrageous. Fine...
Ps. Don’t forget to check in with yourself & question things. All the things. Your mood. Your crowd. Your thoughts. Goals. Passions. Things that piss you off. Everything, don’t keep things bottled up.....(in a jar?)
Pps. & spread good vibes as thick as peanut butter 😚 #staynutty #amood #humpday

NONE of these diets boost metabolism or cause magic fat-loss 🙅🏻‍♂️⁣
⁣
Diets only cause weight loss when they cause you to eat less calories than you expend… these diets just cause people to eat less 😱⁣
⁣
Keto: This diet causes you to eat less by removing a whole macronutrient from your diet 🥓🥩⁣
⁣
Paleo: This diet causes you to eat less by restricting you to eat wholesome, nutrient-dense foods that are highly satiating 🍠🍖⁣
⁣
Intermittent Fasting: This diet causes you to eat less by giving you less time to eat throughout the day ⏳🥙⁣
⁣
Zone: This diet causes you to eat less because it consists of a large amount of vegetables and low calorie fruits 🥗🍎⁣
⁣
Detoxes, Lunar (yes this is actually a thing), Alkaline, Blood Type: Nope. Just no. Don’t fall for these diets, they’re just straight up nonsense with no evidence to support them ⛔️🤦🏻‍♂️⁣
⁣
None of these diets boost metabolism or cause anything magic. Once again, diets only work when they cause you eat less calories. 👌👏⁣ Choose the dietary strategy that’s easiest for YOU to adhere to & be consistent with!

This is why our app @carbondietcoach (link in bio) does not advocate for any one particular dietary strategy but rather gives you a full spectrum of options to choose from so that you can choose the one that maximizes your adherence 🔥

References: Alhassan et al. (2008). Dietary adherence and weight loss success among overweight women: results from the A TO Z weight loss study. International journal of obesity (2005), 32(6), 985–991.⁣

Tinsley et al. (2017). Time-restricted feeding in young men performing resistance training: A randomized controlled trial. European Journal of Sport Science, 17(2), 200-207
Image Text: Why Do Diets Work? BIOLAYNE Keto: Reduces your calories by removing a whole macronutrient Paleo: Reduces your calories by causing you to focus on nutrient-rich, satiating foods Intermittent Fasting: Reduces your calories by giving you less time to eat Zone: Reduces your calories by filling you up with vegetables and low-calorie fruits Detoxes, Lunar, Alkaline, Blood Type: Nope. These are plain nonsense Diets work by reducing your caloric intake. None of these boost metabolism or causes magic!

I first saw this motivational quote on Pinterest when I was really getting into my fitness journey. ⁣
I believed it.⁣
I said it. ⁣
I did it.⁣
⁣
When I was slipping into my disordered relationship with exercise this is the kind of quote that re-enforced the guilt I had for rest days and the belief I had that what I was doing was really good for me. ⁣
I was just being healthy.⁣
I was just being dedicated. ⁣
⁣
But when those workouts cause injury, pro-long illness and cause anxiety around rest days...are they healthy? Are they the best thing for you? ⁣
⁣
Probably not. ⁣
⁣
So whilst on the surface this may seem a harmless fitspo phrase, I needed to unpack this and explain why it’s subtle message to always override your bodies cues to exercise isn’t helpful. ⁣
⁣
In extreme cases it’s harmful. ⁣
⁣
ALWAYS trust your body, listen to it, and work with it. ⁣
⁣
#TrainHappy #Intuitivemovement #motivation #fitspo #fitnessmotivation #restday #fitness #listentoyourbody #mentalhealth

Title: Are Calories All The Same?
Description:
“YoU tHiNk ThAt CaLoRiEs ArE aLL tHaT mAtTer”

Where the actual fuck did this come from?

I will tell you where, some people create this straw man argument that talking about calorie balance means you disregard everything else. It is dumb.

I have been accused of “ignoring food quality” despite the fact that I frequently tell people that prioritising unprocessed and nutrient-dense foods is a good idea, if they have the ability to do so.

I have been accused of “ignoring hormones” despite discussing various hormones at length, like leptin (my refeed and diet break video), testosterone (video on anabolic steroids) or insulin (low-carb videos).

Saying “you lose weight if you are in a calorie deficit” is not the same fucking thing as pretending that nothing else matters.

I am surprised I need to explain this lol.

Gyms are open again in England, and you know what that means.

After months of being away, this is possibly the biggest international chest day ever. Queues to the bench press that rival those of even the most popular theme parks.

Some tips for getting back into the gym:
- If you start slow it is easy to ramp up the individual workout volume. If you only perform a fraction of what you used to and feel fine in the following days, you have a foundation you can build on. If you do too much and are too sore to easily brush your hair or sit down for a shit, you have self sabotaged the next few days of exercise.
- You don’t even have to do the same workout split. A few fully body sessions to ease in may be more beneficial than going straight into a massive chest or leg day.
- Higher reps are legit. If you are out of practice on an exercise, you may feel like you need to relearn the movement again. If you haven’t played golf for a few months your swing might feel a little rusty, likewise if you go straight into heavy bench, you may shake like an electric toothbrush.
- You will be weaker, which is normal. When I was first ill and off the gym for months I went from a 500lb deadlift to not being able to lift a 25lb bar from the floor. Feeling weaker can suck, try and lean into it and embrace it. Making yourself feel shit probably won’t help anything.
- Making progress hinges on psychology. If there is something you can do that makes exercise more fun, do it. Lifting with friends can help if you are a social butterfly, or when the gym is quiet if that’s your thing. Recording your workouts so you can see when you are making progress can be helpful for some people. Give yourself leeway on exercise selection so you aren’t trying to follow a plan you hate. In the same way that good dietary habits you adopt consistently will beat great ones that you do inconsistently, adherence is always going to be a bottleneck for everyone apart from the super hardcore exercise enthusiasts who wouldn’t even miss a workout if the apocalypse was coming that day.
- If soreness was a reliable indicator of muscle growth, running a marathon would be anabolic as fuck. Chase progress, not soreness.
Image Text: Ben Carpenter @bdccarpenter Ifa a gym bro has been out of the gym for months, IS finally allowed to train again and can pick any workout for their first session back... ...how many warm up sets do they take before they attempt a one rep max bench press?

Description: 1 DAY 🤩 Until gyms open in England (image of me trying to remember how to use it, haha 😂) Jokes aside, looking forward to (properly) strength training again since it’s a key component of “getting wintered” I’ve missed. Taken from #TheArtOfResilience (see link in bio for your copy) “Strength underpins everything we do and it is the accumulation of strength over a period of time that allows all of our body’s structures to adapt and make us less prone to injury and more able to deal with the stresses and strains that we place upon it. Whether that be bones, muscles, joints, ligaments or tendons. All of these structures have the ability to adapt to the forces that are placed upon them. If we load too quickly we get injured - that load could come in many forms but in simple terms if we have not accustomed our body and its structures to the loads that we intend to place on it then we will almost certainly pick up some form of injury. On the other hand, if we increase the load gradually over time and expose our body and its structures to ever increasing loads while incorporating some rest and recovery time (that allows the body to adapt further) then we become stronger and more resilient” #Gymshark 🔱

You may be born with a height advantage in your sport / genetics, but outside of that you’re born with no talent or abilities. 

We see what we consider “natural” abilities in comedians for being so funny, but we ignore the hundreds of shows memorising the same order of jokes for years.

I was flattered to be called “a natural speaker” but I’m not. I’m just not afraid to get on stage and because of that I’ve become an experienced speaker, not a natural. 

We have a human tendency to connect people’s dots for them as to how they are doing so well, I’m here to remind you that more often than not it’s usually quite simply repetition. 

I’ve come to realise that life isn’t always easy and you’re often faced with two directions in which to go: 

- become more competent, adapt, overcome, grow, be audacious and better your knowledge and abilities however you can. 

- or to complain, those of you that complain are merely doing so because you’re not competent enough yet and you’d rather whinge and moan than face the daunting task of having to develop yourself. 

It’s the world’s fault, you shouldn’t have to change for it, right?

The truth is; complaining doesn’t often ever change anything in life. It rarely works. 

So realise you have the same opportunity as anyone else when it comes to talent, if they’re better than you they’ve probably repeated it more than you have. That’s it. 

Do whatever you can to become more competent over time, hit your reps, even the ugly ones, then one day you may hear someone say you’re “a natural talent.”

Mad that.
Image Text: THERE IS NO SUCH THING AS NATURAL TALENT. WE'RE ALL BORN WITH ZERO ABILITIES. YOU EITHER BECOME COMPETENT OR YOU SPEND YOUR LIFE COMPLAINING INSTEAD. Jam Smith James

Description:
I put this comparison up on my story last week and it was crazy the response I got. Some shocked, others relieved! 
.
So many women STILL do not realise that social media is only a snippet of someone’s reality. A split second glance into their life that they choose for you to see. 
I feel so passionate about speaking out and showing others that you can still be healthy, strong and fit even with characteristics that you or others call flaws. 
It’s no wonder women or younger girls feel insecure about their appearances when 90% of what they see on here are perfectly posed bodies with the best angles, lighting and editing. 
.
So here’s me at a photoshoot. One of me showing off my physique with tensed muscles and a top fitness photographer snapping away. The other of me standing how I would normally, relaxed and thinking about the massive burger I was getting afterwards!
.
Of course, I love to flex, I love to show off my muscle I’ve worked SO damn hard for, I love to look glamorous and feel sexy. There is absolutely nothing wrong with that. 
BUT,
We also all need to recognise that our bodies will not always look like this and THAT IS NORMAL! You should never feel ashamed or be embarrassed. 
Cellulite, stretch marks, skin folds, wrinkles, spots... you name it. Most of us have it. Me included! 
.
So please, remember this the next time you feel down about your body. YOU ARE A QUEEN 👑
You’re beautiful inside and out! 
You’re unique and YOU ARE YOU! 
Be kind to yourself always.
.
REAL GIRLS AREN’T PERFECT!
PERFECT GIRLS AREN’T REAL! 👏🏻

If you ever feel like you “ruined” all your progress because you ate like an asshole or skipped a few workouts...pay attention.
.
2015 was the height of my Powerlifting career.
.
Everything I did was focused on improving my strength, performance & physique.
.
My training was on point. My nutrition was dialed. My sleep was incredible.
.
My life was structured around my fitness. It was not balanced. It was not a lifestyle. It was a mission.
.
Fast forward to 2018 and I was in the middle of my 3-year deal coaching @garyvee 7x/week for 3 years straight.
.
My focus shifted from my fitness to my business.
.
I ate like shit. I barely worked out. I hardly slept. I was traveling all over the world and spent more time in airports & hotels than I did in my own apartment.
.
I don’t regret it. It changed my life for the better. But it was not balanced. It was not healthy. It was a mission.
.
Fast forward another 3 years to 2021 and my health and fitness are arguably the best they’ve ever been.
.
I’m no where near breaking any powerlifting records. And I certainly don’t have the most successful business in the world.
.
But I’m happy. I’m healthy. And I have much more balance.
.
Most important, even though I took, literally, 3 years away from focusing on my own health & fitness...
.
Even though I pulled all nighters every week...
.
Even though my nutrition and training went to shit for 3 years straight...
.
I didn’t “ruin” my progress.
.
I didn’t fuck anything up.
.
Because when I was finally ready to get back to focusing on myself...I just started.
.
I didn’t dwell on what I did wrong.
.
I focused on what I could now do right.
.
Same goes for you.
.
Quit focusing on the past. Stop worrying about what’s already been done.
.
Focus on now.
.
Focus on what you can do...what you can control...what actions you can take.
.
And do it.
.
Now.
.
Don’t wait.
.
And don’t quit.
.
Because you will never fail as long you don’t give up.
.
#fitness #fitnessmotivation #health #healthy #healthyfood #healthyeating #powerlifting #strengthtraining #weightlifting

Paige Hathaway back with more BS nonsense 🤮

Paige claims a session of cryotherapy burns 300-700 calories 👉🏼👉🏼👉🏼

I would tag her but I’m blocked 😑. In a recent post, Paige claimed that 2-3 minutes of cryotherapy could burn up to 300-700 kcal! Swipe right to see claim 👉🏼👉🏼👉🏼

When people rightly called her on this absolute horseshit, she back tracked & claimed that this was over a 24 hour period of time due increased metabolic rate over that period from the cryotherapy (I believe she is a paid affiliate or has a financial stake in this business, someone please correct me if I’m mistaken).

How does her claim stack up to the scientific literature? Let’s have a look shall we? 😬

Lubkowska et al 2015 investigated the effect of several months of daily cryotherapy (3 min at -130 C) sessions combined with exercise on body weight, fat mass, & blood lipids. At the end of the experiment there was no difference in fat mass or body weight 🤷🏼‍♂️

In a shorter, more tightly controlled study, 12 pro tennis players received 2x per day cryotherapy for 3 min at -120 C for 5 days. The researchers saw NO DIFFERENCE in metabolic rate at any time point & no difference in amount of fat used as a metabolic substrate. A similar experiment in physically active men also saw the  same results, no increase in metabolic rate (Ziemann 2012, 2014) 🤷🏼‍♂️

A recent review of the literature concluded that cryotherapy “Does not affect the resting metabolic rate or energy expenditure during exercise.” (Lombardi et al 2017)

Sorry Paige, as per usual, you have no evidence to support your claim, instead you continue to peddle ‘hacks’ and ‘tricks’ to your audience, since REAL evidence based fitness advice isn’t sexy enough.

What’s even more disappointing is I previously spoke with her regarding her claims & even offered to help her if she had questions, that she could ask me before posting to make sure she didn’t make false claims. She never took me up on that offer

Fitness influencers beware, the days of being able to claim whatever you want without evidence are over. It will no longer be tolerate 🔥

Drinking in moderation won’t affect your goals 🍻⁣
⁣
Some groups of people say that alcohol has absolutely no place in the pursuit to gain muscle or lose fat. Other groups say that alcohol is incredibly good for you and is a must for improving cardiovascular health and inflammation… so which is right? 🤨⁣
⁣
Lets answer by discussing alcohol’s effect on weight loss, weight gain, energy intake and muscle 👇⁣
⁣
Weight Loss: Fletchner-Mors et al. (2004) placed two groups on a 1,500kcal weight loss diet. One group got 10% of calories from white wine and the other group got 10% of calories from grape juice. Subjects on both groups had similar weight decreases and similar decreases in body fat %, waist circumference, blood pressure, blood glucose, insulin, triglycerides, and cholesterol 🍾⁣
⁣
Weight Gain: A study by Cordain et al. (1997) placed participants in a 20-week cross-over trial. In one 10-week period, participants consumed 190ml of wine per day on 5 days per week. In the other 10-week period, participants did not consume alcohol. Calories were maintained the same in both parts of the trial. No weight changes were observed when participants consumed alcohol compared to when they remained abstinent. 🍷⁣
⁣
Calorie Intake: Caton et al. (2004) compared energy intake and hunger after 0, 1 and 4 units of alcohol. It was found that 4 units of alcohol increased energy intake and subjective hunger but 0 and 1 did not - showing there is a threshold where alcohol can increase appetite and food intake 🍔🍟⁣
⁣
Muscle: High intakes of alcohol can actually reduce muscle protein synthesis for a period of 12 hours. Specifically, it can blunt contraction-induced changes, which are the ones that we chase after in the gym (Steiner & Lang, 2014) 🤭⁣
⁣
Overall: Alcohol won’t cause you to gain weight or interfere with weight loss as long as calories are in check. If you decide to have multiple drinks, it may increase appetite and affect muscle protein synthesis. Thus, the most important thing about consuming alcohol is doing it in moderation. 1-2 drinks will be fine for most people but more may lead to the unwanted effects ⭐️⁣
⁣
References available upon request (too long to fit)

// FEELING LIKE A FRAUD // A little truth bomb for you all today and this is definitely not an easy one to share. I felt like a fraud this morning. My inner dialogue was running riot, telling me that I can’t be a good movement and meditation guide because I haven’t taken enough time for my personal practice over the last two weeks. Things have been busy which is fine, but I know it’s more than that. I was avoiding my practices. It felt pretty shitty. I got frustrated with myself, started to look at my body (always my personal go-to for self sabotage), taking out my sadness on my reflection, having moments where I thought I should quit what I love, feeling myself get deeper into this hole of not being enough.

I sat with it for about an hour and then decided to do something about it. I journaled the feelings, asked myself some pretty deep questions. I then got annoyed that I avoided the journaling mid-way through and found myself scrolling Instagram for 20 minutes. Sat with that frustration. Said out loud to myself “Compassion. Remember compassion.” And so I did. I came back to my journal, with a softer approach. I made a very small list of short term goals. To consciously breathe for 10 minutes, to move on my mat for 20-minutes, to dance to some of my favourites songs and to go for a walk on my own.

I have now ticked all of those things of my list and I feel so much better. I’m not saying that these doubts and these anxieties won’t come up again and that everything is solved, but sometimes all it takes are some baby steps, awareness, compassion and space.

I think it’s easy to look at social media and see someone with X number of followers and a successful business and assume they’ve got it all together. I think I speak for many business women out there when I say that we are only human. I know so many of you reading this no matter what industry you’re in, will have had thoughts like this. My advice to you always is to come back to compassion and use the tools that you’re familiar with to help cultivate a sense of calm in your soul. From there, you can unpack, unwind, go inwards, ask for space, ask for support, make goals. But mindfully.
Slowly.

Title: Is Obesity A Choice?
Description:
I have seen a lot of arguments about this on social media recently and to be honest, I think a lot of people are completely missing the point.

Weight loss as a process looks very simple on paper, “eat less, move more” and from a thermodynamic perspective, that is basically all there is to it.

A perhaps unfortunate byproduct of this is that because it looks simple on paper, a lot of people don’t realise the complexities involved. As such, we discuss people changing their body weight as a very straightforward “choice”, someone can choose to change their body weight or not, right?

But, by painting it as a very simple “choice” we run the risk of overlooking a metric fuckload of reasons why changing your body weight is much harder for some people than it is for others.

Let’s discuss some of them.
.
.
.

I used to run until I was dizzy. ⁣
⁣
My workouts took hours... Or they didn’t count. I thought MORE was BETTER.⁣
⁣
I thought eating fewer and fewer calories would help me reach my goal... Until I didn’t recognize myself.⁣
⁣
I cut out foods that I thought were “bad” until I didn’t have many options left to eat... And then spun even more out of control. ⁣
⁣
If I was tired, sore, injured, or hungry... It didn’t matter. I ignored the signs my body was giving me. ⁣
⁣
My body physically was shutting down, but my mind still thought, “Smaller. Smaller. Smaller.”⁣
⁣
Doctors. Treatment. Therapy. Practice. Grace.⁣
⁣
Over a decade later, I am a new person. ⁣
⁣
One big lesson learned is to shift the focus to building STRENGTH in workouts instead of working out to get smaller.⁣
⁣
The irony here is that a byproduct of strength training is all the things people typically are working out for... Muscle tone, fat loss, etc. but the shift to strength is transformational for both the body AND mind.⁣
⁣
💛Building strength allows you to accomplish things you never thought you could do. You not only can change how you look, but you gain confidence and are empowered by your body’s abilities.⁣
⁣
💡Shift your focus from trying to get smaller to building strength. It becomes about you getting to add to your life vs. what you have to take away.⁣
⁣
💛Let’s get STRONG.⁣
#thedailykelsey

I have said multiple times that there was no evidence that exogenous ketones would help fat loss in humans. Maybe they are better for appetite regulation (than a dextrose drink lol) and maybe ketogenic diets are good for appetite regulation (in some people, by no means are they the "best") but this should not be confused with *adding* exogenous ketones on top of your diet.

Well, as of yesterday there is a brand new paper that concluded ketone supplements did not alter body composition.

Three groups. 1) Ketogenic diet + placebo 2) ketogenic diet + ketones 3) low fat diet.

Yes, both ketogenic diets were low carb (<40g per day) and yes, they raised ketone levels (>1.0 mM capillary BHB).

No differences in body composition after six weeks but there was a trend for less nitrogen loss in the ketone supplement group which *maybe* might help retain more lean body mass over a longer period of time.

I like stacking the odds in my favour even more than your average obsessive gym bro but you know what, for the cost I think I am going to give that one a miss on the off chance it might maybe help out a little bit in the future.

And once again, when calories are controlled and protein is controlled, changing the ratio of carbs and fat in your diet appears to make very little difference to changes in body fat.

The authors conclude: "... short-term changes in body composition during caloric restriction are driven by caloric restriction more so than level of ketosis or macronutrient distribution.”

I’m saying your actions, habits and daily choices have a far greater impact on your success than your genetics.
.
Of course genetics matter.
.
Of course your genetics play a role in your progress.
.
Genetics play a significant role in, literally, everything you do.
.
But, by and large, genetics determine your ceiling for potential.
.
And while that obviously matters, most people never get anywhere close to their “genetic ceiling.”
.
Sure, you might not have the genetics to be a fitness model. I know I sure as shit don’t.
.
(And, candidly, i think that’s a good thing because most of the fitness models I know are obsessed with how they look every minute of every day and are more insecure than you could even begin to comprehend).
.
But just because you probably won’t be a fitness model doesn’t mean you can’t make progress.
.
It doesn’t mean you can’t lose fat, get stronger, build muscle and improve your health.
.
You can.
.
You absolutely can.
.
And no matter what cards you were dealt in the genetic lottery, when you stop using the “genetics card” as a justification to not try altogether, you’ll be amazed at just how much progress you can make.
.
.
.
.
.
#genetics #fitness #weightloss #nutrition #health #healthy #healthylifestyle #fitnessmotivation

have been accused of being a shill for sugar companies.

But for some reason, I am yet to receive any cheques from Big Haribo, which is very disappointing.

I am not "pro-sugar", I am just trying to bust some misinformation that causes people to have really unnecessary food paranoia.

Is "sugar" easy to overeat? Well, yes and no.

On it's own, it is sweet but when it isn't combined with any other flavours or ingredients, isn't actually very exciting. Not many people motorboat the bag of sugar they readily keep in their kitchen or drink maple syrup from the bottle.

But, it is often included in foods that are easy to overeat. When you think of "addictive" foods, it often appears, because the most "addictive" foods are highly processed and multi-ingredient.

But, unprocessed foods high in sugar, like fruits aren't normally considered addictive, right?

Also, some highly processed foods that we do consider addictive are low in sugar, but high in fat and salt like chips/crisps and fries/chips.

My biggest concern over demonising "sugar" without any further context is because there is an abundance of people who are paranoid of eating fruit, because they view it as "sugar".

If your criticism of food starts and stops with "sugar", foods like fruits which are higher in micronutrients, harder to overeat, rarely considered "addictive" and actually associated with *lower* body weights in observational research are tarnished with the same brush as ultra-processed, hyperpalatable, calorie dense, micronutrient sparse foods, and that is dumb.

There are very real conversations to be had about the amount of added sugars people consume, but there are also very real conversations to be had about how heavily we scrutinise sugar in isolation. People often look at things through a straw, they see a little piece of the puzzle but bigger picture.
.
.
.

This morning, I lost it. It felt as if Murphy’s law was in the works-everything that could go wrong did. My daughter has had a high fever for a couple of days now. We had an accident last night in the bed. My dog pooped in the house because it was raining. I spent 15 minutes looking for my son’s school shoes only to find them outside by the trampoline, soaking in the rain. Then I went to make my coffee and forgot to place my cup under the machine which lead to coffee seeping into all of my drawers.

I paused what I was doing, quietly went into my bedroom, sat on the bed, cried, and prayed. Being a single mama is tough. Especially when you don’t have family or a current significant other to help most days. I never knew it would be like this. But a little voice said, “mama, I’ll help you.” My daughter snuck into my room when she noticed I had walked away for a bit. I hugged and held her tight. That moment right then and there instantly made my morning better. God answered my prayer of needing a little motivation to get me through my morning.

I know this isnt my typical fitness post. But I know a lot of you are going through what I’m going through right now. I want to remind &  encourage you that it’s okay to pause and cry. Motherhood is hard enough. But single motherhood? The hardest. But also the most rewarding.

So I wiped my tears, walked strongly back into the kitchen with a towel and cleaned up the coffee with dignity and a smile. There’s no use in crying over spilled coffee! 🙂

I hope everyone has a wonderful day today. No matter how it started. Your attitude can greatly change the rest of your day if you allow it. 🖤

All the protein we eat is not used for building muscle😱

Ok, we eat a protein rich meal, what happens? Groen et al., demonstrated that after consuming 20g of protein, 40-50% of that protein is “first-pass cleared,” meaning that it’s used up by the gut & liver for local metabolism & protein synthesis & the other 50% made it into circulation. Only 11% of the total 20g protein bolus was used for muscle protein synthesis (MPS). That means that only a small percentage of what is consumed is actually used for building muscle💪🏻

So how much do we need per meal?
Well, this depends on age. Older adults develop “anabolic resistance” which means that its hard to turn on anabolic processes. Thus, older adults require more protein than younger adults to maximally stimulate MPS. Stokes et al., found that young adults (22 years) can maximize MPS with 0.24 g per kg of bodyweight in a single meal whereas that number is much higher for older adults (0.60 g/kg BW). Of course, these numbers are dependent on protein quality. Protein sources with more leucine (animal proteins like whey & egg) require less protein to maximize MPS whereas lower quality sources of protein like wheat (low in leucine) require quite a bit more total protein

These data are in resting adults though. Data from Witard et al., suggest that following exercise 40g has significant benefits over 20g.
I often hear people mention that “you can only absorb or digest about 30g of protein per meal,” but is simply not true. You absorb almost all of it, but only a small amount goes to MPS, but in order to maximize MPS it requires a DISPROPORTIONATE amount of protein compared to what is incorporated into muscle. Thus, consuming 30-40g of protein per meal every 3-5 hours should maximize MPS & muscle growth 💪🏻

Important to note that this data does not consider the effects on muscle protein breakdown (MPB) which could change things. However, due to methodological challenges in assessing MPB, relatively little is known about it. Still, the consensus of experts is that changes in MPB contribute little compared to MPS for facilitating changes in long term muscle mass

I bang on about this shit all the time because it matters. I could go on and on about how unhelpful labels like ’healthy’ and ‘unhealthy’ can be if you’re feeling pretty weird about food.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
I’ll try not to.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
But !!!!! I always find this logic here helps in the early stages of letting them go. Which is that our diets and eating habits aren’t the sum of one single food we ate on a sunny Monday afternoon at 5:05 pm.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
It’s the sum of *all* foods we enjoy within the context of a day, week, month, and year.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
Branding single foods as ‘good’ or ‘bad’ strips they away from all context and judges foods in isolation.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
Which is kinda pointless. As we don’t eat one individual food in isolation forever. We eat a whole variety :)))⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
We don’t expect each individual food to give us *everything* we need by themselves.
We don’t shit on apples for not having any protein and label them as ‘bad!!!!!’.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
So avoid shitting on chocolate and other less-nutrient dense things you wanna put in your mouth.⠀
⁠⠀⁠⠀
They taste pretty fucking great - and food that tastes great is a major contribution to our mental health. That adds a lovely and essential element to our diets. I’d say that’s pretty ‘healthy’ if you asked me 🤝🤝🤝🤝

CORE BAYBEE 🔥. I’ve never been a fan of dedicated core training. It’s not that I don’t think it’s valuable (although you are using your core a whole lot in compound and unilateral movements), it’s that I don’t really enjoy it and when I plan to tack it onto the end of my strength training days, I end up skipping it most times 😬.

As I’ve moved to a 3-day strength program (my own Building Blocks program 💁🏼‍♀️) I’ve been incorporating specific core work on 1-2 other days. Since I’m postpartum and still rebuilding my core strength, I know I need to dedicate more time to it than I used to (and prefer to 😝). It’s easy to find effective body weight core exercises that you can scale to increase or decrease the difficulty and they take less time than a full body workout so they’re more doable at home.

🔸Pike-ups to push-up with socks or sliders (push-up optional)
🔸Drop-set: bent legs
🔹Lateral pull-throughs from bear
🔸Rotating side plank (elevated optional)
🔸Superset: side plank pulses (elevated optional)
🔹Reptiles (feet elevated optional)
🔹Superset: Knees come forward
🔸Pallof press with small plate on the band (plate very optional)

The 🐻 pull-throughs are a staple exercise I’ve been using. You can increase or decrease the challenge to resist rotation when you pull the weight by using a heavier or lighter weight and placing it on something that offers more or less resistance when you pull. I’m using a 40 lb kettlebell and a small towel. You don’t *need* anything underneath but I like the floors less scratched and scuffed 😝.

I’ve modified the side plank exercises to make them elevated as they’re slightly easier this way and this is where my strength is at right now where I feel like I can control my core throughout the exercise but am still challenged. You can easily move to the floor if you want to make it harder.

The last one I got from my dear brother who uses it in his boxing training. Pallof presses are a great exercise without it but it’s a good way to increase the instability and make it more challenging.

Description:
BOOTY 🆚 QUADS exercises
Which is your favourite to train?
.
Whether you’re a booty babe, quad queen or both, these exercise videos will help you understand the engagement in the muscles you want to target. You will of course work your glutes, quads & hamstrings but with slight differences in movement, foot placement or stance... you can put more emphasis onto a particular muscle.
.
1️⃣ BACK & FRONT SQUATS 
To hit your quads more you want to have your feet pointing forwards with a closer stance. Adding heel elevation will increase range of motion and squat depth. 
Squatting with a wider stance and toes pointing outwards will put more emphasis on the glutes. Add a resistance band to further activate the muscles.
.
2️⃣ KNEELING SQUATS 
To target the glutes more with this movement you will need to hinge more at the hips and activate your glutes with each rep. With the increased bend at the knee, the hamstrings don’t work as hard and therefore the glutes take over.
With your knees narrower together and a greater bend at the knees, you will use your quads more. Notice how I lean back into the squat with no hip hinge.
.
3️⃣ FORWARD & REVERSE LUNGES
Forward lunges are a more challenging exercise, placing more emphasis on your quads due to the forward movement. Reverse lunges are easier to balance and better for your knees. They also activate the glutes more. 
.
4️⃣ BULGARIAN SPLIT SQUATS
To hit your quads more keep your front foot closer to the bench and use a slightly faster tempo keeping tension on the quad.
To hit the glutes more place your front foot further away from the bench and squeeze your glutes at the top of the rep with a slight pause.
.
Hope these tips were helpful! In my fitness programs I demonstrate the correct way to perform every exercise - It’s so important to get this right for maximum results! 
Remember that mind to muscle connection also plays a massive part 🧠💪🏻

Read to the end because this is important.
.
First...way too many people do things that are drastic and/or completely unsustainable (think juice cleanses, detox’s, keto, etc). The reason they do them is because they want to lose as much weight as humanly possible in the least amount of time. Which always sounds great but inevitably leads to rapid weight regain (usually more than they lost in the first place).
.
Second...people expect the scale to go down every day. Even when they logically know it won’t go down every day (or even every week), they let their emotions get the best of them and convince themselves things aren’t working when the scale doesn’t keep dropping. Even worse when the scale randomly spikes up. And, again, even though they know the scale will spike up for any number of reasons far beyond fat gain, they still freak the fuck out and use that as a justification to quit.
.
Third...as soon as they have one “bad” meal or a “treat” or dessert or, God forbid, take a vacation and enjoy themselves for a week, they think they fucked everything up. They think they ruined all of their progress and use that as a justification to binge and quit and throw in the towel.
.
These are just 3 of many many many many reasons why people fail.
.
But suffice to say, the answer to remedy these issues are very simple.
.
1) Don’t do something drastic or completely unsustainable. If the methods are unsustainable, your results will be unsustainable. Do something you enjoy and can sustain long-term.
.
2) Quit living and dying by the fucking scale. It’s just data.
.
3) You can’t fuck this up unless you quit altogether. So stop being such a fucking asshole to yourself and get back on track.
.
Happy Monday.
.

Three of my favourite glute-focused exercises - home and gym options! While these exercises focus a lot on the glutes, they don’t work them exclusively. Don’t be afraid to train your quads and hammies; it’s important to build well-rounded strength 👊🏻.
-
🍑 Back extensions (regular and glute-focused) and Banded reverse hypers:
Man do I ever miss having a back extension machine 🙈. These are great. The glute-focused ones might seem strange or potentially injurious to get into this position but you’re not loading your spine, just increasing your glutes contribution and reducing your erector’s involvement.
.
These usually go right near the end of my workout and I’ll use light weight (e.g. 50 lb dumbbell) or often just bodyweight with reps 25-30.
.
The banded reverse hypers are quite the set-up (I was so impressed the hip pad worked on the box 😝) but I like them as a sub. You can also use a couch and anything heavy to pin the band down, or stick with frog reverse hypers
-
🍑Front foot elevated split squats OR Barbell split squats:
Because people always ask, the difference vs a lunge is that the legs are stationary in a split squat. I feel more stable in a split squat because balance is less of a limiting factor and can therefore comfortably use more weight and execute with a little more control (which is great for muscle growth).
.
I prefer to take a wide stance and lean my torso forward to make it a little more hip dominant (less quad-focused) but both variations will work your glutes well.
.
I generally use reps in the 8-12 range with a relatively heavy (it’s always relative) weight.
-
🍑Single leg hip thrusts or Barbell hip thrusts:
These have a shorter range of motion than most exercises that work your glutes but they target them very effectively. This also means you can use a considerable amount of weight and get very strong with this exercise 💪🏻. Don’t underestimate single leg thrusts; even unweighted they’re challenging!
.
Make sure you’re getting to FULL hip extension (don’t sacrifice form for increased weight).
-
