EVERYDAY

I get messaged on insta or WhatsApp from mates asking if I purely train on TRX to build muscle. It's as if because there's zero steel or iron involved that it's almost incomprehensible.

The answer is 80% TRX, 15% Kettlebells, 5% Resistance Bands

The proof? It's all we have here at the TRX Studios, and it was the same at the last studio we operated at, and has my muscle mass decreased since COVID? It's increased. I train more.

You are what you regularly do. And thats the answer. Just train regularly and your body will adapt accordingly. 

If you run everyday, guess what? You're a runner and your body will make the adjustments you're asking of it. As long as you're not scoffing pizza everyday you'll lean up, your muscles will become smaller to accommodate the long distance demands and your heart and lungs will become stronger.

If you're a scaffolder and you lift 21ft poles everyday you're going to have strong arms, shoulders and core.

If you do yoga everyday you'll be extremely flexible with an affinity for pictures with sunsets behind you.

So if you TRX everyday, pushing, pulling, jumping, planking, twisting then your body will adapt to having a balanced strong phyqisue.

I adapt it and train slow tempo for time under tension and sometimes add Kettlebell supersets and resistance bands. Guess what? Gives me muscles.

So in answer to your question? Yes.

But thank you for asking.

Not eating until 1pm is A STRATEGY TO EAT LESS. That’s it. 

If you don’t need to utilise that strategy there’s nothing wrong with eating first thing. 

People go on about clarity from “fasting” when the truth is eating just makes you feel sluggish (thus the parasympathetic nervous system being named ‘rest and digest’)

If you’re fat it’s not a meal timing issue. It’s a calories in vs expended issue. 

If you’re struggling to build muscle it’s probably a training issue, a dietary issue but it’s not a meal timing issue. Yes more meals help but even IF you’d get 3x in before bed. 

People spout all kinds of shit about the anti-ageing effect of fasting but fuck me! 

The idea of skipping breakfast isn’t worth the extra ten years of life (even if the claims were true.) 

Pass me the pop tarts, the ultimate pre-workout.

Description:
Am I on TRT (testosterone replacement therapy)?

NO

Been getting this question a lot recently. I guess because I’m 39 years old. I want to be clear: if you are living a healthy lifestyle & your testosterone is low I have zero issue with you getting TRT so long as you don’t compete in a drug tested organization that bans TRT. Go for it

Let’s talk about why I am not on TRT. Simple answer is: I don’t need it. Every time I’ve ever had my testosterone checked (with the exception of contest prep) I’ve been between 800-1100 🤷🏼‍♂️. I don’t need it

I have SO MANY PEOPLE talk to me about this who have NEVER ever had their testosterone measured. They just hit age 30 & assume they need it 🙄. I’m gonna say it: you are just looking for excuses to get on the sauce 🤷🏼‍♂️

If you want to get on gear go for it, but don’t justify you ‘need it’ because your test is ‘low’ when you never actually bothered to measure it. Also many of these people eat like crap, don’t train consistently, & sleep like shit. Is your testosterone really low because you hit age 30? Or is it because your lifestyle sucks?

People look at my testosterone results & say ‘lucky.’ 😑. You know what increases testosterone? Lifting hard AF consistently. Not eating like crap. Getting enough sleep. Not abusing drugs & alcohol. Having a healthy sex life. SHOCKER 🙄

I resistance training consistently. I eat well consistently using our app @carbondietcoach to coach me (link in bio) & you can see the results for yourself. I don’t always get great sleep but I shoot for it & usually get at least 7 hours. I also don’t abuse drugs & alcohol. I won’t comment on my sex life but hey, you’ve seen my wife 🤷🏼‍♂️ #testbooster

Now, if you are doing all those things & still feel like shit & your test is low & you decide to use TRT more power to ya. But many of you just want an excuse to justify juicing. If you want to juice, then go for it, but stop trying to validate it with the fact that you are over 30 🙄

Further, I compete in @usapowerlifting which does not allow TRT & like I said, I don’t need it anyway. But more importantly, I PERSONALLY wouldn’t feel right selling you guys products when I’m on the juice 🤷🏼‍♂️

THE SWITCH

Everyone who's ever lost weight and kept it off has had to make "the switch."

And if you want to get results that last, you will too.

The switch I'm referring to is a mental shift from seeing weight loss as a short-term fix to seeing it as the start of a new way of being.

Because regardless of how much weight you have to lose right now, you're going to be spending a far more significant percentage of your life maintaining those results. 

That's the goal, anyway.

And the only happen by making "the switch."

~

You know it too.

You know that you can't lose weight and go back to living the way you did before.

Yet still, you'll find yourself slipping into the trap of being allured by the newest & shiniest thing that promising "fast" results with zero regard to what happens once you reach your goal weight. 

(Cognitive dissonance at its finest.) 😉

But it's not your fault.

Most of what you've seen and heard about losing weight comes from marketers who are making riches from exploiting your pain.

They care more about your transaction than your transformation.

That’s why making "the switch" is freaking tough.

But you can make it easier by doing these two things:

1) Eliminating the "due date" you have for your goals.

2) Erasing pre-conceived beliefs and expectations you have about how quickly you should see results.

Your time-based expectations create unnecessary pressure.

And that unnecessary pressure pushes you towards unsustainable diets and exercise regimens.

It's also what makes you see slip-ups and mistakes as failures rather than opportunities to learn and grow.

When you don't have that unnecessary pressure, most of that goes away.

~

All that matters is that you keep showing up.

It might take you longer than you want.

It might even happen faster than you thought.

Either way, "the switch" will happen when you eliminate unnecessary pressure and put that energy into doing, learning, and growing into the best version of yourself.

– Carter
Image Text: Whether you have 5, 10, 50, or 100 pounds to lose, assume it's going to take at least a year. This way, you're less focused on how quickly you lose weight and more focused on building sustainable habits. Carter Good @CarterGood LFL COACHING LINK IN BIO

Go home Gary, you’re high

Sorry Gary, you are clinging to the carbohydrate insulin model of obesity (CIM) which has been debunked

The CIM basically states that people don’t get obese from overeating, they get obese from high insulin, regardless of calories, & that insulin traps fat in fat cells, making the rest of the body sense that it is starving & people overeat in response⁣. He claims that anyone who loses fat MUST do so by restricting carbs. He even said he would REFUSE to change his mind even if his own studies he funded showed otherwise (swipe to last video to hear it from his mouth)
⁣⁣
How does the CIM stack up against the evidence? I went through a thorough debunking in my book Fat Loss Forever (link in bio). Here is the synopsis. We have over 30 studies that compare various levels of carb vs fat with calories & protein held constant. If the CIM was correct we’d expect to see greater fat loss & in low carb diets (LCD) when kcal/pro are equal, but we don’t. In fact the studies show a small advantage to low fat diets for fat loss (Hall & Guo). Even up to carb intakes of over 300g per day vs keto, there was no superiority for a LCD⁣
⁣⁣
2nd, the idea that insulin traps fat in fat cells thus we can’t lose fat? Nope, T2D & obese people have HIGHER blood FFAs, TAGs, & glucose. In a study where they gave a drug that inhibits lipolysis (acipimox) people lost just as much fat as those who weren’t on the drug & they didn’t increase their food intake (Makimura et al)⁣
⁣⁣
More damning, the trials of the drug liraglutide, which is a GLP-1 mimetic that increases insulin. People given this drug actually LOSE fat 🤣 (Pi-Sunyer et al). If insulin was the most important thing for fat loss, how could you elevate it compared to controls & lose MORE fat? Answer: because it’s not the most important thing
⁣
Others will cherry pick a study from Ludwig et al that found a 400+ kcal/d ⬆️ in EE on a LCD. But 1) the method they used to measure EE tends to overestimate EE on a LCD (Hall et al) & they failed to show changes in BMR or activity, so where is this ⬆️ in EE coming from? Magic? 🤨⁣
⁣⁣
LCD can be a good way to lose fat. But they are NOT superior for fat loss

Account: K I M  F R E N C H 🇬🇧 NASM CPT
Description:
WRONG 🆚 RIGHT 
Lower body exercises to help you correct your form and make better progress 💪🏻
.
Never ever feel embarrassed if you have been performing any of these exercises incorrectly. I used too!!! And I’m not ashamed because it made me more determined to get it right. Remember failure is not the opposite of success, it’s part of success 🙌🏻
.
1️⃣ STRAIGHT LEG DEADLIFT 
This exercise can often get confused with a Romanian Deadlift where you purposely bend at the knees. Engage your lats and core before lowering the dumbbells down as far as you can until you feel the full stretch in your hamstrings. If you struggle to feel the engagement in your hamstrings, elevate your toes using plates which will give you a greater stretch.
.
2️⃣ GLUTE BRIDGE 
If your lower legs are too far forwards you will have less ROM (range of motion) and you will feel your hamstrings take over. To make the best out of this exercise it is so important to pause the rep and squeeze your glutes really hard whilst it is under tension. 
.
3️⃣ SIDE LUNGE 
When leaning forwards you are making the exercise easier by distributing your weight away from your lunging leg. Stand tall, engage your lats and keep looking forwards. This will really help you to keep good form throughout the exercise. Remember to always push through your heels to better activate your glutes. 
.
4️⃣ CABLE SIDE KICK 
If you are using your body for momentum then you are using a weight that is too heavy for you and as a consequence you are likely not working the correct muscles. Your leg should be the only body part moving in this exercise. 
.
Form should always come first 👌🏻
Hope you found this helpful!

Upper Body Workout - “push-heavy”💪🏻. I feel like it has been a long while since I’ve posted an exclusively upper body workout, so here’s one 😝!

I’ve been doing full-body workouts for a while now, which is a great way to train especially when you have a 3 day training frequency, but lower/upper splits are still my favourite. When I have dedicated upper body days I have a more push-heavy day and a more pull-heavy day.

This one uses bands and dumbbells so hopefully it’s doable for most at home who have some equipment 👊🏻

🔹Z-presses
🔹Drop-set: baby presses (very optional. She was smiling at me and I couldn’t resist)
🔹Push-ups (harder mod: weighted, easier mod: incline)
🔹Inverted rows
🔹Banded lat pulldowns
🔹ss banded tricep extensions
🔹Lateral raises
🔹ss bent-over rear delt raises
🔸I did 3-4 sets and kept reps between 10-15 (went within 1-2 reps of failure for most).

I’m incorporating the z-presses to not only work on overhead pressing strength but to simultaneously challenge my core. This exercise is naaat easy for your core and I’m still working on rebuilding and wanted the core challenge (and hopefully ending up stronger than before 👊🏻). If you don’t have the requisite shoulder or hamstring mobility to do this exercise and press directly overhead while seated up straight, elevate your butt or choose a seated variation.

For the inverted rows, you can use TRX straps, a very sturdy scarf in a door (pleeeaaassee make sure this is actually sturdy before you fall backwards), a very sturdy table (same note as the previous one), a power tower, EQ bars, bars at a park, or even a helpful human 😆. Back training is often neglected when training at home because it’s harder to do without weights and machines than pushing exercises are but it’s super important to incorporate. Do your pulls!

Happy Friday everyone! ☀️

Description:
When you are looking leaner while increasing calories on your reverse diet 😬😱

This is my 3rd week reverse dieting with our app @carbondietcoach (link in bio) after being at maintenance for 5 months post cut. I ended my maintenance phase around 3350 kcal/d & after 3 weeks of reversing the app has me up over 200 calories & I gotta say based on the previous weeks, I’m actually looking leaner 😬

How could this happen? Am I violating the laws of thermodynamics? Of course not. So what could explain me increasing my calories by over 200 but not gaining weight & actually looking slightly leaner? First thing is that by increasing my calories it’s possible I’m training harder & expending more calories during my sessions. I gotta say, I’ve been having some GREAT sessions. Further, we know that increasing calories can cause us to spontaneously move more without us realizing it, this increases our energy expenditure from non exercise activity thermogenesis (NEAT) which actually contributes quite a bit to our daily output. Finally, there is some evidence that increasing calories can also increase your basal metabolic rate (BMR)

That doesn’t mean you can pump up your calories & not expect to gain fat. In the case of reverse dieting, the idea is to slowly add them so that your adaptations for energy expenditure have a chance to keep pace with your increased energy intake. If I have in fact gotten leaner, which based on pictures, I think I have, then it means my energy expenditure is slightly outpacing my increase in calorie intake

Now this doesn’t happen forever, there will come a point at which I gain some body fat most likely. But I’m really enjoying this so far & looking forward to more calories & some crazy hard training

How many of you guys are using the app for reverse dieting & have experienced this yourself where Carbon has added calories during a reverse diet & you’ve gotten leaner? Leave a comment below or if you have questions, feel free to ask me ⬇️

ENJOY YOUR REST

So every PT/influencer writes about this at some point or another and they're right to.

I am the worst for driving myself into the ground and not resting adequately. I get so much more done than others in short spaces of time but then pay the price sometimes physically and then mentally.

When you rest, you heal, you recover, you recuperate.

Eric Thomas says "If you want to be successful, you gotta be willing to give up sleep. If you go to sleep, you might miss the opportunity to successful.”

I get the sentiment, he's talking about laziness and inactivity, but if you actually skip rest and sleep you're going to end up injured, stressed, and  operating on limited brain function. Success will just avoid you.

I find what really screws me up is the absolute inability to say no. Something I've written about it before. I let people access my time because I like to help but sometimes to the detriment of my own purpose. You end up getting to YOU last with little energy. It's tough to say no but when you're brave enough to do it, you get freedom.

It's a Bank Holiday today so I'll be relaxing and recovering so tomorrow I can fly all over again. What are YOU doing?

Niko

Lower Body Home Workout 🔥. This is from one of my soon-to-be-released plans and it’s a little bit “mean”, which is how I prefer my leg workouts 😝.

It’s important if you goal is to grow muscle, especially if you’re training at home and using less weight than you would in the gym, that you do your sets within a couple reps of failure. The last few reps should be slower and more challenging (but do your best to not let your form break). There’s nothing magical about 8-12 reps so if you’re approaching 12 reps for an exercise (and don’t have a heavier weight to use) and the reps are still looking as speedy as your first ones, do more reps to get closer to failure.

With that being said, no reps listed here. Go to where you’re challenged with the weights you have available. I did anywhere from 10-15 for most and then ~30 for the final superset.

🔸Banded lateral walks
🔸Bulgarian split squats
🔸Sumo squats
ss Kickstand RDLs
🔸Copenhagen plank
ss side lying hip raises
🔸Banded elevated glute bridges
ss Frog reverse hypers

Workshopping some new names for the banded lateral walks. I’m thinking “spare a square”? or “the roll is empty”. Maybe it’s just me who looks this ridiculous doing them.

If you haven’t tried Copenhagen planks, they are challenging. That’s the warning 😝. I’d suggest starting from your knee and if this is too easy, moving out so your foot is on the bench. You can also do lateral plate slides (put a plate on a towel and slide in from side to side) if you’d rather omit the Copenhagen planks.

Say “I get to” rather than “I have to.” This mindset shift has helped me throughout my mental & physical journey.⁣
⁣
Mindset is EVERYTHING! When you feel stuck, or you forget your WHY remind yourself that it is a privilege to work out! It is a privilege to eat healthy foods. It is privilege to work on yourself from the inside out 💕 have a beautiful day!

// REST IS BEST // 🤎 On Sundays we stay in bed for as long as possible wearing all of the cosy jumpers! 😊

Taking some time out today. Trying to restore my mind and body. Though I have a good work/life balance in many ways, when things get busy I tend to go into overdrive and fight with a feeling of guilt if I rest. At this point my body is clever enough to send me some signs that will MAKE me rest, cue cluster headaches, skin break outs, achy muscles and weakness. That’s what I’m vibing with today, so right now I’m back in bed writing this caption and I’m about to turn my phone off and read my book.

So here’s your reminder to listen to your body when it sends you these signs. It’s more intelligent and intuitive than you give it credit for. And if possible, try to become more aware of these times so that you can rest BEFORE your body tells you to. Observe how you feel, notice if your workload (or any stress in your life) has picked up, prioritise your well-being. Saying no and putting in some healthy boundaries is key. 

Ultimately we can only give love, kindness, creativity and our energy if we ourselves are rested, revitalised and restored. ❤️

And just as a little FYI, we’re going to be working with the theme of Boundaries in the coming months over at @mysoulsanctuary, so come and join the family. ✌🏼

Leg-heavy full-body workout 💪🏻. I slightly modified this one from my “Building Blocks” program and ouff 🔥

This one is fairly quick but tough. I knew I was in trouble when I was shaking after the first exercise 🙈. If you have some weights but no rack, B-stance squats are a great option and much more challenging than they may seem. Unilateral everything is more brutal than it has any right to be 😝

🔹B-stance squats - 4x8-10
🔹Barbell hip thrusts - 4x12-15
ss single leg hip thrusts - 4x12-15
🔹Barbell RDLs - 3x8-10
🔹Chest supported rows - 4x10-12
ss Prone Ys - 4x10-12
ss Push-ups - 4x8-10
🔹Banded lateral walks - 2x30
ss Banded kickbacks (with a missing vid. Sorry!) - 2x20
🔺ss = superset - exercises are performed back to back before resting. 

The barbell hip thrust to single leg hip thrust superset (more like a drop set) was bruutal 🔥. I’ve been messing around with more agonist supersets (same muscles worked back-to-back) for home training programs for when you don’t have access to heavy weights. They are crushing me…in a good way.

My training frequency is definitely down from a year ago with lockdown and having a baby but that means I can mess around with more techniques going to failure and not be as concerned about not recovering for my next session. Silver lining 😂.

Kick butt you guys 👊🏻

Kettlebell Conditioning 🔥

I truly miss feeling athletic and I know being stuck at home isn’t particularly conducive to crushing high intensity workouts (or feeling like doing much of anything active 😩). I’ve been doing more conditioning and cardio circuits because 1) the format makes it feel a lot more doable, 2) they’re time efficient (and baby), and 3) endorphins 👌🏻

Workouts like this won’t make you more “toned” or build “leaner muscle”🙅🏼‍♀️. Doing a combination of resistance training and cardiovascular training for health is super beneficial but if you’re looking to increase your strength and definition, don’t be afraid to do workouts that utilize heavier weights and longer rest periods. Those should be the foundation of your training 👊🏻

🔸RDL to goblet squat
🔸Kettlebell swings
🔸Shoulder-tap push-ups
🔸Kettlebell deadlifts (or burpees)
🔸Pull-throughs from bear
🔷Performed in a circuit, 30 seconds ON and 30 seconds rest between all exercises. Repeat 3-4x.

I used a 40 lb kettlebell but feel free to use more than one weight. If I had something slightly lighter I would definitely have added in an overhead movement, like overhead reverse lunges.

Even though I did them and am showing you them, I’d probably recommend against the kettlebell burpees and just do the quick deadlifts. I have seen people topple over on unsteady kettlebells and I personally only want to go face to floor when I’m doing a push-up 🥴. Be very careful and only attempt if you feel comfortable and have a kettlebell with a wide base.

Happy Monday everyone 😊

Put the snack down and ask yourself this:

Am I actually hungry?

Emptiness-in-my-belly hungry?

If not, all the mini Reese’s in the world won’t fix that feeling you’re feeling. See, food is incredible for fixing hunger. But it’s a poor substitute for connection, excitement, affection, rest, peace, order, adventure... legit anything that’s not hunger.

You’re not alone if you emotionally eat. More of the clients I’ve worked with than not once identified as emotional eaters. The good news is you can learn to manage emotion in non-food ways. It feels so good to honor how you’re actually feeling versus stuffing your emotions down with endless trips to the pantry.

This is something we’ll be tackling together in the Menopause Weight Loss Course. You have 3 more days to join. (Link’s in my bio)

Xx,
Kim

I don’t know when or if I’ll ever go back to a regimented program. It’s definitely what helped me out and gave me the building blocks and knowledge I have now. Everyone is looking for BALANCE, but what the f*ck is balance?! Personally, I think one can only derive at balance through rigidity. I am able to be where I am now only because I followed something and stuck to it, when That no longer served me I took what I learned and what worked and went on to another rigid routine. Because we are looking for the “one thing” that’s going to fix the problem, that’s going to change our lives. If there’s anything I’ve learned is that the “issue” never gets fixed, most of the time when you fix one thing it’s at the cost of another. If you don’t learn that what you see on the outside is only a reflection of your thoughts and habits then you will always be searching and no amount of anything will ever be enough. Balance is accepting the way things are NOW from everything you’ve learned because you’ve taken steps, steps forward, steps backwards and side steps here and there. You allowed those steps to take you to the next one, whether they led to the “right” place. I want everyone to understand that it doesn’t matter if you’re on the right path, the right path is only when you try to make the best decision for you, without judgment, without expectations. Balance is learning to let go and trust the isness of what is.

Firstly, you don’t need to lose weight to get fit. Attaining physical fitness, is far more reliant upon cultivating endurance (cardiovascular and muscular endurance), as well as strength, agility, mobility and coordination. ⁣
⁣
Unfortunately, because we are inundated with ‘slim’ bodies in the media we (understandably) make the assumption that a slim body is a fit body, and that a slim body is the only way to achieve a fit body. I also recognise that there are going to be elements of my page that perpetuate that message based on the fact that I am both slim and able-bodied. ⁣
⁣
SO - BEFORE I SHARE SOME TIPS: I want to reiterate (as I have done since I started this page) the gym/mat/training space is NOT the place for you to repent your ‘dietary sins’ because 1. There’s no such thing as a dietary sin 2. I encourage you to see training/exercise as an expression of appreciation for your body and it’s abilities. ⁣
⁣
To address this question properly however, is a non-exhaustive list of some suggestions I have to start out on a fitness journey:⁣
⁣
- Ignore the online HYPE - Increase your physical activity slowly but consistently. This might look like choosing to go for a 20 minute walk 3 times a week, increasing that frequency every 2-3 weeks if you feel ⁣
recovered (this is going to be VERY individual).⁣
⁣
- Split up your physical activity into morning and evening sessions - perhaps splitting up a podcast in between two walks so you’re motivated to do the second walk to get to the end of the podcast episode.⁣
⁣
- Track your weight - not the weight you lose, but the weight you lift. This is incredibly motivating and again removes you from the constant associations of exercise and fat loss.⁣
 ⁣
- Get adequate sleep this is often overlooked but it’s going to play a huge role in your mood, performance and recovery which in turn has the power to completely derail you. ⁣
⁣
⁣
SIDE NOTE: It’s true, that feeling of being out of breath is uncomfortable, but weirdly, you actually learn to love that feeling as you begin to associate it with the physical adaptations that will come from it.⁣
⁣
K what other suggestions do you y’all have for starting on a fitness journey?

This dumb shit again 🙄

People love their strawman arguments & false dichotomies. Just because flexible dieting gives you the freedom to eat some junk food doesn’t mean that’s all you can or should eat

That is like saying keeping a budget means all you can do is buy sports cars, lottery tickets, boats, gold watches, & platinum teeth 😆. Sure if you keep a budget you COULD buy any of those things if it fits in your budget, but it doesn’t mean that’s a good idea because it might mean you can’t pay your mortgage/rent, utilities, clothes, etc.

By the same token, if your caloric budget is 1500 per day & you decide to spend 900 of that on a big slice of cheesecake, that only leaves 600 remaining. Gonna be hard to meet protein, fiber, & micronutrient goals on that intake. Also will be hard to feel satiated

On the other hand if your energy expenditure is high & your budget is 4000 calories per day, you might need to eat some calorically dense foods in order to meet your energy requirements without feeling completely stuffed & bloated. Yea it’s 900 calories of junk food... leaving 3100 calories remaining to still meet your nutrient requirements... easy

Flexible dieting is self regulating for people who don’t abuse it. For example, I eat ice cream daily in my offseason because I really enjoy it & I can still hit my nutrient requirements by eating it each day. It also prevents me from feeling like a bloated mess. However, when I’m dieting down & calories drop under 2500, I will choose less energy dense sources of foods by default. I rarely eat salad... til I’m dieting. Then I eat the shit out of it because it’s really satiating. I could have ice cream & protein powder instead but why would I want to when I’d still feel super hungry afterwards 🤷🏼‍♂️

@soheefit actually did a contest prep (she won btw) where she ate a snickers each day & still lost fat just fine. But the funny thing was that after a few weeks she did not want to eat the snickers because it was 250 calories & not very filling. She would have much preferred something less energy dense & more filling

That is what flexible dieting truly is, not the ALL JUNK FOOD DIET 🙄

Instagram vs. Reality … (TW - if you are a Virgo and can’t handle the sound of someone eating you’re going to struggle.)⁣
⁣
I wanted to share this footage of myself to normalise and/or reinforce the reality that (often) gets left off apps like this;⁣
⁣
⁣
1. I don’t think we see fitness professionals and/or models eating enough. Normalise girls eating please - not just taking photos of their food. ⁣
⁣
2. Fitness Professionals eat sandwiches, or at least this one does. It’s not all protein pancakes and shakes and steamed veggies (as great as those things may be). A sandwich is a wonderfully convenient way to consume nutrient dense foods; but somewhere along the path it suffered some defamation. I love sandwiches and I wanted to normalise the idea of eating it incase you somehow felt it wasn’t ‘fitness’. ⁣
⁣
3. There’s a whole process that goes into creating a lot of the content that ends up online that, unless you’re producing it then you really don’t know exists. Which leads you to feel as though everything is just perfect, there’s not a hair out of place and that’s what fitness (and life) should look and/or feel like. My hopes is that by sharing this hashtag BTS you are reminded of all the stuff that goes on behind the proverbial curtains. ⁣
⁣
Just remember these things the next time you’re scrolling through your beautiful feed of curated imagery.⁣
⁣
Hows the ASMR on the eating tho? And yes I ate the corn, but threw away the arugula (rocket).

In short, you can either suffer now, or suffer later on in life. 

Waking up, doing the workouts, being sore, not eating the almond croissant when you see it giving you the side eye, it’s all a part of some form of suffering. 

But it’s suffering for the ‘greater good’ (hot fuzz voice). 

Should you neglect to suffer now, you’ll no doubt suffer later on in life when you pay the repercussions of not staying on top of your health seeking lifestyle. 

I said in an email this week: 

“Not proactively looking after your health with good diet and exercise is like leaving the front door wide open each night before bed.

There’s every chance nothing bad will happen. But if you wake up one day and all your cherished possessions are stolen from you in the night...

You’d probably have wished you locked the door every night before bed.”

However it will be too late at this point to lock it, the stuff is gone.

The suffering is going to happen at some point, that’s life... 

Don’t be fucking naive, you’re not going to get through this without facing the music at some stage in your life. 

Here’s the important part:

There’s a way to fall in love with the suffering when it’s on your terms. 

I’m not sure there’s a way to fall in love with the suffering when it’s not.

So when you construct your life and what you do in it each day, choose wisely.

James
Image Text: SUFFERING IS NOT ONLY A CHOICE. IT'S INEVITABLE I'll explain... BRA'

Absolutely fabulous post by @teambiolayne coach @antidiet_dietitian on why motivation is NOT ENOUGH for long term success. Read & follow her!

Repost: Motivation is just a fleeting #emotion that needs to be backed ⬆️ with something #stronger ⁣
⁣
#Inspiration, doesn't last long. You gotta find something ➕ powerful to replace it with 👉that's where #MOTIVATION comes in. However its downside is that fluctuates & isn't very reliable despite being a big key in that intermediate phase of a journey i.e #dietingphase⁣
⁣
📍when motivation is ⬇️ you'll need something STRONGER than that to fill up those gaps of ⬇️ motivation:⁣
👉 so that's where #COMMITMENT & #INTENTION come into the game. Hence, even when you're not motivated you're still going to do whatever it takes & will stick to the PLAN.⁣
⁣
The key here is to have a #PLAN. If you dont have a plan you won’t have anything to stick to🤷‍♀️⁣
⁣
If you have a plan is easy, when your motivation is ⬆️, you stick to it. When it's ⬇️, you use your INTENTION & COMMITMENT to stay FOCUSED⁣
⁣
Now you can have all the intention of the world ( it's a promise, it's a dream), but it ain't enough, so here comes the #DISCIPLINE.⁣
⁣
This is something that uses #WILLPOWER to accomplish your #ADHERENCE up to where it needs to be. However, WILLPOWER has a limit & it can get burned out quickly & may not recover that easily so there's when #HABITS come in⁣
⁣
With HABITS all that stuff that requires motivation & WILLPOWER, gets automated, making ADHERENCE ➕ easier⁣
⁣
To create those habits you gotta have a structure such as simple & sustainable customized meal plans, strategies around behavior change, how to do meal prep, how to count macros, read labels, ongoing coaching & support. ⁣
⁣
However the caveat of habits is that you gotta hang in there, they can take a while to develop 2wks at least.⁣ So does it get easier? 100% yes
⁣
The last thing to achieve ADHERENCE is PASSION (Excited about the journey) get in love with healthy eating, educate yourself ➕ , be part of a community to share experiences & ideas, which elevates passion to a whole new level⁣
⁣

Description:
Posture is everything.
Having children makes working on my posture incredibly challenging. Can any other mamas out there relate? 

Growing bub, having a cesarean, breastfeeding, carrying bub 24/7 and now that Paris is stronger I tend to favour a hip and push one side up higher than the other. (I’m consciously trying to evenly hold on both sides)

My core is weak (from 3 cesareans) & my lower back is now whack from it 🤪

Luckily I have been working closely with a chiropractor who has a keen interest in pregnancy & pediatric related conditions.
This has helped my diastasis recti, mild scoliosis, pelvic tilt & twisted hips.

Please don’t ignore discomfort, your body is smart, it’ll tell you when something isn’t quiet right. No matter who you are, how long you have been training for, seeking professional support for your health is VITAL.

You aren’t going to recomp your way to an impressive physique 🤷🏼‍♂️

So many people ask me if they can use our app @carbondietcoach (link in bio) to recomp. My answer is sure, but not many people can recomp to an appreciable degree. Those who can actually gain a significant amount of lean body mass (LBM) & lose a significant amount of fat simultaneously are mostly limited to the following groups:

-New to resistance training
-Returning to resistance training after a long layoff
-Obese
-People on steroids
-Any combination of the previous

Can others recomp? Sure, but it will be relatively minor. Most people want to build LBM with zero fat gain. Sorry, but you need to add mass in order to build LBM. You don’t have to get sloppy, but let’s just use basic logic

When I started lifting I was 140 lbs. I was about 8% body fat on calipers. Don’t you think I wanted to add slabs of LBM while getting shredded? Of course I did. But check this photo out from my last pro natural bodybuilding show. I was just over 190 onstage shredded. I had to add over 50 lbs of LBM over 15 years to get there. Do you HONESTLY think I could have added that much LBM without adding body fat? If so, then I’ve got a bridge to sell you

As you approach your genetic maximum, being in an energy surplus becomes even MORE important for building LBM. Muscle is energetically expensive tissue, why would the body add LBM that’s energetically expensive with no energy surplus when you already have a lot of LBM?

Im not saying you have to get sloppy. You don’t. Even when I was up to 230 lbs I was still in better shape than most people, I just had extra fluff. Then I used our app to cut back down to a leaner physique & guess what? That revealed all the LBM I had built

So sure, you can try to build LBM & lose fat staying the same weight. I tried to do that when I was a kid & I just spun my wheels for a year until I committed to BUILDING.

Here’s the good news, we tend to add a mix of LBM & fat mass when we gain weight with training (more LBM than fat in most cases). When we diet down properly, we lose preferentially from fat compared to LBM. Do enough PROPER gains & cuts & you will build something impressive

Calorie Density vs Nutrient Density 💪🏽 Taken from #TheArtOfResilience (see link in bio for YOUR copy) I thought this was worth repeating as to why @phdnutrition super greens are a STAPLE in my diet ALL year round... (Lesson 20: Resilience is best Served with Food)... “Despite swimming for up to 12 hours a day and burning calories like a furnace, I had to adhere to the research published in the journal Obesity Surgery, ‘It is a common belief that clinical vitamin or mineral deficiencies are rare in Western countries because of the unlimited diversity of food supply. However, many people consume food that is either unhealthy or of poor nutritional value that lacks proteins, vitamins, minerals, and fibre. The prevalence of vitamin deficiencies in the morbidly obese population is higher and more significant than previously believed.’
Athletes’ diets (and the nutrition of some people) are basically high in calories, but low in nutrients. Ina survival situation, any calories are good calories. But studies show when possible you should always choose nutrient-dense foods. ‘Ultra-endurance exercise training places large energy demands on athletes and causes a high turnover of vitamins through sweat losses, metabolism, and the musculoskeletal repair process. Ultra-endurance athletes may not consume sufficient quantities or quality of food in their diet to meet these needs. Consequently, they may use oral vitamin and mineral supplements to maintain their health and performance.’ (2010, International Journal of Sport Nutrition and Exercise Metabolism) 
This is an idea echoed by others. ‘Additionally, micronutrient needs may be altered for these athletes while dietary intake is generally over the Recommended Daily Allowance because of high caloric intake.’ (1991, International Journal of Sport Nutritionand Exercise Metabolism)
For that reason, the goal of every meal was always to eat calorie-dense and nutrient-dense foods during the hours I was awake and conscious (in the water or on the boat)” 🔱 #PerformSmart

Our weight fluctuates so much throughout a day, we can’t expect all weight movements to be correlated to fat gain and fat loss. 

We often forget 1 litre weighs 1kg, so hydration and dehydration influence the scale so much. 

Bowel movements, even having your morning turd after your coffee is enough weight to get in your head. 

Sally from Slimming World would slap you round the head with her slipper for gaining a lb, the truth be told you haven’t had your morning shit yet.

Pro fighters often drop 5-10% of their weight before a fight. Almost all of it comes from water and water stored in carbohydrates inside muscle. 

10% for me is 9.5kg, that’s 20 lbs!

You wouldn’t sack a sales employee for having a day with little to no sales. 

So don’t be a dick when weighing yourself, keep the variables the same (usually empty bladder first thing). 

Accept there will be fluctuations and merely monitor the averages across time. 

One hot day doesn’t make a summer. 

Weight moves, all the time. It’s an accurate metric over time but not for those who can’t be pragmatic to handle the fluctuations. 

James

I have been on both ends of the spectrum.

I was once considered overweight, but I also knew my lifestyle wasn’t healthy. I binged on Burger King, alcohol, and smoked cigarettes here and there. I definitely didn’t work out! I was a broke, newly married nursing school student just trying to survive and my health was of the least importance.

When I did discover organic foods and healthy living, I started losing weight rapidly! This made me feel soooo good. However I started taking it too far.. until I was considered underweight. I would spend countless, wasted minutes in the grocery aisles reading the labels, counting calories. My diet per day consisted of Diet Coke, diet pills, healthy choice meals (200 cal per meal, if y’all don’t know), 100 calorie Campbell’s soups, and not touching anything with sugar in it. I still didn’t workout but I managed to lose 45lbs because I severely restricted my calories. I was miserable.

It wasn’t until I became a mom that I realized what true health meant-that it truly had more to do with the inside. If you improve your mental health, the outside will reflect that. don’t get me wrong, I’ve suffered from severe postpartum depression for many years and it’s always been a roller coaster for me. But as of today I can truly say I am on the right track.

Today, I don’t count my calories or macros and I’m working on my sobriety. I don’t omit any foods! I do CrossFit when I can and work out at home with my guides. I like to meal prep to save time and peace of mind, but I also like going out for sushi, pizza, and pasta with friends. I don’t do any special diets but I do eat in moderation.

I promise you, there is a perfectly healthy middle ground. A middle ground where you CAN love your body and not be extreme. It might take you a few years to find it like it did for me. But once you reach that balance, you’ll know! And it has nothing to do with how you look. 😉

Are you working on your relationship with exercise? Then maybe this journey might resonate!?⁣
⁣
START in the Diet Mentality: ⁣
You and exercise have a complicated relationship. In the past it may be tied to restriction, dieting & disorder. ⁣
You know it can’t go on like this together and are looking for another way. ⁣
⁣
MIDDLE in the F*ck It Phase: ⁣
You learned what Diet Culture is and how it’s played a role in your difficult relationship with food, exercise and your body and you say F*CK IT! You need a break and time away from your old exercise behaviours and time to experiment and figure out what works for you. ⁣
This part, could be weeks, months, years but it won’t be forever. ⁣
⁣
IN BETWEEN the f*ck it phase and the sweet spot: ⁣
You challenge the fitness rules, have fun trying different types of movement and work on strengthening the connection between you and your body, ⁣
⁣
END at the Intuitive Movement Sweet Spot: ⁣
This is where you have found your own version of balance. It will look different for everyone but at it’s core it’s a place where you can enjoy movement without immense pressure. You listen to your body & take rest when needed. ⁣
And you’re able to work towards goals in a flexible way (this is the principle of Gentle Guidance in practice). ⁣
⁣
This journey is different for everyone depending on our experiences in diet culture, and the external pressures of weight stigma and fat phobia. ⁣
⁣
But just so you know, you’re not alone on this path. It’s normal to take time away from exercise before you’re ready to gently re-introduce it! ⁣
⁣
You can hear me chat about this in last weeks episode of @thetrainhappypodcast with @zannavandijk & @victorianiamh. ⁣
But I hope this diagram gives more meaning and visualisation to that conversation.⁣
⁣
Let me know what other questions or topics you would like me to cover when it comes to Intuitive Movement.⁣
⁣
#intuitivemovement #trainhappy #fitnessjourney #balance #exercise #intuitiveeating #rejectdietculture #dietculturerebel #recovery #joyfulmovement ⁣
⁣

When you get a flat, do slash the other three? 🚙🔪

When you stub your toe, do you turn around and stub the other?🦶💥

When you get a bad grade, do you purposefully flunk the semester? 📝❌

No.

You don’t do any of those things. (I hope)

So the question is…

Why let one bad meal or day of eating turn into weeks & months of eating poorly?

Why let one missed workout turn into weeks & months of sitting on the couch?

Look.

When you start a nutrition or exercise plan, you have every intention of giving it your all.

You want to do things *perfectly.* 👌

And while I commend you for the effort, there’s just one tiny problem...

Perfection doesn’t exist.

There will absolutely-positively be moments when you eat off-plan — even when you have every intention of staying on track...

There will absolutely-positively be mornings you wake up and don’t feel like going to the gym, even though you promised yourself you’d go the night before...

Shit happens, and that’s okay.

The most successful dieters have three things in common:

1️⃣ They do the right things most of the time.

2️⃣ They make mistakes occasionally.

3️⃣ When they make a mistake, they acknowledge it, learn from it, and get back on track.

Losing weight is just like everything else in life.

There are ups & downs & highs & lows.

Success comes when you stop chasing perfection and start chasing persistence in each moment regardless of what happened the moment before.

What you do MOST of the time matters most. 💯

~

When was a time you chose persistence over perfection?

Comment below.

– Carter
Image Text: Stop letting one bad meal turn into a full day of poor choices. Stop letting one bad day turn into a week of falling off track. Chase persistence, not perfection. -Carter @CarterGood LFL COACHING HING LINK IN BIO

Description:
Motivation is important.

If you aren't motivated, you'll never get started.

But if you want to lose weight and keep it off forever, you need to build discipline.

When you're motivated, it's easy to hit your nutrition targets and get your workouts in.

But no amount of motivation will keep you on track all of the time.

Sometimes, you'll end up eating more calories than you needed. Occasionally, plans will change and you'll have to skip a workout.

It’s easy to lose motivation in those moments…

… And when you lose motivation, it's a lot easier to beat yourself up for falling off track…

… And when you beat yourself up for falling off track, you're more likely to STAY off track.

You need to be able to stay on track, but you need to be able to get back on track too, and that's where discipline comes in.

How can you build more discipline?

One way is to identify (and work around) your weak spots.

For example, if you struggle with willpower, then you need to get better at planning.

At @leanerforlife, we make all of our clients schedule their workouts a week in advance. We also get them in the habit of planning their meals at least 24 hours ahead of time. 

(A strategy called "24Before")

This works because you’re more likely to stay committed to a promise you made to yourself than rely on willpower in the moment.

Another way is to start with a smaller commitment.

If you're struggling to exercise 4-5 days per week, start with just 2-3 days. 

Or even just one day!

Build discipline with a smaller commitment, and once you feel that you've mastered it, you can increase your level of commitment and start the process over again.

You have to be willing to forgive yourself too.

Discipline isn't built from perfection — it’s built from persistence.

Especially in the face of adversity. 

If you can learn to forgive yourself, you'll be in a better headspace to learn from your mistakes and, even better, use them as tools for growth. 

~

Comment below if this was helpful. 💪❤️

– Carter
Image Text: Being able to stay consistent with your diet shows that you're motivated, which is definitely important. But being able to go off your diet one day and get right back on track the next shows that you've developed discipline When it comes to long-term success, discipline beats motivation every single time. -Carter @CarterGood LFL COACHING LINK IN BIO

Maintenance calories is so underrated 

It’s underrated because the process of dropping fat occurs over a longer period of time, depending on expenditure with moving and training 

Now when we’re trying to accomplish ‘a good physique’, work rate, consistency and patience is the most essential thing. 
It’s also the hardest trait to improve on because it requires a lot of discipline. 

Reasons I think maintenance calories for the long run are great 

1. Better performance in the gym due to energy levels 

2. Better recovery due to eating more 

3. Athletes tend to sleep better on higher calories 

4. Mental stability which helps athletes stay consistent with routine and training

5. General activity tends to increase with a higher caloric target #neatup247

6. Brain functionality is so much better

And the most important one 

7. You’re not a miserable bastard 🤷🏻‍♂️😂

There are many more benefits to being on maintenance calories, these are only a few and yes, you’re able to lose body fat and build muscle on maintenance calories but you have to be patient and train well ✊🏼 💪🏼 

Ps: I don’t look like that anymore #softbellychronicles

#neatup247

Description:
Did you know your rest days are just as important as your workouts? ⁣
⁣
And yet many of us fear rest, feel guilty for taking time away from training and therefore don’t give our bodies the opportunity to actually respond to what we’re giving it.⁣
Very much speaking from personal experience here 🙋🏼‍♀️. ⁣
⁣
And if you’re training to improve strength, speed, endurance etc rest days are integral to improving! ⁣
⁣
So in the same way we might plan our workouts for the week, try scheduling rest days too.⁣
AND if your body is telling you it needs more than a day to rest, take as much time as you feel you need. ⁣
⁣
🔑 A key component of Intuitive Movement is UNCONDITIONAL PERMISSION TO REST. ⁣
⁣
Knowing that no. matter. what. it’s ok to rest.⁣
⁣
Through doing this we are taking the power away from the guilt, shame and fear that try to stop us from listening to our bodies and push us into the ‘no days off’ mentality. ⁣
⁣
And by building up that trust with our bodies, we start to learn our bodies cues for rest as well as movement. ⁣
And we also learn the difference between needing rest, and needing to just get our workout going with some gentle self discipline - but I think that’s a post for another day. ⁣
⁣
What are your thoughts about rest days? ⁣
How do you feel about taking them? ⁣
⁣
#TrainHappy #Restdays #intuitivemovement #unconditionalpermissiontorest #rest #restday #fitness #workout #nodaysoff #beastmode #fitnessjourney

Title: How to get a 6 pack [Truth]
Description:
Tag and share this with as many people as possible🔥 It’s important to understand that when it comes to ‘revealing’ your abs (we all have them, only difference is their prominence) the fat burning portion of your workouts and what you consume on a daily basis, will have far more significance in helping you achieve that goal than all the abs work you do. 

Now I used the term ‘revealing’ as it is a goal sort by many which is separate to building, just wanting to see those lines come through, is not the same as wanting to ‘build’ your abs. Clearly to build the abdominal muscles you need to train them, but there is a huge misconception that just training them in isolation, will miraculously emulsify the fat that hides them, it won’t.

This is why I always encourage those seeking abs to be mindful of their body fat, evaluate your starting position, you may decide that your time could be better spent on exercises that torch more calories and lower your body fat, than doing a 1000 crunches.

What would happen if every fitness influencer (or self-proclaimed educator) had to write a research report every time they made a health claim on instagram? ⁣
⁣
My hypothesis is that there would be a decline in the rate of claims (especially BS ones), possibly an increase in just entertaining content (at least there would be no real danger there) AND there would be a distinct increase in quality. ⁣
⁣
Now all that said, I am certainly NOT advocating for this ... What is so appealing about SM is that we can access bite-sized reminders and inspirations about human health habits. But health is so abstract and SM makes it WAY TOO EASY for people to make false claims by virtue of the halo effect (google it - so interesting). ⁣
⁣
Now let’s be real, we like our content, the way we like our food; FAST, PALATABLE AND HIGHLY SAUCY. ⁣
⁣
But at what cost to our society?⁣
⁣
So what’s the answer here? Trust only qualified experts (that seems a little academically elitist right)? OR encourage content consumers (aka. us) to raise our expectations by …. I don’t know, fill the gap please. ⁣
⁣
What are your thoughts?

There is no such thing as “too out of shape” to work out.

Fitness is for you.

It’s not some kind of exclusive club you have to earn entry to (though I totally get that it can feel that way.)

What’s your biggest reservation about getting started? Tell me below.

We all started somewhere. And some of us started way later than others. (41🙋‍♀️)

If somewhere for you is walking a few minutes everyday- YES! Let’s go!

If somewhere for you is a single set of bodyweight squats- Boom. Get after it.

Let one step, however big or small lead to another and than another. The sum total of all those first steps will compound to long lasting positive results.

Don’t let fear of looking stupid or of being judged or failing keep your from experiencing the incredible mental & physical benefits that exercise can bring to your life.

Xx,
Kim

 #workoutmotivation #workouttip #exerciseathome #outofshape #fitish

Description:
This bathroom probably isn’t the appropriate place for a P.S.A. but imma say it anyway.... 

Your boundaries won’t scare the right people away.

This has probably been THE SINGLE most difficult AND important lesson for me to learn in life this far. 

hbu? What’s been the longest / most difficult lesson you’ve needed to learn (unlearn)?

Can you get away with just dieting to lose fat and not exercise? 🤔

This certainly is a loaded question, and while the answer may be yes you can “get away with it,” I want to discuss why it certainly isn’t optimal.
How is weight loss achieved? You eat less than you burn, simple. By taking the diet-only approach, you are influencing the “how much you eat” portion of the equation.

However, simply eating less for sedentary individuals may be difficult since their metabolism can be relatively slow due to low levels of muscle mass and physical activity, both of which influence metabolic rate. Additionally, as you start to lose weight your metabolic rate will decrease as an adaptive mechanism, which means you’ll have to eat even less if you don’t exercise!

So, what does exercise do? To answer this question, I want to cover a study by Willis et al., (2012), which compares the effects of aerobic, resistance, and aerobic + resistance (A+R) exercise on fat and lean mass in overweight and obese adults for eight months.

What happened?
At the end of the study, those who performed A+R lost the most amount of fat mass. This makes sense, since they were exercising the most, they had the highest energy expenditure. RE alone resulted in the least amount of fat loss. This also makes sense, RE doesn’t burn as many calories as aerobic training, so it resulted in lower fat loss. However, RE resulted in the largest increase in lean mass, followed closely by A+R, while those performing just aerobic exercise lost a bit of lean mass.

What does this mean? Exercise can help increase the rate of fat loss compared to just dieting. Also, including resistance exercise will attenuate losses of lean mass, which is a major reason why individuals metabolic rate tanks after losing considerable weight.

Overall, there is no reason to NOT exercise. Sure, dieting is a step in the right direction, but including exercise is just as important to help you achieve your physique goals!

Does red meat really cause cancer independent of other dietary variables? Our newest Team Biolayne coach Dr. @josephmu94 breaks down the most recent research on the topic

Red meat consumption causes cancer!"

We’ve all heard this, right? I know several people who shy away from red meat for this reason. They’re not to blame, there’s certainly some scientific data suggesting that processed red meats contain compounds that may be carcinogenic like heterocyclic amines & polyaromatic carbons

However, when talking about whether a specific food causes a certain disease in humans, we need direct, clear, & convincing clinical data. Biological systems are complex, & the effects of a 
substance in a cell culture study may not play out the same way when introduced to a physiological system with many moving parts

This recently published meta-analysis by Maximova et al., (2020) investigated the associations between different levels of meat consumption (low, med, high) & cancer when co-consumed with fruits & veggies at different levels as well. I like this study design because it mimics real life. Most people don’t just eat meat in a meal. Typically, we consume it along with some plant-based foods

On slide 2 I summarize the results between unprocessed meat consumption & cancer. We see an elevated risk of cancer ONLY for the high meat consumers who also eat very low fruits & veggies. Every other combination of meat and F&V consumption was not associated with an increased risk of cancer compared to low meat & high F&V intake

Interestingly, the high meat & high F&V consumers actually had a numerically lower risk of cancer!! However, it was not statistically significant so we can’t just to conclusions

I think this study is a really good demonstration of why clinical data are important & we can’t make conclusive suggestions based on animal or cell culture studies. Again, our physiology is complex. The 
foods we eat interact during the digestive and absorptive process & may have different outcomes compared to their individual effects.

Give Dr Munoz a follow for more great info: @josephmu94

Unless you’re converting UV rays into energy with some kind of photosynthesis you’re probably consuming too many calories than your requirements when you gain body fat. 

It’s not the end of the world, our composition should be full of ups and downs all year, Christmas, Summer Holidays and apparently Pandemics. 

Having too much body fat can cause issues down the line as systems in the body can’t do their thing, case in point T2 diabetes. 

But outside that, it’s just a protective mechanism doing it’s thing. Having the majority of our fat stores close to our centre of gravity make it easier to manoeuvre. 

I feel body fat gets more hate than it should, “cushin for the pushin” and all that. 

If you want to lose some of the stores:
- not a detox
- not a cleanse
- not a change in PH
- not a different eating window

Just reverse the process of how you attained the weight, find a calorie deficit and drop some of the fat. 

Some of it will find it’s way back I’m sure, but that’s life and the peaks and troughs of needing to diet, wanting to diet, needing time away from dieting and not wanting to restrict. 

None of which in my eyes are a bad thing. 

James
Image Text: Body fat isn't a bad thing, it's really a double edged sword of a protection mechanism. 1) too much food consumed, prevent it from circulating and store it efficiently 2) not enough food consumed, utilise the stores to fuel you efficiently It's just doing it's job... James Smith @jamessmithPT_

It’s time to reverse diet!

As many of you know, I lost 30 lbs from November of 2019 to November of 2020, culminating in my ‘Shred with Layne’ photoshoot with @sergey_yusin in Miami. I used the fat loss setting on my app @carbondietcoach (link in bio) to lose the weight, then switched to maintenance in the app after my photoshoot & have been on maintenance for the last 20 weeks or so. During that time I maintained within 2 lbs of my photoshoot weight the entire time, what can I say, the app nailed it

Last week I made the decision to begin a reverse diet in the app for a few reasons. 
1.  I want to try to slowly add some more lean body mass. Being that I’m likely close to my genetic ceiling after 20+ years of lifting, this isn’t going to happen without at least a small transient surplus
2. I want to get my energy expenditure up so that in the future I have a larger cushion to cut from it I want to shred to another level
3. I normally have good energy for training but having more calories will help me recover even more and push my strength further
4. Who doesn’t love to eat more?
5. All of 1-4 but I also want to minimize bodyfat gain

Now some people will claim you don’t need to reverse diet.. you don’t 🤷🏼‍♂️

Some people have said it isn’t magic... it isn’t 🤷🏼‍♂️

It’s simply another tool. I have seen some clients have crazy results with reversing where they lose weight while adding significant calories over time, even up to several hundred, even has high as ~1000! Now people will say “you’re saying they defy calories in calories out!”

Nope. CICO is a LAW

What is likely happening for these individuals is their increases in BMR & NEAT outpace their increases in calories, leading to a deficit even through caloric additions

I’ve never responded like that, I usually respond pretty standard to a reverse. But I’m starting a new kind of training I’m excited about & if it goes well I will be talking more about. So I’m ready to put these calories to good use

Swipe right to see my first reverse check in on @carbondietcoach 👉🏼

Funny enough, I actually LOST 😬

Who else is reversing? How is it going? How do you like it? Leave me a comment or question below! ⬇️

✨No one has a right to be “freaked out” by your body.⁣
⁣
I got a comment from a woman who was super scared to start lifting weights because her husband “freaked out” that she would start looking like a body builder.⁣
⁣
So much to unpack here... but first:⁣
⁣
1️⃣No one has a right to be offended by the way your body looks. It’s YOUR choice to look how you want to look. ⁣
⁣
Whether we have more muscle, body fat, wrinkles, or whatever, our bodies are GOING to change and that’s ok. It’s not freaky, it’s normal.
⁣
2️⃣Putting on muscle is actually really hard. If it were that easy, you would see a lot more ripped dudes walking around. ⁣
⁣
It takes time, consistency, and hard work. It doesn’t happen overnight. Also, women have different hormones which make the process of building muscle a bit different. Regardless, it takes time and consistency. ⁣
⁣
💛All that to say, I wanted to give her (and you!) a hug and a confidence boost that you can be confident in how you look now without changing a thing AND you can also be excited about making healthy changes (if that’s what you want to do with your body). ⁣
⁣
💪Beyond that, just flex and do your thing.⁣
#thedailykelsey

Why are you doing this? You don’t have anything left to prove to anyone?

“You’re too old”
“Too broken”
“The young guys have passed you by”
“The game has changed since you competed...”

I was talking about my journey through injuries the other day. In my lifting career I’ve been through:

-2 herniated cervical discs
-Torn right pectoral (required surgery & 18 month recovery)
-2 bulged & herniated discs in my lumbar
-Torn muscle in my left hip
-Partially torn left pec
-Adductor strain

And yet I’m still diligently working my way back to the platform

Why? I have already won nationals twice, won the Arnold, set a world record in the squat (been broken since), gold medal in the squat at worlds, and a silver medal overall at @theipf worlds in 2015

So why keep trying to comeback? This person was right... I don’t have anything left to prove to ANYONE

But it’s not about you or anyone else

It’s about ME. Because I still have something to prove to MYSELF

I still have a burning passion & desire to hit the platform again & mix it up. Yea these guys competing now are hitting insane numbers. Maybe I’ll never get back to another title. But... if I can train like I KNOW how I can train when I’m pain free & I know what I can do when it comes to gameday. I’m a hunter. The big meets I won I was NEVER the strongest lifter there. But when it’s show time, I don’t fucking miss. I would put so much pressure on my competitors because they knew I wasn’t going to make mistakes & if it was in my reach on the last pull, I was going to hit it. So they made calls they wouldn’t usually make

But maybe I’ll never win another title. That’s ok. What I would never forgive myself for would be quitting on something I was still passionate about simply because of setbacks or frustration

So I’m going to empty the fucking tank. Give it everything I’ve got. I may fail, but I will get way further & learn about my myself than if I just gave up because the mountain seemed too high.

I’m going to do whatever it takes. Maybe it’s not enough. But that will be because I gave it everything I had in the arena

505 x 3 tempo squats pain free. You may not see it yet, but I see it

Here I come...

No.

I won’t tell you what to eat.

Because I’m not you.

I don’t want anyone telling me what to eat b/c, frankly, I’m in no way eating Lima beans, green beans or peas.

You don’t need a meal plan to lose weight, because meal plans are a band aid. A poorly fitting, germ infested band aid at that🤢

You are a grown woman and can choose what goes in your mouth. Pick proteins you like, pick fats you like, pick carbs you like. Carbs includes vegetables my friend so choose the ones you like or at the very least can tolerate. You can learn to like vegetables no matter how old you are. I did it at age 43.

Eat those things in proper portions so that you’re getting optimal protein, plenty of micronutrients and staying in a deficit of weight loss is your goal.

If you’re a woman over 40 and want me to walk you step by step through creating your own meal plans: hit the link in my bio to join my 60 day challenge.

Xx,
Kim

PS- tell me what food will 100% not be on any meal plan you make for yourself!

Aaaand apps such as this one are one of the many reasons why women are so insecure with their faces. So many apps on the market-this has over 1 million ratings-to slim your jaw and nose, smooth your pores, enlarge your lips and eyes, and even apply freaking makeup. Ugh. It sucks to know that this is the world our daughters and sons will grow up in. But this is why I spread the good word. 

Don’t get me wrong. Filters are cool and fun. But these apps that drastically (even minimally) change your appearance are the problem and they end up doing more harm than good-especially when you use them for yourself. Because you fall in love with the edits and hate what you see in the mirror. Many people use these and you wouldn’t know... until you saw them in person.

Again. Don’t compare yourself to a stranger on the internet whom you’ve never met. 🖤

Glutes get a lot of attention but don’t neglect to strengthen the front of your legs too! Here are some non-barbell/non-machine exercises you can try at home (or the gym if you’re lucky enough to be back there) to target your quads.

☀️Elevated bear squats with band resistance
☀️Skater squats (I did counterweighted and limited rom with a block)
☀️Heels elevated goblet squats
☀️Kneeling leg extensions (can adjust rom to make easier or harder)

Because people always ask, this isn’t a workout with reps/sets. I wouldn’t suggest doing all of these in the same workout. More isn’t always better! Pick one or two in a workout to try.

If the kneeling leg extensions are too challenging, you can try limiting your range of motion or using a band for assistance by attaching it to a banister or something else sturdy and putting it behind your glutes. As you go backwards, the band stretches and helps you to get out of the bottom position.

If any of these make your knees feel “less than great”, you can always try modifying so your posterior chain contributes a little more. E.g. do regular goblet squats or even do them to a box to limit forward knee travel or swap reverse lunges for the skater squats.

Go forth and smash thy quads (with great form 😝👊🏻)

AD / HOW TO BUILD RESILIENCE? @underarmour 

1. Put yourself and your goals first. Sometimes you have to be selfish and block out the negative dramas around you which could so easily be holding you back from reaching your full potential. Once you’re free from the negative energy you’ll have the time and focus to do what’s best for you and your VISION 👊🏼

2. Optimistic approach to everything you do. Don’t doubt yourself, don’t be scared to fail. Visualise the best outcome of every situation and go for it. You’ll be left behind with a pessimistic approach. 

3. Self Compassion! Don’t be so hard on yourself, don’t always have to be the tough guy who just gets on with it. Accepting your current situation and dealing with the problem with a thought out solution will get you a lot further than hiding away from your failures/stressful situations. Don’t do it 👊🏼

4. HEALTH. Looking after your health should be a priority. Eat healthy, avoid large consumptions of alcohol and junk food, sleep 8 hours and workout regularly. Build your strength with weight training and your fitness with cardio. How do you expect to reach you full potential without being physically fit? A fit body will result in a healthy mind, Has to be done 👊🏼

5. Collaboration - who are your connections ? who are you surrounding yourself with? People who want to see you succeed or people who are more than happy to see you fail. Delete and move on from those who stop you 👊🏼
Positive energy always!! 

6. Belonging! Find your belonging don’t waste your time doing something you don’t enjoy, something that doesn’t test your skills. What are you passions? what best suits your characteristics? 
Enjoying what you do finding your purpose will bring progress. 
Don’t fall into the trap of ‘this will do’ because you can achieve better 💪🏼

// LET’S GET YINTIMATE // Pretty chuffed with that title! 💁🏼‍♀️ We’ve got a 60-minute soothing yin practice going live on @mysoulsanctuary today for the members and it just made me think about how much I love a good old yoga prop! And not just for restorative practices.

Props are NOT for beginners and by using one it does NOT mean you’re doing it “wrong”. I remember when I first started practicing I never took a block, a strap or a bolster with me to my mat. I practiced very much from a physical egotistical space, thinking that these ‘things’ would just make me look rubbish and not understanding why I might find them useful. Needless to say I was practicing asana, but I was worlds away from practicing YOGA. Fast forward 11 years of yoga being in my life and I can safely say that props have been a big part of my journey and I love them. Even if I don’t end up using them in a practice, they will always be close to my mat, just in case.

Have you experienced a similar relationship with props?

I think we should make some lovely @mysoulsanctuary props...
What d’you think!? 😜 Ethically and sustainably made of course. ❤️

Most people think losing weight is about fighting against who they are right now when it should be about evolving into who they want to become. 

Read that again. 

And again.

Because what’s holding you probably back isn’t your diet or exercise plan. 

It’s the story you‘re telling yourself.

The story being that you are “broken” now and have to be “punished” with a weight loss plan to “fix” yourself. 

☝️ That’s some bullshit. 

You are not broken.
You don’t need to be punished.
And you don’t need to be fixed.

You’re just not satisfied with where you’re at right now, and that’s totally okay. 

But if you ARE unsatisfied, you have to either choose to accept it or change it.

If you choose to accept it, then you can’t beat yourself up about it. 

If you choose to change it, you need to be ready to embrace the suck that comes early on when you’re just getting started.

Embrace it, learn from it, and keep going. 

With time, you’ll suck less and less, and before you know it, you’ll be one of those people who figure out the “secret” to getting results. 😉

– Carter

Just a quick PSA - Bodyweight does not always mean beginner. ⁣
⁣
Imagine a the difference between a bodyweight push up and a dumbbell chest press. Provided you choose a light weight, the DB Chest press is actually EASIER than the push up. ⁣
⁣
Don’t be fooled into thinking that just because you’re a beginner that you don’t need weights; I would argue that if you’re a beginner YOU DO NEED WEIGHTS because they can help to build the strength gaps that are preventing you from performing some of those body weight based exercises that you’re not quite able to do yet. ⁣
⁣
That said, I don’t want to dishearten anyone that is experiencing financial difficulty right now - there are ways to create resistance with relatively cheap items (I’ve shared these workouts before).⁣
⁣
But I felt the need to:⁣
⁣
a. normalise beginners using weights ⁣
⁣
and ⁣
⁣
b. dismantle this notion that bodyweight workouts are strictly for beginners; try saying that the next time you try bodyweight gymnastics drills. ⁣
⁣
I’m not really as mad as I look in the picture but if it helps drive the point home, I’m here for it.

Title: HOW TO PROPERLY BRACE IN CHATURANGA JUMP BACK
Description: Make yoga safe again 💙🙏🏾

𝐊𝐄𝐄𝐏 𝐑𝐔𝐍𝐍𝐈𝐍𝐆 🏃🏽‍♂️ 

For a lot of people it’s easier to answer why they don’t like running than why they do. Why?? A good run is like medicine for the soul! I can’t tell you how many times I’ve been told, “I can’t run.” It’s like people expect there is some magical technique or test that marks people who can run from people who can’t. NONSENSE. If you run, you’re a runner. End of story. 

If you don’t feel ready or confident enough to get running, start small. Start with a slow walk, pick up the pace each time you go, then when you’re ready, pick it up to a light jog. You don’t have to time it, you don’t have to map it or track it. If you’re just starting out, just go until you can’t. Then walk. Then go again if you think you can. Don’t overcomplicate it. Running is that simple.
.

You could eat a banana nut muffin & a glass of OJ from the local mini mart for breakfast, a large cake -in-a-cup coffee concoction mid morning, a burger from McDs for lunch and a Coke and chicken fingers for dinner. 

Or for less calories but *more* food eat:
✅ A banana, big bowl of oats and some Greek yogurt  for breakfast.
✅ A massive salad with greens, tomatoes, cucumbers, onions, carrots, & peppers, grilled chicken and a sweet potato with cinnamon for lunch.
✅An Apple and some air popped popcorn for snack 
✅ A salmon filet with a side of roasted broccoli and rice for dinner.
✅ And even a small chocolate chip cookie for dessert

If you haven’t tried this way of eating, give it a shot. Not only will you be in a better position to lose weight, you’ll be more satisfied & of course healthier.

Enjoy your weekend!

Kim

DO AB WORKOUTS MAKE YOUR ‘tummy’* ‘FLAT’?⁣
⁣
The short answer is no. They may contribute to an overall energy deficit by virtue of the effort it takes to execute them, but even then, exercise activity thermogenesis (EAT) contributes to a relatively small portion of your Total daily energy expenditure …⁣
⁣
BUT THAT’S OK RIGHT? BECAUSE THAT’S NOT THE REASON WE DO AB EXERCISES. ⁣
⁣
So tell me - why are you training your abs? ⁣
⁣

Same day, same minute.✨ Just because you don’t see it doesn’t mean it’s not there. For as long as I could remember, this bothered me-so much that I threw all of my shorts away! As I’ve gotten older, I’ve become more comfortable in my skin. I realized there are bigger things to worry about such as the health of my kids, world hunger, and taxes. Seriously... cellulite... over 90% of women have it. It’s quite silly that we have come to demonize something so common! What gives?

Put on that swimsuit. Wear those shorts. Stop letting your body control you! You’re only given one life to live and I doubt you would want to miss out on 95% of that life to weight 5% less. Am I right?

I don’t care about any cellulite creams or fascia blasters. My cellulite fluctuates just as my weight does. The best way to minimize the appearance of cellulite is by lowering your overall body fat percentage through regular exercise (cardio + weight lifting) and a diet low in sodium & saturated fat while staying away from excess sugar, alcohol, and nicotine (toxins). That’s it.

The truth is, most of us might not ever get to completely get rid of it. And that’s OK. It’s all down to genetics at the end of the day. But that is really all you can do so save your money and practice self-love while improving your daily habits. 🖤
