Description:
All my single ladies! This post is for you. No, this is not fitness related. But it’s something that I felt called fo share.

I’ve been single for a few months. Honestly, I can’t remember the last time I was single for this long.. I was maybe 17 or 18 years old? Being single seemed like such a scary thing to me, something I did not want. I had the biggest fear of being alone up because I was sooo co-dependent. But I realized something.. being single is a superpower.

I do go on dates here & there, but I come home to me, myself, and I. I rely on myself and for the first time, I don’t feel like I need anyone. I don’t call anyone mine-I am my own. Wow. What a power to have!

Being single has also made me a better mom. I get to put 100% of my attention to my kids during this time. I have zero distractions in my life and they get the full me. These are the most important years of their lives and I want to be there for them 100%.

Being single has also allowed me time to reflect, grow, and do inner work. Separating from my husband really showed me a lot of what I needed to resolve within myself. I got closer to Christ, I quit relying on alcohol to soothe my depression and anxiety, and I started becoming a better friend.

Does it get lonely? Of course, sometimes. At times I wonder if I’ll ever find the one 🤣 I swear that I’ve gotten so picky!

The reason why I am sharing this is because I know that some of you ladies are probably struggling right now with being single. I’ve been told that this season won’t last forever and I do believe that. I was also told that once you stay single long enough you won’t want to start dating again. I didn’t believe it at first, but that’s so true 🤣 I love it!! I never thought I would say that. Getting to do what I want, when I want, without someone else limiting me. It’s awesome!

If God (or your higher power) has called you to be single right now, use this season for yourself. Use it to get closer to Him. Use it to change bad habits. Use it to find out what you truly want in life. Use it to envision your perfect ideal partner and teach yourself to not settle just to be with somebody.

Enjoy singlehood. It won’t last forever. 🖤

Title: Can You be Fat but Fit?
Description:
Obesity is strongly associated with all cause mortality, cardiovascular disease, and cancer (PMID: 19940414/) 

While there is some evidence that you can be 'fit and fat' insofar as you can be obese but still have healthy biomarkers (PMID: 24438729) 

It appears that even when 'healthy obese' (obese people with healthy blood markers) are compared to healthy non-obese, there is still an increased risk for mortality, cancer, and cardiovascular disease (PMID: 23637352)

Facts > Feelings
Image Text: CAN YOU BE FAT AND FIT

Description:
Do you have chronic low-back pain? 😩

I’m not talking about those of you who snapped something up from deadlifting something that was too heavy. I’m talking to those who go about life with general low back pain (LBP) on a daily basis. Guess what, you’re not alone.

According to Georgetown University, nearly 16 million Americans report persistent or chronic LBP. The question is, what do you do about it?
The last thing many people want to do may actually be one of the most beneficial… Lift weights! Many people with LBP may shy away from resistance training due to the fear that lifting heavy things will aggravate their pain & think they need to just rest to reduce the pain. WRONG! Lifting weights has been shown in several studies to improve LBP💪🏻

Chronic LBP may result from a sedentary lifestyle which is typically accompanied by weight gain, perceived disability, & decreased physical function, NOT because “you’re really injured”. Exercise on the other hand can improve these conditions.

A study by Cortell-Tormo demonstrated that a 12-week progressive resistance training program improved general LBP as well as physical fitness (measured in total repetitions performed in exercises like the squat & bicep curl) compared to sedentary controls (slide #3)

Strengthening of the muscles of the back & core seems to be the main mechanism by which resistance training reduces LBP. These results have also been supported by meta-analysis that look at the sum of literature on resistance training & chronic LBP with very large effect sizes on reducing LBP!

General considerations: Resistance exercise is not the only modality of exercise which has shown to improve LBP. Yoga, aerobic exercise, & Pilates all have been shown to improve back pain. The main message is… EXERCISE! The main reason I wanted to cover resistance exercise specifically is because so many people are afraid to do it when they have some pain. Additionally, lifting weight will make you look better in the process!

That said, if you have suffered an acute low back injury, you may need to rest it until you can get to a pain level that allows you to resume lifting weights
Get to the choppa, @nasa!

If you’re struggling to lose weight, chances are it’s one (or all) of the reasons I’m about to share with you.

~

01 - You’re not in a calorie deficit.

It doesn’t matter how “clean” you eat, how hard you work out, or how many supplements you guzzle down.

If you’re not in a calorie deficit, you won’t lose weight.

That doesn’t mean you have to count calories,but calories count, whether you count them or not.

Now, in my opinion, keeping a food log alongside calorie counting is the best way to ensure you’re being consistent.

And when you go about it the right way, it can actually help you develop a better relationship with the foods you come in contact with on a daily basis.

But whatever you choose to do, you need to be in a deficit.

~

02 - You ARE in a deficit, just not consistently

Getting in a deficit isn’t the hard part — it’s staying in a deficit long enough to see results.

And that’s because most people have unrealistic expectations for how quickly weight loss should happen.

They expect to see multiple pounds every week, and when that doesn’t happen, they get discouraged.

Another reason it’s is because of the unsustainable methods people use to create their deficit — usually something that requires you to eliminate carbs or sugar.

Eliminating can help you eat fewer calories, but it’s not sustainable for most people — especially if it forces you to overhaul your entire way of eating.

~

03 - You aren’t fully invested

When motivation is high, it’s easy to commit to a new diet and exercise plan.

But motivation eventually goes away, and if you aren’t invested in the process, your chances of success are slim to none.

The most obvious form of investing is a coach or program.

But you don’t have to spend money to get invested.

You could also find an accountability buddy or join an online support group like the free LFL Facebook community.

You could also create a reward system where you buy yourself something new at different progress milestones.

What matters is that you invest yourself into the process beyond your own motivation and will.

~

Title: 10 MOVE HOME HIIT
Description:
Whole body home sweat - this HIIT workout is a super sweaty cardio blast

We work through 10 moves - twice - with the timings changing on each lap

First lap: 40 secs work, 20 rest, two sets on each move
Second lap: 20 secs work, 10 rest, two sets on each move

That first lap is your endurance lap with the longer sets and longer rest, the second lap is your speed lap so go for those sprints as fast as you can on each set

And of course, there is a little two minute finisher at the end

𝐓𝐑𝐀𝐈𝐍𝐈𝐍𝐆 𝐈𝐍 𝐑𝐀𝐌𝐀𝐃𝐀𝐍 

I’ve had so many questions about this and the answer isn’t one size fits all. You have to listen to your body and do what feels right for you as we all respond differently to fasting. I tend to strength train in the day, BUT I’ve been doing that for years and my body responds well to it. Ramadan isn’t the time to start training if you haven’t exercised before. Your health is the priority and you must ensure any training you do is done safely. In general, I’d recommend the following to the majority:
*If you’re trying to maintain muscle mass, I’d personally try to limit cardio to twice a week and do after iftar rather than before
*Largely, I’d recommend people who wish to train before iftar try training at a lower intensity or try something like a brisk walk
*If you want to continue with higher intensity workouts, try breaking your fast on something light like coconut water and dates beforehand
*Heavy weight training is usually best saved for before suhoor so you can refuel adequately within the “golden hour”
*Be realistic. You may well lose some mass during Ramadan because it’s hard to train so late at night. This is ok! If you maintain some sort of training and consistency, you’re on the right path so don’t panic. 
Focus on your internal health rather than the aesthetics. I’ve created an IGTV RAMADAN TRAINING SERIES with some low intensity workouts, be sure to check them out. Share & Tag a friend or relative below who might benefit from them, hope you’re having a blessed month 🙏🏽🌙
.
.
.

Title: FULL BODY DUMBBELL WORKOUT
Description:
Dumbbell strength and conditioning workout to add a little bit of resistance to your training.

This one works the whole body with a slight focus on core and legs.

We work through two circuits of five moves, and perform one lap of each circuit

Each set is 40 secs of work, 20 rest, and we perform 2 sets on each move before we move on.

At the end of each circuit we perform a 40 second cardio move before moving back on to our weights.

I have two 4kg dumbbells but you can choose any weights that suit you/you have at home.

You can use full water bottles or cans if you don't have weights.

ENJOY

Not the most elegant or sexy #throwbackthursday 🤣back when I had a lil’ internal bleeding (not planned) while wrestling @UFC Hall Of Famer, @kenshamrockofficial aka “The World’s Most Dangerous Man”.

I loved wrestling Kenny around the world and we had some classic matches.

On this night I took a hard suplex and the impact damaged blood vessels in my lungs causing the blood to come up. 

Kept composed, made sure I could breath and continued with the match. 

I’d like to think Ken would’ve shown me some compassion, but his facial expression says “f*ck your bleeding lungs” as he tries to rip my ankle from my tibia
😂🦶🏾🩸 

These were good days and this was how I proudly made my bones. 

As always, “thank you for house”, brother 👊🏾🥃

I’m not against anyone who chooses to go Keto, Paleo, or Vegan to lose weight. 

If it works for you, and you genuinely enjoy it, then keep at it.

But idk.

I just don’t get it. 🤷‍♂️

Why follow a diet that force so much restriction and lifestyle change when there’s a scientifically proven way to lose weight that doesn’t require a single bit of elimination?

You have to be in a calorie deficit to lose weight. (SCIENCE 🤓)

You can either create a bunch of rules about what you can and can’t eat in hopes that it’ll create a deficit…

OR

You can learn how to use moderation and portion control to create a deficit and never have to be that person who’s always declining dinner invites with, “sorry, I’m on a diet.” 

Both are hard, but I’d argue that one comes with a much larger upside and a flexible fitness lifestyle.

The choice seems obvious to me...

But hey, what do I know? 

I’ve only lost over 145 pounds and kept it off, helped hundreds of clients get results, and helps hundreds of thousands more with through my posts and emails. 😉 

– Carter

I wrote this for someone who is going through a rough time. We all go through hard things every now and then, so I thought maybe it could be helpful for you too... ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
✨I want to give you some encouragement. You have been through a lot and have overcome so much. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
It can feel so hard when negative thoughts bombard our heads, but you are not doomed. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
You ARE making progress. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Strict and rigid food rules and disordered eating habits will NOT be the answer. They will only lead to further challenges. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Stick with this program. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Keep putting in the work. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Make adjustments according to your doctor's suggestions. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Think of this as a life journey rather than a few weeks. It can help take off some of the pressure of timelines and wanting results quickly. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Let's also flip the script in your mind to positive truths.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
You are more than your weight.⁣⁣
You are more than your measurements.⁣⁣
You are more than your dress size.⁣⁣
You are more than your body fat percentage.⁣⁣
You are more than the calories you eat (or don't eat).⁣⁣
⁣⁣
You are great because of who you are and not how your body looks in this moment or how it looks when you reach your perceived goal. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Keep your head up. You are WORTH it. ⁣⁣

Upper Body Dumbbell Workout | SAVE TO RAVE⁣ 
⁣
Following on from yesterdays post regarding weight training here is a simple upper body sequence using dumbbells:⁣
⁣
A1. Push Ups (if you’re not able to do these yet, just work on the eccentric portion, lowering down for a count of 4seconds, optional 1second hold at the bottom - this will also help to strengthen push ups if you can do them, but have hit a strength plateau) 4 sets, 8 reps.⁣
⁣
B1. Skull Crushers (tricep strength is an imperative for yogis - I mean for everyone, but definitely yogis - get this into your repertoire but ensure you’re keeping forearms parallel, do not let elbow spray out to the sides) 4 sets, 12 reps⁣
⁣
C1. Standing lateral raise (I had to swing a little here which I wouldn’t normally encourage, but when you don’t have lighter weights, that can be an option, provided you try to lower down slowly). 4 sets, 12 reps⁣
⁣
D1. Standing Bicep Curl (just out here tryna normalise girls with big biceps because they’re important muscles) 4 sets, 15 reps. ⁣
⁣

Who loves more calories? 😬

I do! This is the end of my 2nd week of reverse dieting using my app @carbondietcoach (link in bio) & my calories are up, energy is up, weight has barely moved (less than half a lb total) & my caliper measurements are still the same! Things are going so well, the app increased my calories a bit! Swipe right to see my check in 👉🏼👉🏼👉🏼

Before anyone says anything, I am aware that I’m not REALLY 6.1% body fat. But that is what calipers are putting me at. I don’t really care what the real number is, I just use these measurements for comparisons. The fact is that NO measures of body fat are truly accurate unless you want to die & have your adipose tissue excised out of your body & weight. Na I’ll pass thanks!

So why reverse dieting? Well I enjoyed the dieting process & honestly @carbondietcoach made it stupid easy for me to drop 30 lbs last year. Then once I hit my leanest state I switched to maintenance mode on the app... & that’s exactly what the app did. Maintained me within 1.5 lbs of my end of cut weight for almost 5 months!

Now that I’ve healed up a few injuries it’s time to get BACK to crushing some weights. Since the limit of my weight class in powerlifting is 93kg (205 lbs) it doesn’t really make sense for me to stay here at a full pound under. So my plan is to reverse diet using the app for the following reasons:

1) More calories to fuel my performance in the gym 🔥

2) Increase my lean body mass while minimizing fat gain😈

3) Maximize my energy expenditure so that when I go to cut back down in the future, I can get even leaner, with even less effort 😎

4) And who doesn’t like more food?🍔🌮🥙🥪🥗🍕

Honestly the app makes it so easy. I just pick my goal, select how conservative or aggressive I want to be, then just log my food, log my weight daily, check in weekly with the coach, & the app takes all the guesswork out of my adjustments. Swipe right to check out my weekly update 👉🏼👉🏼👉🏼

Over 30k people trust our app to coach them, including @hollytbaxter & myself. At less than $10/month it’s a no brained. I can honestly say I’m so proud of this app

Did you know that the diet and weight loss market is a $78 billion industry?

(And that’s just for the US)

Yet as a nation, we are more overweight and obese than ever before.

Clearly, there’s a disconnect between what people *think* they need and what they actually need to be successful.

As a teenager going into my young adult years, I fell victim to this industry over and over again.

I followed the same pattern every year:

🔄 I’d get a burst of motivation to lose weight…

🔄 I’d start whatever diet was most popular at the time…

🔄 I’d get some quick results in the first few weeks or months…

🔄 Eventually, I’d burn out and gain all of my weight back plus some. 

It’s a sucky cycle, to say the least.

But the addictive nature of the cycle is what makes it vicious. 

With each failed weight loss attempt comes impatience, and that impatience makes it easier and easier to fall victim to diets and programs that promise unrealistic results.

So how can you get out of this cycle once and for all? 

You have to realize there’s no amount of motivation or discipline that’ll end the cycle. The only way out is to reframe the way you think about fitness and weight loss as a whole.

𝗜𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝘄𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗹𝗼𝘀𝗲 𝘄𝗲𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗸𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗶𝘁 𝗼𝗳𝗳 𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗳𝗶𝗻𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗹𝘆, 𝘆𝗼𝘂’𝗿𝗲 𝗴𝗼𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘁𝗼 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝘁𝗼 𝗺𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝗳𝗶𝘁𝗻𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗿𝘁 𝗼𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗹𝗶𝗳𝗲 𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗿.

It’s not sexy or marketable.

I can’t sell it to you for 3 easy-peasy payments of $29.99.

But it’s the truth.

And the sooner you accept it, the better.

Because once you do, it’ll be a hundred times easier to stop falling for unsustainable diet and exercise programs that waste your time, money, and energy.

And START following diet and exercise advice that fit your lifestyle forever. 

– Carter

I have overnight oats all year round, but during Ramadan I love them at suhoor because they’re easy to grab and eat. But they’re also full of slow release energy and protein to help sustain me through a day of fasting. I make a big batch of soaked oats with a mix of oats, nut milk, chia seeds and ground sweet cinnamon and use that as my base. It keeps in the fridge for a few days in an airtight container. I then serve up a portion for suhoor and add whatever I fancy. Swipe across for my favourite flavour combos during Ramadan and see below for what what I add to the soaked oats mix to make them. 

Carrot cake oats: Grated carrot, small splash vanilla essence and a handful of raisins. Topped with chopped walnuts and sprinkle of desiccated coconut. 

Berry boost oats: Mash some raspberries into your oat mix, with a splash of vanilla essence. Top with berries of your choice and desiccated coconut. Pad it out with some pistachios or almonds if you have some. 

Tropicana oats: Coconut milk or a splash of coconut water works well with your oat mix on this one. Stir in some desiccated coconut and a mashed banana. Top with pineapple and mango. 

I don’t measure anything, I just do it by eye. But when you add chia seeds for the protein and omega 3 benefits, you need quite a wet mixture because they soak it right up. I’ve put a story up to show you the base mixture if you want to give it a go. Don’t forget, you can add protein powder to your base oat mixture if you want to fill yourself up even more during Ramadan (or are eating these post-training throughout the year.) “FAISAL35” will give you 35 per cent off on the @phdnutrition website if you wanted to grab some protein to try any of the above.
.

Real quick before we jump into home gyms: The Menopause Weight Loss Course: Your 60 Day Challenge is available for only 2 more days. Dozens & dozens of ladies have signed on to build their strongest, healthiest, fittest body yet. Hit the link in my bio to see what it’s all about & join them.

The course comes with a 6 week progressive strength training program that can be done in your home gym, speaking of which:

The most important piece of equipment you need in your gym is dumbbells. The adjustable ones are a good option if maximizing space is important. Whatever kind you choose, don’t stop with 3s, 5s, 8s, 10s & 15s. You are underestimating your own strength. You can lift more than 15lbs & will need those 20s, 25s, 30s, 35s, 40s etc to give your body the stimulus it needs to adapt (read -get strong, toned & defined.)

If you try to base your home gym around bands you will be frustrated w/ your lack of progress over time. But for sure get the long loop bands in a variety of thicknesses. In combo w/ an over the door pull up bar you will be able to train your back. (You don’t have to start with pull ups: there are loads of pull down variations. But also: you *can* do pull ups.)

An adjustable bench will be useful. Sure you can get away with your ottoman & the floor, but you’ll be able to do a much wider variety of exercises w/ the adjustable bench: incline chest press variations, batwing rows, & chest supported rear delt raises, to name a few. I have clients who’ve bought foldable ones if space is an issue. Check out the rest of that 2nd slide for more useful equipment that will fit in most people’s long term budgets/spaces.

Now slide 3: maybe it’s not realistic for your space.  But if you have a garage, basement, or spare bedroom, get your hands on a barbell, plates & a rack. I want you to experience the transforming power of the iron. You are already stronger than you realize &  have the capacity to be so much stronger. The physical strength you can build with barbells pales in comparison to the inner strength that builds right along with it. There is something magical about challenging yourself physically. It is transformative. 
Xx,
Kim

Is your cousin’s girlfriend’s Aunt’s neighbor’s son’s 5th birthday really a special occasion for you?
 
If every co-worker gets a birthday lunch and you treat every single one like it’s your birthday…
 
It’s gonna be hard to reach the level of consistency you need to see real fat loss progress. Every week having a “special event” isn’t conducive to fat loss.
 
Look, I’m not here to tell you what’s special and what’s not. You get to decide that for yourself because you’re a grown woman. I’m just here to push you to question yourself. The next time you think “it’s a special occasion, so I’ll just eat…” question yourself.
 
One more unpopular opinion: not all special occasions need to be celebrated with food.
 
That likely feels wrong because it’s just what we do- big thing, fun thing, exciting thing happens- we go out for ice cream, cake, pizza…
 
But what if sometimes, we celebrated by going for a hike to see an incredible view or going dancing, or literally any fun non-food bit of specialness you can create. There are loads if you can get out of the special occasion = food mindset.
 
Hope this helps!
Xx,
Kim 

#weightloss #fatloss #losingweight #losingfat #menopauseweightloss #menopausefatloss #over40fitness
Image Text: Kim Schlag @kimschlagfitnes Unpopular opinion: Your loose definition of "special occasion" is standing in the way of you losing weight. If every week there's a special event, are they really that special, or is that just daily life to navigate?

Description:
Parents, have you ever helped your kid look for candy that you know you ate?

You dig through the pantry, shrugging your shoulders with a feigned look of bewilderment on your face. “I don’t see it here Buddy.” (In case any of my kids are reading along, I have never , ever done this👀)

Yeah, your chances of “finding” motivation are slightly better than your kid finding that candy.

2 pieces of good news though:

1. You don’t need motivation nearly as much as you think.

Think of all the things you do just because you value the outcome of doing that thing. Teeth brushing is the perfect example. You’re not pumped to brush your teeth every morning & night. You’re  not putting the Crest on the brush because you’re feeling it. You do it because you don’t want a mouthful of cavities. You do it so your partner won’t cringe when you go in for a kiss. Think of your fitness habits like brushing your teeth. You don’t need to wait around feeling motivated to eat more protein or go outside for a walk any more than you need to feel motivated to brush your dang teeth. Make a decision. And then take a small step forward. Walk for 5 minutes. Chop some cucumber and eat it with your favorite dressing. Grill some chicken & portion it out into individual containers.

Decide. And move.

2. You can create motivation as you get that forward motion going. One little step and then another becomes a habit. That habit brings results.

Results are, wait for it...

✨MOTIVATING✨

Love your guts,
Kim

#motivationalspeaking #motivationalsayings #motivationalthought #motivationalmoments
Image Text: Kim Schlag @kimschlagfitnes No one is motivated all the time. The people who are most successful at achieving whatever it is you want to achieve aren't motivated everyday. Stop agonizing over needing motivation. What you actually need is a decision & forward movement. Grit down & take 1 step forward.

Fat Carbs ("Dual Fuel") 🔱 I was getting A LOT of questions about my cake and coconut (oil) ball combo the other day during a long, aerobic session so wanted to quickly post 😊 It was inspired by Lesson 20 from #TheArtOfResilience (see link in bio for YOUR copy) which states, "We can’t eat enough carbohydrates and store enough muscle glycogen to fuel really long endurance events. This is why research conducted at Harvard Medical School said, “Considering the total carbohydrate-based energy reserve from muscle glycogen, liver glycogen, and plasma glucose, it becomes clear that normal carbohydrate stores alone would be insufficient to fuel a marathon.” The solution? Add fat. This is because research published in the American Journal of Physiology found working muscles consume a mixture of metabolic substrates, and the relative contributions of fat and carbohydrate to this mixture dynamically depend on exercise intensity and the size of available glycogen reservoirs. It’s concluded, “Carbohydrates account for a greater proportion at higher intensities, while fat accounts for a greater proportion as available glycogen is depleted.”

Description:
Carbs do NOT make you hungry! Eating too much hyper palatable processed food high in carbs AND fats make you hungry! 👉🏼

Type 2 Diabetes (T2D) is one of the leading comorbidities associated with weight gain & obesity. Since diabetics struggle with proper carbohydrate disposal due to insulin resistance, dietary strategies that reduce carbs have become popular for T2D

So T2 diabetics should just eat less carbs right?

Saying eat less carbs to a diabetic to manage their T2D is like putting a band aid over the symptom & not necessarily addressing the root cause. There is plenty of data suggesting that reducing body fat can improve insulin sensitivity & glycemic control independent of the type of dietary intervention used. What’s one of the major issues associated with eating less?
Hunger! Which makes it extremely difficult for some individuals to eat in a caloric deficit. Therefore, using strategies that improve satiety may be a better strategy than avoiding carbs for both diabetics & normal individuals alike!

A study by Struik et al. compared the effects of isocaloric very low cab (VLC) or high carb (HC) diets on measures of hunger & satiety in diabetics while being in a 500 – 1000 kcal deficit per day. The VLC diet was 14% CHO and 58% fat while the HC diet was 53% CHO and 30% fat

What happened?
After 16 weeks, both diets decreased bodyweight by about ~10.5 kg on average. However, the HC diet improved overall ratings of fullness and prospective consumption (the desire to eat in the future) compared to LC. This means that the HC group had fewer thoughts about their next meal compared to the VLC group

The authors suggest that this is may be due to increased gastric filling. Carbohydrate rich foods contain more volume than high fat foods for the same number of calories & there are some interesting mechanisms by which food volume can reduce hunger. But that will be a topic for a future post.

Moral of the story, if you personally feel more satiated on a VLC diet then it can be a tool to reduce your intake. However, there is no evidence that its better than eating calorie matched HC diet on average, even in populations that have issues with T2D

You're going to screw up.

No matter how hard you try.

No matter how motivated you feel.

No matter how disciplined you try to be. 

You're going to overeat, skip workouts, and fall off track. 

But here’s the thing. 

Overeating isn't that big of a deal. Skipping a workout isn't that bad.

The real issue is when you set unreasonable expectations to be perfect, inevitably fall short, and creat undeserving guilt and shame.

~

You need to stop thinking that every mistake you make is a sign that you can't do this.

Because you CAN. 

All of the mistakes you make along the way are normal.

What matters most is how you respond to them.
⠀
You have to stop with the same and guilt. Stop with the "woe is me" crap.

When you make a mistake, forgive yourself. USE that mistake to learn and grow.

And then make the next choice the best you can make it.
⠀
That's what'll build consistency, confidence, and success. 
⠀
– Carter
Image Text: You shouldn't feel shameful or guilty for falling off track. It happens to everyone, and dwelling on it will only make things worse. Just focus on making your next choice the best you can make it. That's how you build confidence and consistency. Carter Good @CarterGood LFL COACHING LINK IN BIO

Stability Drills (great for Runners or people with hips) | ⁣
⁣
These are HARD if you’re executing them correctly. Particularly the first one. ⁣
⁣
Both these exercises have been paramount in strengthening my hip post injury, as well as helping me to improve stability around my shoulders, ankles and core. ⁣
⁣
You could add them to the end of a resistance workout as ‘finishers’ or as a movement preparation - the difference being you would hit higher reps if performing as a ‘finisher’ and moderate reps, definitely low sets (maybe even just one) if only using as a movement prep. ⁣
⁣
Runners (particularly those of your new to running) there’s this misconception that you need running to get you fit, but the truth is, you need to get your body fit to run. Exercises like this (or slightly regressed variations are incredibly beneficial in prepping joints and muscles). ⁣

Losing weight is hard.

Anyone who tries to convince you this process is easy is likely trying to make a quick buck.

But it can be made easier.

These 3 strategies have helped me lose over 145 pounds and hundreds of clients, and I know they’ll work for you too.

~

1. Create a Calorie Range

Calorie counting ensures you’re consistently eating few enough calories to create a calorie deficit.

The keyword being consistent.

Let’s say that you work out that you need 1800 calories to lose weight, and one day you go over and hit 1950 calories.

If you believed you had to hit 1800 calories to lose weight, then eating 1950 calories would technically be off-track.

And that may lead to more overeating that day into the next. 
But here’s the thing —> 1950 calories is STILL in a deficit!

Just less of one. 

But if you set a calorie range that was 150 calories above and below 1800 calories (1650-1950), you’d still technically be on track.

And because you’d still be on track, you’d be in a better mental space to continue moving forward.

If you wanna give it a try, click the link in my bio to use my calorie range nutrition calculator.

~

2. Find Staple Meals & Foods

One of the great things about tracking is that it allows for flexibility and variety with food choices. 

But too much variety can backfire — especially if it’s taking up loads of time each day.

That’s where staple meals & foods come in.

A staple meal or food is one that: a) you enjoy, b) is easy to make, and c) helps you hit your nutrition goals. 

I recommend finding 5-10 meals or foods that fit the criteria above and making those stapes in your daily.

(Some staples for me are @Flexpromeals, eggs, crockpot chicken, rice, and shredded potatoes.)

~

3. Plan 24 Before

Making fitness a priority requires planning, and 24 Before is the strategy we use to help our clients stay one step ahead. 

And it’s a simple as taking 5-10 mins at night to plan for the next 24 hours.

When you make 24 Before a priority each day, you’ll end up staying on track more often than not. 

~

Implement these strategies will make this process easier and more enjoyable.

Cardio and core circuit to build strength in the trunk of the body and improve our fitness with some seriously sweaty cardio moves

Our circuit works through 14 moves and we perform 2 sets on each move, 40 secs work 20 rest, before moving on to the next

This means making time for the things you have to do, as well as the things you want to do.

I'm not falling off the wagon, I'm just enjoying the fruits of my labour & I’ll get back to work later. ✌️🏾

As gyms re-open and more activities are starting up, this post is a reminder to be kind to yourself and above all listen to YOUR body! ⁣
⁣
The temptation may be to throw ourselves back in to exercise out of guilt from lockdown weight gain and a loss of fitness. ⁣
⁣
BUT, we know when diet culture is running the show it often leads to unsustainable habits, worse body image outcomes and therefore more guilt & shame. ⁣
⁣
So if you’re trying to adopt an intuitive approach to movement remember these tips above as we ease back in to movement and find our groove again. ⁣
⁣
Above all, don’t compare to others online or in the gym. Focus on you, your fitness levels and how your body feels. ⁣
Because this is different than how it used to be. No more punishment. No more earning & burning. Instead it’s self celebration and self care all the way 🙌🏻💜⁣
⁣
What other intuitive movement reminders do you find useful and would add to this?⁣
⁣
#TrainHappy #IntuitiveMovement #listentoyourbody #fitness #selfcare #nondietfitness #dietculturedropout
Image Text: INTUITIVE MOVEMENT REMINDERS @tallyrye Choose the workout that makes you feel good Listen to your body for cues to move & rest Give yourself unconditional permission to rest Celebrate what your body can DO instead of focusing on what it looks like Take a break from your Fitness watch- Don't let numbers define your workout

Description:
When someone first gets into fitness, one of the first things they’re recommended to do is eat more protein.

And for good reason.

Eating enough protein is important for building and maintaining muscle. 

Protein is also very satiating, which is helpful when you’re in a calorie deficit.

But here’s the problem.

The common recommendation for protein intake is 1 gram per pound of body weight. 

This might not be an issue if you’re at healthy body weight, but if you’re currently overweight, trying to hit this requirement can be incredibly difficult.

Here’s the thing...

The 1 gram/pound recommendation is based on what’s OPTIMAL for building muscle. 

Chances are, you aren’t trying to be a bodybuilder.

If you’re like most of us, you’re just wanting to lose fat, build some muscle, and feel confident in how you look & feel.

And for that, you don’t need to force down gobbles of protein every day. 

Here’s a better approach:

Instead of aiming for 1g of protein per pound of body weight, shoot for .7-1g of protein per pound of GOAL body weight.

For example, let’s say your current weight is 200 pounds, and your goal weight is 150 pounds. Instead of aiming for 200g of protein, you should aim to get 105-150g of protein per day. 

You can even take it a step further and make 105g of protein per day your minimum daily goal, meaning you can have more than 105g of protein, but you won’t eat less than that on a consistent basis.

The Bottom Line:

If you want to lose fat at build muscle, you need to make sure you’re eating enough protein each day.

But you don’t have to eat as much as you’ve been led to believe. 

If you’re able to get .7-1g of protein per pound of goal body weight, you’ll be getting plenty of protein to support your goals.

Plus, having a lower protein goal will make it much easier to actually hit your target without having to make your entire day about protein.

~

Was this helpful? Let me know in the comments

– Carter

Title: Hear this loud and clear...
Description:
You shouldn’t feel guilty for making time for your health. YOU are just as important and your actions speak louder than your words.

My kids won’t remember the clean house, the perfectly made beds or the expensive clothes they wore. 
But they will remember how their mum made them feel, the example their mum set, the positive energy she radiated & how she made her health a priority.

Actions speak louder than words!

When you work on YOU, you are calmer, responsive as opposed to reactive, you are more patient, motivated & and tend to be more productive.

Self-care is giving the world the best of you, instead of what's left of you.

RUN REHAB SEQUENCE | #MindOverMuscle @Underarmourwomen AD⁣
⁣
Progress is the accumulation of small, daily choices. For me (while injured) those choices have had to include; exercising less, dialing back the jiu-jitsu and NOT SKIPPING REHAB no matter how boring or frustrating it is. ⁣
⁣
Here is a sequence I am working with at the moment to maintain strength around my hips (particularly my right hip, adductor and ankle) and build more stability in my right foot (all these stability issues occurring on the fractured tibia side). ⁣
⁣
1. Hip extension & abduction⁣
2. Isometric Adduction
3. Single Leg DL to SL Calf Raise⁣
4. Skaters Lunge to Calf Raise.⁣
⁣
The last exercise is one of my favourite strengthening (and proprioceptive improving) exercises for the feet and ankles (mine are really struggling post injury). ⁣
⁣
These exercises also double as excellent running warm ups/movement preparations (obvi provided you don’t have any pre-existing  contraindications). ⁣
⁣
For anyone struggling with a niggling injury, kind of past the ‘bed-ridden’ and/or rest phase, the JUST WANT TO TRAIN HARD BUT CAN’T phase … don’t rush it. It’s not worth it. Remember we’re in this for life, just just 8 weeks or 12 weeks or for June 21st. ⁣
⁣
Train for life (oui, oui, it’s a double entendre).⁣
⁣
Drop your Q’s below and let me know if you want me to make some real time sequences like this for Youtube. ⁣

Thanks for having me on again @studio10au to talk about “InTuItiVe EaTiNg” 🍩🥤

- in a nutshell I think eating intuitively is great for all times in your life apart from when you need to lose body fat

- most fitness people and celebrities who preach it as a lifestyle often come from backgrounds of restriction and tracking, therefore it’s more calculated than intuitive

- fat loss dieting is like accelerating on a road, there are times the foot is down, others coasting and others slowing down. It’s not a constant state, only a protocol to reach your destination

- if you went payslip to payslip without creating debt I’d applaud your efforts and say you go ahead and spend intuitively - but if you were constantly in your overdraft I’d say it’s a smarter idea to watch your balances and give yourself a daily limit to ensure you could reach your goals

I’m someone who needs to eat 25% beyond full to be happy at a meal, calorie tracking has worked for me and thousands of my clients. 

Most my clients are in a pickle in the first place from listening to their bodies in the first place 😂 

My clients listen to me, not their bodies for the first few months of being in my academy. 

They apply knowledge and experience from there on in, not so much intuition. 

Feel free to change my mind 😂
James

Staying focused has been a challenge lately.
I'm finding I'll step it up in one area but drop the ball in another. Yes, I get this is life & that's cool we can all relate. But my gosh the ball has been dropped a little too much lately. Am I alone?

What do I do when this sort of stuff starts happening?
1. I acknowledge it.
2. I whip out my “to-do” list and write absolutely everything down on the specific day that needs to be completed.
3. I go through my “calendar” and organise my and my families life.
4. I lock in all my training for the next few weeks.
5. I clean, tidy and put things away so there's no clutter.
6. I block my day out to go through all my email accounts and text messages.
7. I work on my posture, water intake & open up my windows to let in as much natural light and fresh air.
8. I take a break from TV (except Home & Away 😂) and YouTube for a few days.
9. I schedule in when I need to be in bed.
10. I nourish my body correctly.

If I am not focused, I not only fall behind, but also drop the ball, and hold onto this awful uneasy feeling that increases stress. 

Taking necessary steps to fix your state (if it is not serving you) is vital to moving forward and getting your control back.

I have a whole blog post dedicated to training during Ramadan, but I just wanted to focus on one question I get asked a lot. Muscle mass. How do you prevent yourself from losing muscle while fasting from Ramadan?

The holy month is just not the time to embark on a new fitness journey if your goal is to bulk up, because that’s a very hard task indeed with fasting such long hours (approx 18 hours in the UK!!) The focus, if strength and muscle matters to you, will be on maintenance. People often welcome weight loss during Ramadan because of the inevitable calorie deficit, but muscle loss isn’t something they want, so here are my three top tips:

1. Decrease the intensity of workouts to balance out the calorie deficit. Most people naturally enter a calorie deficit during Ramadan simply because it’s hard to consume what you normally would in the smaller window you have. This will begin to eat into muscle mass if you’re training as hard as you do normally. So decrease the intensity - lower the weight, reduce the reps and increase rest time. I’d say 20-25% reduction in intensity is about right. And consider halving the time of your normal training sessions, or doing less sessions than you would normally.

2. Don’t waste your refuel time. When you have broken fast, use that time wisely. Avoid the junk food and focus on protein which takes longer for your body to break down and will help with muscle maintenance. Lean meats like turkey as well as fish and plant based proteins such as chickpeas and beans are a great choice. If you’re really struggling to fit in your protein intake, protein shakes are a good idea for suhoor but I’d bulk them out with goodness such as spinach, oats, fruit and nut butter so that you’re ticking all the nutrition boxes.

3. Don’t carb dodge and drink that H2O. If you want to keep strength training to help maintain your strength, you really need those carbs for energy. Your training won’t be sustainable without them so add brown rice, oats, wholegrains, sweet potatoes etc to the shopping list. And if you aren’t getting enough water in when you can, then it’s game over. Water is life!!!
.
#ramadan #ramadan2021

Therein lies the rub.

Losing weight is challenging in practice for a bunch of reasons:

✅ You’ve built a lifestyle/habits that support weight gain

✅Our society is quite sedentary

✅ Hyperpalatable food is everywhere

✅ You’ve used food as a main tool to cope with emotions.

✅ You’re unclear how exactly to do it because everywhere you read someone is telling you something different.

I spent 2 decades losing and gaining the same pounds over and over growing ever more confused and ever heavier until I was 41.

When I realized the answer lies in figuring out practically how to make “moving more & eating less” fit into my life as well as adding in dedicated strength training you could have knocked me over with a feather.

You mean Dr. Oz wasn’t bringing me the answer from a rain forest somewhere 🤯😵

You can work through all of those things above. Without a doubt you can. The first step is giving up the idea that it will be easy. You will need to fundamentally change your habits.

Here to help anytime.
Xx,
Kim

Everyone’s got their own opinion on what nutrition approach is optimal for weight loss, performance, and physical & mental health. 

I have my own opinion too.

We could get into the weeds of nutrition science and research too... 

But at what cost? 

Arguing super-duper specific differences in views won’t help you, me, or anyone else reading this who’s wanting to get lean, healthy, and happy.

There’s more to being healthy than eating healthy.

What I mean is this... 

WHAT you eat is important.

But what’s equally as important is HOW YOU THINK about what you eat.

(I’d even argue it’s even more important.)

You *could* eliminate & restrict all “bad” foods from your diet and only eat foods you deem as being “good.”

But what does that do for your mental well-being?

Does it create peace OR does that restriction cause unnecessary stress in your day-to-day life? 

Does it empower you OR does it isolate you from everyone and everything around you?

Does it make you happy OR does it keep you from enjoying your life?

~

I’m not here to argue against the importance of eating whole, nutrient-dense foods.

Most of the time, you should be staying away from large quantities of highly processed junk foods. 

But if you’re at your nephew’s birthday party and he brings you a slice of cake, eat the freaking cake.

If you’re on a date with your significant other at a fancy-pants restaurant, eat what the chef recommends and finish the bottle. 

BEING healthy is about so much more than EATING healthy 100% of the time.

– Carter

PS. If you want 1-on-1 guidance with finding YOUR perfect balance with fitness and getting the body you’ve always wanted, click the link in my bio to apply for the LFL coaching program 💪❤️
Image Text: Healthy eating isn't abont about eliminating foods that are "bad" and only eating foods that that are "good." It's about eating foods that are in line with your goals most of the time and having moderation with everything else. -Carter @CarterGood LFL FL COACHING LINK IN BIO

Ever heard or been told that you should be losing 1-2 pounds per week? 

Chances are you have.

And while losing 1-2 pounds per week will make sense for some people, it won’t make sense for everyone.

Let’s take two different people — Billy & Sally (our example dieters)

Billy’s 6’2, weighs 280 pounds, and wants to get down to 220 pounds.

Sally’s 5’3, weighs 145 pounds, and wants to get back to her comfortable weight of 130 pounds.

For Billy, losing 1-2 pounds per week is great progress.

But if Billy is following his plan consistently, he will likely end up losing more than 1-2 pounds per week, especially in the early stages of his journey.

On the other hand, for Sally to lose 1-2 pounds every single week, she would have to go the extremes with her diet and exercise to even come close to that recommendation.

As you can see, the “lose 1-2 pounds per week” recommendation is flawed once you take into account people’s unique situations.

For Billy, it’s a conservative.

For Sally, it’s unrealistic. 

The better recommendation is to aim to lose 0.5-1% of your total body weight per week.

This gives you a weekly weight loss recommendation based on your current weight that will adjust as your weight goes down.

The closer you get to your goal weight, the less weight loss you should expect to see each week, and this percentage-based recommendation accounts for that. 

Using the new recommendation, Billy should expect to lose 1.4-2.8 pounds per week.

(Since Billy has a lot of weight to lose, he could likely lose up to 1.5% of his body weight each week in the beginning)

Sally’s new weekly weight loss recommendation would end up being around .7-1.4 pounds per week, which is much more realistic and sustainable. 

~

Losing 1-2 pounds per week might work for some people, but it ends up being too aggressive or even a bit conservative depending on the person in question. 

A more realistic and individualized recommendation for weight loss is to aim to lose .5-1% of your body weight per week.

(Or 0.5-1.5% for folks who have a lot of weight to lose.)

📩 Send this to someone who needs help setting realistic expectations for their weight loss results.

Whether you’re back at the office or still working from a makeshift desk at home, workday snacking is a calorie buster that you can tackle.

👉The first thing to look at is your meals. Are you eating enough? I know you think you’re doing yourself a favor eating a puny piece of plain chicken and some dry leaves. It’s a false victory to get in as few calories as possible though. You’re likely to never be satisfied. Not to mention the actual physical hunger that will return quickly. Get in enough calories, a decent amount of protein (25-50g) some fiber, and a bit of dietary fat. That’s a meal that’ll stick✨

👉 Next let’s tackle your environment. Why are you sabotaging yourself with snacks in your desk? You’re not a toddler and you don’t need to eat every 2 hours. Trust that you’ll be ok if you get hungry. Hunger isn’t something that has to be avoided at all costs. You had a nice big meal, remember? You have another nice big meal planned. If you’re going more than 5 hours between those meals, sure plan a snack. Keep it single serving size.

👉 If you find the urge to snack coming and you’re not actually hungry, try taking a break. An actual, step away from work break. Go for a walk, stretch, close your eyes for a few minutes, get outside for some fresh air, talk to a coworker or pet your dog.

Snacks aren’t bad and there’s  no one correct meal frequency. Snacking only becomes an issue if it’s keeping you from seeing the progress you want (in other words you’re eating too many calories.)

Give these strategies a go & let me know how it works. 

Have another strategy to nix workday snacking? Drop it below.

Xx,
Kim

#snackattack #nibbles #flexibledieting #flexibleeating #cico #losingweightjourney #menopauseweightloss
Image Text: Kim Schlag @kimschlagfitnes How To Stop Snacking At Work Stop keeping snacks in your desk purse "just in case." Eat substantial meals. Newsflash: 250 calories is a snack, not lunch. When you feel the urge to snack check to see if you're hungry. Or do you actually just need a break?

Title: Muscle Gain on Low Carb Diets? 🤔
Description:
There have been a lot of buzz about low carb diets for fat loss but what about muscle gain and improved exercise performance? Some have speculating that low carb diets may enhance exercise performance due to people becoming fat adapted & better at using fat for fuel

In ultra endurance athletes this appears to be fine, but once you get above 70% of a VO2 Max we start to see significant performance decrements on low carb diets.

During high intensity exercise we see even greater impairments in exercise performance from low carb diets, likely due to decreased glycogen availability in muscle. While muscle can use fat for fuel at low intensities (aerobic exercise) it is unable to use fat during high intensity (anaerobic) exercise. Thus, when glycogen is limited, less glucose is available for anaerobic metabolism & performance is impaired. 

When it comes to muscle gain, there is some evidence from Vargas et al that men who resistance trained while on a low carb diet gained LESS muscle and strength than those who at the same calories and protein on a higher carb diet. While carbohydrates do not stimulate protein synthesis they do decrease muscle protein breakdown & this may explain the differences observed in these studies as well as possible differences in exercise performance making it more difficult to create progressive overload in the low carb group. 

In this video I break it all down 😬
Image Text: & BIOL MUSCLE GAIN ON LOW-CARB DIET

Exercising at home and Training at home are different things in my eyes. 

Jumping around to Sean T or a youtube video is exercising, it’s just getting a sweat on where a million people can do the same programme and that’s no problem if you’re desperate.

But training is following a system of which your reps and sets are just one of many moving cogs which inch towards a goal. 

Although getting more high knees and mountain climbers do count as “progressive overload” not many clients have come up to me over the years with those as their goals. 

“James, my mountain climbers need work.”

You can train at home with no equipment but you’re very limited. From a TRAINING perspective I’d always recommend a suspension trainer where all you need is a strong tree or a door frame. 

As a coach, when you have that, I can programme suitable push exercises, pull exercises, core exercises and even isolation exercises on the triceps and biceps. 

When you can bring those together in a fashion that lines up with a goal you can work towards it.

For instance most women get an insane buzz from doing push ups without their knees down and progressing to their first chin up a lot more than they get a buzz from doing 30 burpees in a minute. 

At home your main resistance you’re using is gravity, with something as simple as a suspension trainer you can make gravity your bitch across so many dimensions. 

From there you may add a band, a free weight, a bench and before you know it... you’re a fitness wanker. 

Sorry to say it, but youtube workouts can suck a fat one. I like my clientele to train at home. 

Not. Just. Exercise. 

James

P.s check out @jamessmithacademy for an unlimited free trial - NO EXERCISE WANKERS ALLOWED.

If you’re not seeing the results you want from your training there’s a good chance you’re making 1 of those common mistakes. Here’s what to do instead:

1️⃣ Instead of always lifting the same weight for the same reps prioritize progression. Pick up a heavier weight or do more reps with the same weight. You want to be working close to failure (not just stopping because you get to the end of the number of reps on your training plan.) Your last reps should be *hard.* As in you couldn’t lift it again more than 1, maybe 2, times.

2️⃣ Instead of trying to burn as many calories as possible during your lifting sessions by turning everything into a giant circuit, by skimping on your rest time or spending your rest time doing cardio, slow down. Take rest times. 2-3 minutes if you’re lifting in the 1-5 rep range. 60 seconds if you’re lifting in the 6-12 rep range. 45-60 seconds in the 12+ rep range. Spend your training focusing on getting stronger.

3️⃣ Complicated isn’t better. In fact it’s usually not.  You don’t need to string a bunch of exercises together. You’ll see this a lot on social media posts of “trainers” who don’t actually have the experience or education to be training anyone. They’ll put together weird exercise combos. News flash: you shouldn’t be able to curl the same weight you’re squatting.

4️⃣ Stop skipping rest day.  You are not helping yourself training every day. Take a Minimum of 1 rest day a week (most of my clients train 3-4x per week.)

5️⃣ Stop chasing soreness. Soreness does not = a good training session. You will get sore sometimes. But you don’t need to be sore to get results,  and if you’re *always* sore you need to  take a look at your total training volume and your recovery.  Chase getting stronger not getting sore💪

Ok, what’d I miss? What’re some training mistakes you’ve made in the past?
Xx,
Kim

PS: I’ll show you exactly how to set up your training in my Menopause Weight Loss Course launching Tomorrow!Inside the course you’ll get a full 6 week strength training plan, optional metabolic conditioning circuits as well as cardio guidelines. In the meantime hit the link in my bio to come to my free webinar to get all the details.
Image Text: Kim Schlag @kimschlagfitnes 16 Top 5 Workout Mistakes 1 Always lifting the same weight for the same reps (no progression) 2 Focusing on burning calories during strength training 3 Thinking complicated better Training too often 5 Chasing soreness

Title: Weight Loss and Social Media
Description:
What do the accounts you follow say about your chances of losing weight? 

A new study examined social media characteristics of those who want to lose weight and those who have actually been successful with weight loss. Interestingly, the study found that people who are wishing to pursue weight loss were less likely to follow people who were thin, while people who were actually successful with weight loss were MORE likely to follow people who were thin. I discuss these results, what they mean, and the practical implications of them. 

What do you guys think? Leave a comment below ⬇️

Please share and save this post

Once upon a time, I edited a ton of my images. I look back sometimes and cringe beyond belief at how insecure I was and how silly I looked. But to be honest, I think that insecurity should be normalized too. Because we all have our own hang ups and that’s alright!

I am so proud that I’ve reached a point where I am comfortable with posting normal photos. Photos on the right should be normalized. Who the hell walks around with their abs popping 24/7? I certainly don’t.

I also want to take this moment to normalize weight fluctuations. As I’ve gotten older, I’ve had more weight fluctuations than I can count. Some due to health issues.. others due to stress/anxiety/depression and simply sometimes falling off the wagon.

Don’t let anyone guilt you into not having the ideal summer beach body that society conjured up. Not me, not anyone on this app, or real life!

Rare clips of me hitting Incline chest yesterday 😅 contrary to some of the comments I sometimes see regarding my upper chest development (or lack of 😏), incline bench press, incline smith press and incline dumbbell press have been staples in my routine from the beginning. 

Whilst you can grow your muscles and target specific areas to improve, as these muscles grow, they will form a specific shape. With years of training, some will develop that upper chest ledge you can rest a shaker on and some never will 😅. 

With all the upper chest work I’ve done over years (even at one point only hitting upper chest for at least a year) I’ve always been lower chest dominant. 
I suspect the reason could be either be the huge amount of dips I used to perform in my early years of training (search YouTube and you’ll find a video from 9yrs ago of me dipping with 220lbs 100kg between my legs, I did this often 😅) or the biomechanics of my long arms not being optimal for hitting upper chest 🤷🏾‍♂️

Regardless of all that I am very satisfied with my development, just thought it would be interesting to share 💪🏾👊🏾

The Upright row!

Here are a few tips that can help ensure you're getting the most from this exercise. 

❌Not pulling high enough and pulling too much weight. Most people ‘can’ perform full range, however, they tend to load it up which can affect their range. Lower the load and complete effective reps. You don't have to be an ‘upright row hero’ to get great results! 

❌Pulling too high. Yes, confusing right? Pull to where it is comfortable, avoiding any shoulder, elbow & wrist discomfort. So only go as high as you can safely. 

❌Uncontrolled descent. It's common for the concentric movement to be performed correctly but not control the eccentric AT ALL, letting the weight drop by gravities force.

❌Forward weight. Keeping the weight centred to the body not only allows for heavier lifts it targets your side delts more. So focus on keeping the weight flush to the body and elbows going up and not forward.

❌Dump the dancing. Keep to a strict technique and work the targeted muscles. (traps, side delts, all the muscles of the upper body). No legs & no swinging!!! 

LASTLY, you don't have to do Upright rows if you don't like them. Lots of people don't do them and have strong side delts and traps. There are SO many different side delt & trap exercises. Still, give upright rows a chance and play with the technique to see if you can get them to work for you. But if at the end of the day all they do is mess up your joints, too easy don't do them.

Description:
In my experience coaching, people really struggle with the concept of having a positive body image while also trying to improve their physique for competition or even bring up physique “weak points”. 

You might give push back to things you see online about the importance of a positive body image because you’re focused on “fixing” your physique from a competitive perspective. Thus, these can seem like contradictory concepts, but they don’t have to be. You don’t have to view yourself as defective or unworthy to improve as an athlete, whether we’re talking about throwing a fastball or getting bigger biceps. It might just be a matter of reframing. 

But on the other hand, maybe you really do have some negative thoughts and perceptions about your body that you don’t want to acknowledge. Maybe you make excuses for those thoughts and perceptions because you compete thinking “it’s just part of bodybuilding”? 

Wherever you are, I’d encourage you to head over to @team3dmj to read our new blog by our always awesome Mental Health Consultant Amanda Rizo MS, LPCC @rizo_amanda_marissa to learn just what positive body image is, what it means, and how it can fit in with competitive physique goals.
Image Text: NEW ARTICLE WHAT IS POSITIVE BODY IMAGE AND HOW DO WE CULTIVATE IT? BY: AMANDA RIZO

I was 15yrs old and just moved to Bethlehem, PA and just started attending Freedom High School. 

Within a month I’d already been arrested as well as suspended for fighting. I had an incident with a teacher/football coach named Jodi Cwik in the teachers lounge where we almost came to blows. 

I acted like a real asshole to him, so the next day I found him so I could apologize eye to eye and face to face.

HIP DIPS ARE NORMAL. Seriously. It is all based on your bone structure! And there’s honestly not a whole lot you can do about it. Yet I always get asked how to get rid of them! Your iliac crest is the curved upper portion of your pelvis which makes your hips protrude. The greater trochanter is the top portion of your femur and this tends to protrude outward from upper your thighs, forming a “dip” between the two landmarks-see my dips? This is literally your skeletal structure and no amount of dieting and workouts can truly fix this. So don’t be ashamed of them because they’re 100% normal and this is why your hips dip. Some hip dips are more visible than others. Every human body is so different. So please remember this next time you’re standing in front of the mirror judging your hips!
Image Text: Iliac crest Greater Trochanter

Description:
❌SAME BUTT, DIFFERENT POSE ❌

Don’t miss out on 95% of your life to weigh 5% less.

I remember hating my body once upon a time. I sat around making a list of every surgery that I wanted: a breast augmentation, nose job, lipo, Brazilian butt lift-you name it. Luckily I only went through with one of those and had my implants removed 7 years later.

We can be so hard on ourselves and allow social expectations to poison our minds. The cellulite sometimes does still bother me, but not as much as it used to. I’ve realized no matter how lean I get, I’ll still have some. But I’ve accepted that.

We can be our own worst enemies... if we allow ourselves to be. Our minds control so much. If you change your thinking, you change your life.

AD - HOW HAS THE WAY YOU TRAIN YOUR MIND CHANGED OVERTIME?
⁣
I would brush things under the carpet when I felt under pressure and would tell myself to get on with it, despite not being in the right frame of mind. I didn’t know the importance of switching off, setting goals and putting thought through plans in place. I simply thought I would be fine. ⁣
⁣
27 now with my more experience under my belt I know how important it is to have a fit healthy mind to succeed but most importantly enjoy the journey.⁣
⁣
I learnt I had to visualise what I wanted to achieve. I had to set out a plan seeking the advise from people who wanted to see me succeed, who wanted to help me grow. (Who do you surround yourself with?) ⁣
⁣
I also learnt I had to put my own interests first and had to say no to social peer pressure. Putting myself and health first is more than ok. I’m no ‘yes’ man like I once would have been. ⁣
⁣
Learning to switch off, finding my form of meditation that allows me to calm my mind and reflect on my current situation, allowing me to deal with stress and any anxiety I was experiencing. ⁣
⁣
Walking @man.like.roots, a tough workout or 20 minutes in the steam room. Phone, WhatsApp, Instagram, emails far away from sight does it for me. ⁣
⁣
We will all fail at some point, so how we cope will determine whether we succeed or not. Beating ourselves up won’t help so ⁣
we must learn to pause and reflect. ⁣
⁣
So being mentally fit is so important!! ↙️⁣
⁣
1. Eating healthy ⁣
2. Sleeping well ⁣
3. Exercising regularly ⁣
4. Surrounding yourself with positive people ⁣
5. Setting yourself goals/targets ⁣
6. Being able to say no (social peer pressure) ⁣
7. Meditation - calming your brain/anxiety/stress levels. ⁣
8. Have things to look forward to. ⁣
⁣
I’ve recently set myself a goal to improve my core strength so here’s a workout I completed yesterday 💪🏼⁣
⁣
1. Advanced Barbell roll outs - 6 x 4sets ⁣
2. Knee roll outs - 20 x 4sets⁣
3. Weighted flutter kicks - 40 seconds ⁣
4. Weighted v ups - 10reps⁣
5. Russian twists - 20reps⁣
6. Plated knee tucks - 20reps ⁣
X 3rounds (exercises 3-6)⁣
⁣

Dinner tonight! Teriyaki salmon + avocado over rice.

The sauce was super easy to make! All you need is:
1/2 cup soy sauce
2 tbsp honey 
2 garlic cloves, minced

Stir sauce ingredients together. Heat a skillet over medium and spray pan with olive oil. Place salmon filet into the pan searing the skin side first for 5 minutes. Flip and pour sauce over the salmon cooking for 3 minutes or until sauce starts to thicken. Remove from heat and serve with rice and 1/2 avocado chopped.

Most people think losing weight is about fighting against who they are right now when it should be about evolving into who they want to become. 

Read that again. 

And again.

Because what’s holding you probably back isn’t your diet or exercise plan. 

It’s the story you keep telling yourself.

The story being that you are “broken” and have to be “punished” with a weight loss plan to “fix” yourself. 

☝️ That’s some bullshit. 

You are not “broken.”

You don’t need to be “punished.”

And you don’t need to be “fixed.”

~

I get it.

You’re not satisfied with where you’re at right now.

There’s nothing wrong with that. 

But if you ARE unsatisfied, then you have to choose to accept it or change it.

If you choose to accept it, then stop beating yourself up about where you’re at right now.

If you choose to change it, then you need to be ready to embrace *the suck* that comes early on while you’re just getting started.

Embrace it, learn from it, and keep going. 

With time, you’ll suck less and less, and before you know it, you’ll be one of those people who figure out the “secret” to getting results. 😉

~

Small adjustments to help improve your technique and save your knees from that extra pressure.

Personally, I enjoy burpees & sprawls, call me crazy but there’s something about the way they fatigue my muscles and lungs faster than a lot of other bodyweight movements that I find satisfying. Possibly because burpees are a full-body workout that you gain strength in the entire body. (Arms, chest, quadriceps, glutes, hamstrings and core)

Burpees/Sprawls 
👉🏾 Fatigue your muscles fast
👉🏾 Quickly improve strength & conditioning
👉🏾 Require no equipment 
👉🏾 Require very little space

Landing on the ball of your feet is a common mistake made, my advice is to slow it down. Perfect your form and when you’re feeling confident, increase speed & go hard. 
While I know society has slapped a label on burpees like a form of punishment, they honestly are the complete opposite.
They are dynamic and fast-paced and can be a great addition to any training session. The rapid flexion and extension of the hips make them awesome for learning force production from core to extremity.

BEGINNER DIASTASIS RECTI WORKOUT using my @shopfighther glute bands! Did you know that booty bands work great for healing diastasis recti?

These are the three most simplest moves for healing DR. 🙌🏽 This workout is not only Diastasis Recti safe, but it’s made to actual HEAL it.

Diastasis Recti is a condition in which both halves of your abdominal muscles split open due to pressure of the growing baby. This allows for your organs to protrude through forming a tummy bundle or pooch. It doesn’t happen to all women, but for some.

These moves are also good for strengthening the pelvic floor & your Tranverse Abdominals. You have to rebuild your core from the inside out after pregnancy and avoid moves that could worsen your DA.

The transverse abdominis, also known as the TVA muscle, is the deepest innermost layer of all abdominal muscles and is located underneath your rectus abdominis. Think of it as the “corset” of your body. During pregnancy, the pelvic floor and TA keep your belly from dropping to your toes. The TA and PF, together with the uterus, work to push your baby out during delivery.
-
Moves to avoid for Diastasis Recti:
Front Plank
Twisting moves such as a Russian Twist
Crunches
Sit ups
-
How to check for DR:
Lie on your back with your knees bent, feet flat on the floor
Place your fingers with the palm facing you on your belly button
Lift your head and neck just slightly off the floor while you press down with your fingers. If there is a gap, that is the diastasis
Conduct the same test just above your belly button and just below the belly button.

How to do the moves:
Complete each move slowly and controlled while focusing on belly breathing.
Aim for 20 reps per move, 3 times.

#ad @underarmourwomen #UnderTheArmour | “How do you stay focused on your goals?”… I remember when my fitness journey first started and I couldn’t do one single press-up, not even on my knees. I face planted the floor so many times I lost count. It was just SO hard for me to get my head around, how could everyone make these look so easy??
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Fast forward 3+ years later and they are a staple in my routine. I had a goal, showed up and stayed focused on achieving it. Staying focused on my goals for me means not shying away from challenges. It’s not supposed to be easy, you’re not supposed to know how to do it yet — if you did, it wouldn’t be a goal.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My biggest advice for staying focused on your goals is to break them down, start small. I started just trying to get 1 from my knees, that then became 2, 3, 4 then I moved to my toes and started all over again. Break it down, keep showing up & keep reminding yourself why you’re doing it when your mind doubts you 🙌🏻 What’s one of your big goals right now?? #TheOnlyWayIsThrough

This was an important @team3dmj podcast episode. I joined @nunez3dmj and @3dmjcoach to discuss how to navigate the overwhelming amount of books, podcasts, and research papers on all of the various health and fitness topics. Getting overwhelmed by information these days is pretty much unavoidable. It’s great how available good info is these days, but it’s lost amongst mountains of less than good info. Also, knowing how to apply and interpret even good info, is challenging. As a content creator I often find my meaning doesn’t come across perfectly to everyone, and may not always have the needed context for everyone to be able to apply it. 

Given these challenges we answer the following questions: what is our advice when it comes to content consumption? How is consuming content different if you’re an athlete vs. if you’re a coach? What filters and processes do we use to cut through the noise of the internet? What are some of the most common mistakes we see when it comes to content consumption? What does, “Principles move slow, strategies move fast” mean?

The answers to these, plus many related questions are covered in this episode. Head over to the @team3dmj team page and click our bio link to listen 

Timestamps:
0:00​- Introduction
8:12​- The coaches’ advice for content consumption
34:09​- It’s hard to change your approach when your approach works
46:58​- Principles move slow, strategies move fast
56:59​- Consuming content as a coach vs. consuming content as an athlete

Let’s go Zoe! @zoey.kalilimoku 

Repost from @bleaver808

This video pretty much captures Zoeys heart. Most people don’t know that she aspires to be a pro level coach someday, and at the moment her heart is with coaching these kids!  She puts in any extra time that she has away from her studies and her own soccer career to work with and develop the kids. 

Most don’t know that at just 16, she has been invited to go overseas to play professionally in Europe. But we declined the offer to not lose her eligibility to play in college to be able to pursue her dream of being a coach someday as certain coaching certifications require you to have a college degree. It wasn’t an easy decision to make because of course a part of her dream is play professionally but we figured that she will only continue to get better from here. And to have the opportunity for one dream to come true right before you can be tempting. But with lots of prayer and advise from people who want to see her succeed long term, she made her decision. She has a lifetime ahead of her but I’m so glad to see that she has her head on straight. 

We love and fully support you Zoey!!!! Keep your standards high! 

@beasley_elite_sports_training @ballhawku @nationalplaymakersacademy @bleaver808

MY TOP TIPS FOR LUNGE FORM (low impact)
So many of you in the #SweatCommunity ask me for low impact alternatives to the exercises in @Sweat. 

Even if you’re not doing high impact training, you can still build your strength and fitness with low impact workouts that are more gentle on your body and your joints. 

One of the best low impact exercises to build your lower body strength are lunges. I love lunges because they can be done absolutely anywhere you have space to move, they require no equipment and they are perfect for any experience level.

HOWEVER this is one of the exercises that I have found that people do incorrectly and by doing this, they start to dislike it because their form is off and it starts to hurt in places when it shouldn't. When doing lunges, it's SO important to take the time to get confident with your form so that you're using the right muscles and getting a more effective and enjoyable workout! When you master your lunges, you'll not only strengthen you back, legs and hips, you'll also improve your mobility and stability! 💪 

Here are my top tips for nailing your lunge form, to get the most of out of your next lower body workout:

👉Make sure you don’t place your back foot directly behind your front foot. Plant both feet on the floor in a split stance with your left leg forward and your right leg back, ensuring that your feet are shoulder-width apart. This is your starting position.

👉Inhale. Bend both knees to approximately 90 degrees. If done correctly, your front knee should be aligned with your ankle and your back knee should be hovering just off the floor.

👉Exhale. Extend both knees to return to the starting position. Complete half of the specified number of repetitions on the same side, before completing the remaining repetitions on the other side.

Will you be trying my tips to improve your form next time you do lunges? Tell me in the comments below. 👇

Title: LOW IMPACT FULL BODY WORKOUT WITH MY MUM!
Description:
MY NEW PROGRAM! 💜
My mum always thought my programs were too hard and fast for her and her friends. It's one of the reasons I created my new Low Impact program. The program is for my mum and for ALL WOMEN like her, who don't want high intensity workouts that are fast and have jumping in them.

I designed Low Impact to have absolutely no jumping moves and to keep your whole body supported or at least one foot on the floor for most exercises.

So I invited mum over to my house to film some Low Impact workouts together and for her to really get to know the program. It was so much fun to train with her properly for the first time.

In this video we both did a Full Body Low Impact workout. As you can see in Low Impact we use time rather than number of reps in a workout. This means you can go at your own pace and focus on building up your strength over time.

✅Squat - 30 secs
✅Curl & Press - 30 secs
👉3 laps

✅Chest Press - 30 secs
✅Glute Bridge - 30 secs
✅Alternating Toe Tap - 30 secs
👉3 laps

I'm so proud of how well she did today in front of the cameras too.

{NEW BLOG: I Tried a Juice Cleanse For 2 Days.. Here’s What Happened! Link in my bio}

Ahhh the juice cleanse. It’s been around for ages promising marvelous things. I read where it was supposed to help with inflammation (celery juice craze), stomach issues, and even depression! Hmmmm.

After feeling sluggish for a few months, I decided to put it to the test to see exactly what could happen and if the promises were true. After all, I make a good guinea pig! 😂

What DID happen:
I did gain more energy it seemed as my body woke itself up at 5:30 instead of 8am.
It did beat my cravings (well after day one-the first whole day I was craving the new KFC chicken sandwich)!
It did give me a better outlook on which foods to choose for my body and to become more mindful about what I eat.
It did give my body a break from all the crap I’ve been eating and drinking lately.
I did load up very good nutrients, veggies, fruits, and herbs such as turmeric, ashwagandha, milk thistle, beets, kale, and algae.

What DIDN’T happen:
I didn’t lose weight or fat (don’t ever believe these claims)!
I didn’t feel magically different.
I didn’t “detox” through a cleanse alone. The truth is that your body’s organs detoxifies themselves!

Bottom line: This is not a quick fix-there’s no known proof that cleanses actually “clean” you. The body is always cleansing itself anyway! Your best bet is sticking to a well rounded diet filled with lots of fruits, veggies, and water!

To read about the juices I tried and what I did, click the link inside my bio to read my blog + watch my YouTube video.

Have you ever done a juice cleanse? What were your thoughts and what happened to you?

This kind of plate brings back so many great memories for me because this is the kind of thing my mum would make for my sister and I to eat after school, and I still eat like this today!⁣
⁣
My mum worked at my primary school so she always KNEW that we were going to be SO hungry when we got home because we had been running around all day and hadn’t eaten for a few hours!! ⁣
⁣
So she would cut up lots of fruit and vegetables and put them on a platter with a type of homemade dip (like tzatziki or hummus) for us to snack on. We used to complain and say that we wanted things like chips, ice-cream or chocolate. And she would say “I bet you will eat this!”. And sure enough, we did. ⁣
⁣
This kind of snack would keep us full enough before dinner, but didn’t fill us up so much that we didn’t want to eat our whole meal. ⁣
⁣
For those of you who are asking about how to stop unhealthy snacking while you’re at home, this kind of thing is exactly what I would recommend. Get prepared and chop up vegetables and keep them in the fridge. Then, when you're hungry or feel like a snack, you have a healthy option that is sitting right in front of you. It will make it so much easier to make good choices. ⁣

#healthysnacks #healthymeals #foodideas #healthyfoodideas #food #instafood #foodie
