When I first went back to the gym after having Arna, there were moments when I felt like I had nothing to give and absolutely no physical strength. The gym had always been the place where I felt in control, comfortable and strong. I felt so upset when I realised I couldn't do anything I used to be able to do. But I persisted and kept working, and eventually I've become stronger than I was before.

What I have now realised is that although this was a really difficult time, it actually allowed me to grow as a person. I was able to prove to myself that I could build my strength back and that felt amazing, I felt empowered and proud of myself. Also, being pregnant and becoming a mother gave me so much experience and I gained mental and emotional strength that I’d never had before. Now, I am even more understanding of other women's experiences and I have become so grateful for what my body can do. 

Tough times are going to make you stronger, and help you to grow. #SweatCommunity, I want you to realise the importance of your life experience. Tag someone who needs to hear this today. 💛

I absolutely love one sheet pan dinners! They are quick, easy, and require less dishwashing afterwards. If you’re looking for a yummy dinner idea, I’ve got you covered! Try this!

Sheet Pan Teriyaki Salmon & Veggies

Ingredients
4 6 ounce salmon fillets
2 cups broccoli florets
1 cup snow peas
1 cup bell pepper chopped
1 cup carrots sliced into thin strips
sesame seeds for garnish (optional)
Teriyaki Sauce:
1/2 cup light soy sauce or 1/4 cup dark soy & 1/4 cup water
1/4 cup brown sugar
2 garlic cloves minced
1 teaspoon sesame oil optional
1 teaspoon cornstarch

Instructions 
1. Pre-heat oven to 400F. Line a baking sheet with foil or grease with oil and set aside.
Whisk all the ingredients for the sauce in a medium bowl.Place salmon in a large ziplock bag or large bowl. Pour sauce over salmon and marinate in the fridge for 15 minutes or up to 24 hours.

2. Transfer salmon to baking sheet. Reserve the marinade that is left in the bag. Add broccoli, snow peas, bell pepper and carrot to the pan. Spoon a few teaspoons of the marinade oven veggies and drizzle with a teaspoon oil.

3..Bake at 400 for 15 minutes or until salmon is flaky and cooked through, bake times may vary by thickness of salmon.
While salmon is baking, transfer remaining marinade to a small sauce pan and bring to a boil then reduce heat to a simmer and cook, stirring occasionally until slightly thickened (2-3).

4. Remove salmon and veggies from the oven and brush remaining sauce on salmon fillets. Top with a sprinkle of sesame seeds if desired. Serve with rice, noodles, salad, or alone. Enjoy!

#salmon #salmondinner #veggies #pescetarianlife #cleaneating #healthyeating #mealprep #mealprepideas #mealprepping #mealprepsunday

Are frozen vegetables healthy for you?

This is a popular question for busy people who struggle to find time to prep and cook fresh produce on a daily. 
Now the way that you cook frozen vegetables CAN affect their nutrient content, BUT this is also the case with fresh produce. 🤔

What you need to look out for is whether the frozen vegetables that you are buying contain any added sugar, salt, or premade sauces and seasonings.

Frozen vegetables are a convenient addition to a balanced diet & I personal LOVE them and use them for both myself and my children.

So what is best?
Picking fresh veggies from your own veggie garden has to be the optimal situation. But (in Australia), veggies
often travel a very long distance to get to us. (this can be several days)
We know that the longer it takes to get fresh food to us from the farm, the more nutrients (in the food) slowly decrease.

I'm not saying fresh fruit and veg is not a good choice. But frozen vegetables are certainly a valid option.

Description:
If you have never worked out before or taken a long break.... TODAY IS YOUR DAY ONE 
For anyone who has taken a break from fitness, I know how hard it can be to start again. Potentially even more daunting or scary is taking that very first step. Starting to make a change and doing your first ever workout or exercise. One thing I want everyone to know and remember is that most people have been there too. Right where you are now. Every single person in your gym, everyone you admire in the fitness industry, even the trainers you follow on IG, the women in your workout classes or in your network have had their own DAY ONE! 

If you feel like starting to exercise or working out for the first time feels like a big mountain to climb, then I'm here to tell you that it doesn't need to be that hard. Taking just small steps to begin with is all you need. Try to attempt things that are manageable and are on your own level. Try moving more throughout your working day or try swapping a car ride for a short walk. 

My main advice is DON'T compare yourself to others, don't try to jump ahead too quickly. Go at your own pace with any exercise you do. I've created a brand new program that is perfect for this exact moment. If any women out there are reading this and don't know how or where to begin, then my Low Impact program has got you! The program is low intensity, meaning no jumping or explosive moves you might see a lot on Instagram. We take it slow with this program but you will still be able to build up your fitness level, just at your own pace. We always have a FREE 7-day @Sweat trial available for anyone wanting to take that first step and now my Low Impact program, which is my most accessible program ever, is here to get you moving. FALAFELS 😍
We all know that I absolutely LOVE this type of meal (gyro in Greek) and because it's so quick and easy to make my family and I often make this for dinner. Something that I have been really enjoying and adding to my gyro or yiros lately is falafels! Not only are falafels delicious, they are actually a great source of plant-protein. If you are vegetarian or flexitarian (which means you generally have a vegetarian diet, but occasionally eat meat), these are such a good option. 🙌

You can eat them by themselves dipped in hummus or with tzatziki, or you can add them to salads or put them in a wrap like this!

They are also really easy to make at home. This is the recipe I use:

✅ 250g tinned chickpeas, drained and rinsed
✅ ½ lemon, juiced
✅ 1 small handful fresh parsley, roughly chopped
✅ 1 garlic clove, crushed
✅ ½ tsp ground cumin
✅ ½ tsp ground coriander
✅ 2 tbsp wholemeal flour
✅ Salt and pepper, to taste
✅ 1 tbsp olive oil

Put all ingredients (except for the oil) in a food processor and blend until well combined. Put the falafel mixture into a large bowl then shape the mixture into 6 falafel balls, then flatten them slightly between your hands. Cover and refrigerate the balls for 30 minutes.

Heat oil in a large non-stick fry pan over medium heat. Cook the falafels for 4-5 minutes each side or until cooked through and golden in colour. Then add them into a wrap or pita bread like this one with some greek salad. SO yummy! 😍 

#SweatCommunity, let me know if you try my recipe and tell me what you think!!

Snack idea! Hummus with pita bread!! SO delicious. 😍
This recipe is my family recipe that I LOVE and make it all the time because it’s so quick and easy. 

Chickpeas (garbanzo beans) are the main ingredient, and they are an amazing pantry staple, as they’re an excellent source of both protein and fibre. When I make my hummus it usually lasts around 5 days in the fridge, so I always make a big batch on the weekends and then my snacks are sorted for the week ahead! 🙌

Recipe:
✅ 2 x 400g cans of chickpeas ⁣(garbanzo beans)
✅ 1 tsp cayenne pepper⁣
✅ 3 tbsp lemon juice⁣
✅ 2 garlic cloves, crushed⁣
✅ 1/2 cup olive oil⁣
✅ Sprinkle of salt and pepper⁣

Depending on what flavours you like, you could also add:⁣
✅ A handful of coriander⁣
✅ 1/2 tsp chilli flakes⁣

All you need to do is throw all of the ingredients into a blender, except for the olive oil, stopping to wipe down the edges when needed. Once blended, gradually add the olive oil until the hummus is a nice consistency. And that's it! You can then add toppings like tomato, red onion and herbs too if you like.

Description:
HIP DIPS WORKOUT using @shopfighther glute bands! Click the link in my bio to shop them.

Let’s get one thing straight: “hip dips” are not a flaw... yet I get asked constantly on how to get rid of them.

What are hip dips anyway? They’re the inward curves on the outer, upper thighs, just below the hip bone (scientifically called a trochanteric depression) due to a space between the hip bone and the femur (thigh bone). It’s usually most noticeable in women with higher and/or wider hip bones. 
Here’s the good news: If you have them, don’t be alarmed. It’s totally natural. The shape of your hip-to-femur joint requires no more concern or change than the shape of your knees, knuckles, or any other joint. Same thing with a thigh gap-it’s all down to your genetic structure.

How do we get rid of them? Well, you can’t target them and you can’t change your bone structure. You’ve got to find peace about this. BUT what you CAN do is build upon the muscle in this area aka the Gluteus Medius which can help *some* with appearance. However, I’m not going to bullshit you-I do not believe you can grow your muscles to completely “fill out” this space.

Here are several exercises to work the Gluteus Medius. I always say, if you can’t fix it, work it & flaunt it! 
Besides... what’s wrong with hip dips anyway?

Title: LEARN HOW TO DO PUSH-UPS
Description:
MY NEW PROGRAM! - LOW IMPACT 💜
LEARN HOW TO DO PUSH-UPS
Building your strength to be able to do push-ups can can take time. If you can't do push-ups yet, I always recommend that you don't go straight into them. Instead, build up your chest and wrist muscles first and make sure you know how to do them the right way to reduce your risk of getting an injury. 

It might take you a few weeks or months before you feel confident to do push-ups. Remember, it doesn't matter how quickly you're able to do an exercise, what's more important is taking it at your own pace and learning the correct technique. 

If you’re starting out on your fitness journey here are my tips if you're learning how to do push ups:

👉 Align your shoulders over your wrists
👉 Engage your core and glutes throughout movement
👉 Keep your chest lifted and press away from the floor
👉 Move as slow as necessary to maintain control
👉 Ensure elbows bend towards your feet

#SweatCommunity I've released my new Low Impact program for anyone returning to fitness or starting out for the first time. I've designed it so that you won't have to jump and it will take the stress out of your joints when you are working out. 

So give these tips for push-ups a go and if you want more low intensity exercises and workouts, give my new Low Impact program a go!

I'm loving trying new vegetarian options right now! These crispy baked cauliflower tacos with cabbage slaw look so delicious and are super simple to make with salad ingredients and vegetables from your fridge. I love how with a few simple tricks you can turn a simple veggie like cauliflower into something special. To make cauliflower the main event in a meal like this, I like to mix it up in a bowl with olive oil, garlic, lemon juice, salt and pepper and roast it in a really hot oven until it becomes brown and crispy on the edges. You can take it to the next level by adding some breadcrumbs to up the crunch factor! 

#SweatCommunity tell me your tips and tricks for making your veggies extra delicious? I'd love to hear in the comments below. 

#food #SweatCommunity #recipes

Pic: @eatwithclarity

You can make a nutritional bowl out of so many ingredients in your fridge or leftovers from dinners. Healthy eating can be easy and quick!

I love eating like this because it means you get to try a variety of different flavours and textures and you can use both fresh and cooked ingredients. This one uses beans and tofu but you could easily substitute your favourite protein or vegetable. 

I also love that you can eat this either as a bowl or mix it up and serve it in a taco shell or with your favourite flat bread to make a healthy wrap. 

Here's some ideas to help build a quick and easy nutritional bowl:

✅ Start with a leafy green. I like romaine lettuce or baby spinach or you could even try kale.
✅ Choose a protein that you like - why not try beans or tofu, or if you eat meat or fish choose your favourite! 
✅ Add some extra veggies like cucumbers, zucchini (courgette), snap peas, radish, green beans, broccoli or cauliflower. 
✅ Try to include some healthy fats. I like avocado, olive oil, olives and nuts for crunch. 
✅ Load in some extra flavour. I love making a homemade salad dressing with crushed garlic and olive oil. I also love to add chilli flakes and fresh lime to add some extra kick! 

#SweatCommunity what do you use to make your favourite nourish bowl? Tell me in the comments below! 👇

Did you know that by simply adding in a recovery session each week, or stretching before or after your workouts, you can improve your range of motion? Increasing your range of motion will help improve circulation and increase your flexibility, which means working out will feel easier because you will be able to do each exercise with proper form (well, you'll still be working hard, haha 😜). Title: HOW TO CHOOSE THE RIGHT WEIGHTS
Description:
If you don’t know what weight is right for you, here’s a quick and easy guide to getting started. 

Choosing the right weights depends on which one of my programs you're doing. I know that when you first start working out, selecting the right weights can feel intimidating. With so many different weight amounts and types - from dumbbells, to medicine balls, kettle bells and barbells - it can be confusing to know where to start.

Whether you’re wanting to build muscle, increase flexibility or grow stronger, choosing the right weights to add to your workout can help. Using weights is not only an amazing way to increase your strength, it's also great for beating stress and challenging your muscles - so they can come back stronger! 💪

So if you’ve been unsure about where to start with weights, I’ve created this guide to give you all the info you need. How to get started, when to increase your weights and, just as importantly, when to STOP increasing weight. 

For everyone who is completing one of my programs and is incorporating weights, I recommend you go lighter so you can complete more reps and build up resistance rather than only being able to complete a few reps with heavier weights. 

#SweatCommunity watch this video and use it as your weights cheat sheet! Give it a try and tell me how you go in the comments below! 👇

I made a video like this recently and you guys couldn’t believe I used an editing app! You thought I was wearing real makeup. Well I’m back with another one to show you that you can change even more than just your facial features.

I was so inspired with @dove and their newest campaign against editing apps. They literally took a bare faced pre-teen and turned her into a grown supermodel. Don’t believe me? Go see it or checkout my stories.

Studies show 80% of Canadian girls are using photo editing apps by the age of 13. I can’t imagine the stats for USA. What are these apps teaching us? To hate our natural look and live in a fantasy world of what we only wish we could view ourselves as? When we look in the mirror, these apps leave us feeling like shit when we see our real selves. I’ve often heard women say, “I wish this filter was real life!”

I feel these apps should be banned. You don’t know what’s real these days until you see it. And even when you see it, you still don’t know thanks to cosmetic surgery.

Show this to your sons & daughters. Warn them. If I had seen this when I was 14, it would’ve prevented my eating disorder and helped to have given me better self esteem.

See my stories for the side by side before and after comparison.

#nodigitaldistortion #theselfietalk

Description:
POST PREGNANCY WORKOUT
After going through the experience of giving birth,  it can take time for women's bodies to regain strength.

After I was pregnant with Arna, I found that hip strength was a particular area that took time to rebuild before I could slowly work my way back up to higher impact exercises. This inspired me to create a workout for all the #SweatCommunity who are looking to get back into fitness after having a baby, to help gently rebuild hip strength and return to exercise with confidence. 

Pregnancy, as well as carrying around little kids all day (yes, I can relate haha!), can place extra strain and pressure on your hips. This workout has been designed to help you gradually rebuild your muscle strength before you’re ready to do higher intensity workouts.

✅ Four-Point Arm & Leg Extension - 16 reps (8 per side)
✅ Donkey Kick - 16 reps (8 per side)
✅ Fire Hydrant - 16 reps (8 per side)
✅ Glute Bridge - 20 reps
✅ Clam - 16 reps (8 per side)
✅ Hip Abduction - 16 reps (8 per side)

Try doing 2 laps - and tell me how you go in the comments. 👇

Every woman and every pregnancy is different, so make sure you speak to your healthcare professional and seek clearance before exercising after giving birth (like I did). For more post-pregnancy workouts, check out my Post-Pregnancy program on @Sweat.

www.kaylaitsines.com/app

Description:
POST PREGNANCY WORKOUT: UPPER BODY & CORE 
We all know exercising has so many benefits, but after having a baby it can be hard to know where to start and how to regain your strength. While you may be keen to stay active post pregnancy, your body has been through some big (and amazing!) changes, so it is really important to take it slowly and gradually to rebuild your foundational fitness. 💪

After giving birth to Arna, I was genuinely shocked at the toll pregnancy had taken on my body. I felt like I couldn't put one foot forward on the treadmill, I thought my career as a personal trainer was over. A job that I LOVED... I thought I couldn't do it anymore. 

I came to realise there isn’t clear guidance for women who want to start exercising after pregnancy. So that's why I created my Post-Pregnancy program in @Sweat - for women like me who had no idea where to start. 

Here’s an upper body and core workout to give you an idea of what to expect in my Post-Pregnancy program: 

WARM UP: 
✅ Thoracic Foam Roll - 50 sec
✅ Child's Pose - 60 sec
✅ Floor Slides - 30 sec

CIRCUIT: 
✅ Bent-Over Row - 12 reps 
✅ Shoulder Press - 12 reps
✅ Bent-Over Reverse Fly - 15 reps 
✅ Hover - 30 sec 

Complete 1 lap of the warm up and 3 laps of the circuit! 

SAVE this workout and let me know how you go in the comments below! 🙌

Remember - it’s so important that you obtain clearance from your health professional after giving birth before starting any exercise program.

www.kaylaitsines.com/app

#BBGathome #fitness #postpregnancy #Sweat

Description:
Tuesday reminders 
-
✨Your happiness & mental health comes first.
✨ Try not to make assumptions
✨ Will it matter in 5 years? 
✨You’re deserving of good things ❤️

A post lower body stretch session to save & get done because I know most of you skipped stretching this week👀
-
Look these stretches probably aren’t new to you, you know you need to get it done after a session but without the structure there you probably forget so try this routine which focuses on hip flexors, hamstring, glutes. Do all the stretches or just pick 3.
-
Do 1-2 sets of 30 seconds to 1 minute. Get comfortable being uncomfortable with these static stretches. Challenge yourself to get into the positions that are uncomfortable for you & hold it there. You can’t say static stretching doesn’t work if you aren’t really giving it a good go.

Celebrating surviving lockdown✨-
-
Thank you for supporting me during this period, i’m so grateful . Hope you had the best Saturday ❤️

Gyms are open & here’s my top tips if you plan on going to an adult gymnastics session any time soon 💪🏼
-
1- Check your local gym club to see if they are running open sessions. They are more places that run them than you think it’s just a matter of finding where & the closest session to you.
2- Have a structure ie warm up, train, conditioning, stretch but have no expectations of training. You don’t want to leave disappointed & deflated, instead spend the time getting used to the environment, chatting to some new people, using the equipment, trying some skills. 
3- Talk to people! You’ll be sharing the floor or tramp or bars with other people so find out what days people train, what days are busy, what they do, how they learnt.
4- Have fun!!!! When was the last time you jumped on a trampoline or did a forward roll? Literally even if you never go back again at least your inner child had some fun. 
-
Get the first session out of the way, I DARE you 😉❤️
Image Text: ONDON

Description:
3 exercises to help develop strength & flexibility for middle splits 🙌🏼
-
I’ve just uploaded a YouTube video that has all information on why I love these 3 & how they will help if you are on the journey to a middle/ side split! Go check it out through the link in my bio❤️
-
Let’s get strong & flexy❤️

You don’t need a strong core to hold a straight handstand 🙊
-
Yep it’s a myth. Don’t get me wrong I am a huge advocate of incorporating hollow body drills & core exercises into handstand training because it’s an incredibly important shape needed in gymnastics skills & it’s a great way to develop body awareness so you know what the shape feels like but what’s more important for your handstand is to understand what’s going on with your upper body. 

The straight handstand you see is a result of having the shoulder flexibility to get arms to ears & the strength to elevate the shoulders during the handstand. So if you can stand with yours arms in the air , ribs down you have the ability to hold a straight handstand. If you are weaker or not flexible, the body compensates to try & help you balance & that’s where shapes like the banana or pikes can occur. The downside is our wrists are a lot less stable than our hips so it won’t be an easy journey. 

I would however also point out that you can hold a handstand & develop pretty good handstand skills without a perfect line . It’s more of an aesthetic thing so don’t get too caught up on that whilst on your journey! 

My beginner handstand guide is in my bio ❤️

Matching gym wear is so POWERFUL💙
-
Crazy start to Monday for me with classes restarting, gyms re opening & finishing off a 3 month block of sessions with @impowercreatives 🎉
-
In January i invested a lot of money into myself with new courses, mentors & honestly for the growth it’s given me it’s been totally totally worth it. 
-
I think investing money into yourself through coaches & mentors & courses can sometimes be really hard to do but I think when we hold our hands up & realise we can’t do it all ourselves & that there are people there to help us & (if you get the right person) it will be worth every single penny. 
-
I appreciate every single person that has trusted me & put their flexibility training in my hands for the month because they took the step out of the comfort zone to come & learn more about a skill they didn’t know how to develop on their own. My aim is to provide a space that keeps people accountable, connects them to a community & helps them learn how to actually get flexible as an adult. It’s exciting to see how my own growth is now helping other people too! So excited for session 2 on Thursday 💙

Smiling during middle splits practise to convince yourself you aren’t in any discomfort🔥(swipe for vid)
-
I am so proud of my middle splits. They are slowly but surely becoming so much stronger & more comfortable & everything I’m learning gets put not only into my own training but my strong & flexy classes which start again TOMORROW.
-
Live classes for the second block start tomorrow morning & I am so excited to see everyone & get back to regular training myself. All information is in my highlights! ❤️

Thoughts are not facts 💪🏼
-
Let me tell you I know how hard it is when the voice in your head starts feeding you lies & I also know how much time, pain & stress you can remove if you can stop those thoughts in their tracks early doors so here’s some tips that I’ve found help me out.
-
1- Being aware of my triggers. Even if i don’t really want to admit what sets me off because it feels silly , holding my hands up & being more self aware can help stop things getting out of control. 

2 - I imagine I’m in a court case with myself. I present myself with the actual facts. 
‘I’m a bad teacher’ well actually you have 20 plus reviews here saying how much everyone enjoyed it so that’s not the case’ 
‘Noone enjoys my content’ oop well actually you have a community of people here that felt comfortable sharing their experiences in space you created . 
‘I got a bad comment everyone hates me’ okay is it constructive criticism or is it just spiteful. If it’s constructive you are allowed to get things wrong if it’s spiteful block & delete. 

3- Removing myself from situations with instant gratification. What i don’t want is to use others to make me feel better. Because while a very good temporary fix it’s not long lasting. Instead I trying doing something solely for myself & because I enjoy it. Reading a book, walk with a friend, study, Netflix, journalling, training. 

I hope these tips help. Sending lots of ❤️

Block 2 of strong and flexy classes is starting 12th April🤩

So excited to be able to put on this second block of classes! If you have no idea how to approach flexibility training as an adult & are struggling to get started or get committed to making your flexibility a priority then these classes could be perfect for you!

Our bodies usually allow us more range of motion where we are strong & can demonstrate control so these classes work on strengthening muscles that allow us into positions like the middle split, front splits and bridge through the range of motion & aswell as stretching.
-
Check out my story & strong & flexy highlight for more info & the swipe up ❤️

The deal with adult gymnastics 
-
Had some great chats in my dms yesterday about adult gymnastics. Many of the conversations were about how many people wanted to try it but just had no idea where to start but also...
X - Not wanting to go alone
X- Fear of being a beginner & being the worst
X- Fear of falling & embarrassment 
X - Not knowing how to structure an open session by themselves
X- Not even knowing adult gymnastics was a thing. 
X- Feeling like their body wasn’t physically ready for the demands of gymnastics (not flexible, strong, fit enough) 
-
I use adult gymnastics as a general term here but open gym sessions are home to calisthenics athletes, parkour athletes, martial artists, cheerleaders, trickers of all levels & in my experience everyone is lovely. It’s a community of people who just really love training & pushing the limits of what’s possible with their bodies.
-
As a beginner that might seem daunting but I can promise you that the majority of people there started learning as adults too & are happy to have a chat, encourage you & give you some tips. We are all too worried about trying to not fall on our own face than if you fall on yours & if you do, someone will be right there to help you up & encourage you to go again. 
-
As gyms re open i will try to post once a week about tips for going to open adult gym classes & try & give you the little push you need to get started on your journey! Dms are always open for questions 🙌🏼❤️

Happy Easter 🐣❤️
-
Suns out, we’re seeing more of our families & Lots to be grateful for❤️. Can you tell how uncomfortable I am having my photo when not in gym wear 😂

Horse stancing my way to a strong middle split 💪🏼 (swipe for video & save to remember to try it)
-
Okay so something I introduced a little while ago when training my middle splits & also teaching is the horse stance squat. I’m flexible enough to get into my middle splits but I’m not very strong there so this has been a game changer. 
-
When you think of it a middle split is a very wide & very low squat & you can see how it really does start to look like a middle split. Obviously you start with legs a lot closer together & when you can do sets where hips go below knees & chest is up  you can take legs wider. 
-
I have loved playing around with these over the last month. I like to pause at the bottom for 3-5 seconds for maybe 10-15 reps. Usually I go bodyweight but have started playing around with some external load & here is where I’m currently at! 
-
Give it a try if middle splits is your goal🙌🏼

Happy Easter weekend 🐥 
-
After a full week of rest I’m finally ready to start training again🎉. Having a fitness account when you aren’t doing any fitness & watching everyone else do their bit can sometimes be a bit of a challenge. However, like I said the other day, rest is important . We need it & we need to enjoy it.
-
But with all the rest I’ve had lots of time to focus on plans for April & a new block of strong & flexy classes are coming back this month!!! Be sure to check your emails if you are on the list to see what those who took part this month had to say & when I’ve confirmed the start date there will be lots of info up on my stories in the next week ❤️. 

Thank you for the support, have a lovely weekend ❤️

Caption this ✨

Best caption gets a free strong & flexy class from the on demand library 🌸

A reminder that fully relaxing & resting is still productive. If you don’t enjoy your rest days because you are worried about not working or all the things you feel you should be doing then it’s not really resting. When I’m struggling to switch off here are my top tips. 
🌸 Phone away (
🌸Hydrate
🌸Go to bed earlier 
🌸 Eat some good food (ice cream mandatory) #
🌸 Call a pall
🌸 Read a book
🌸Listen to a podcast
🌸Walk / Fresh air
🌸Have a bath
🌸 Write what’s on your mind
🌸 Put on fav playlist 
-
It’s all so simple but sometimes you need to see someone say it to make you realise you aren’t really resting at all. If you don’t rest you burn out & burn out is not CUTE, look after urself 🌸💛

Gymnastics style Ab workouts for the win 🔥 (save & try💪🏼)
-
I know these type of core exercises take a bit of a bashing but i not only love them for a core  challenge  but also body awareness. This workout is built around our hollow body shape. You’ll see my lower back stays pressed into the floor when I return to a hollow body shape every rep . Even the final exercise my glutes are squeezed & tail bone tucked. 
-
If you are going to do these exercises make sure you do them properly. Be aware of the shapes you are making & slow it right down if needed. Less reps down better 🙌🏼
-
Start with 20 secs on 20 off & built to 30/40 secs on 💛

Learning to be proud of me❤️
-
I posted this to my story yesterday & felt a little emosh & I can’t remember how many of you were touched by it. I forget how long some of you have been on this journey with me. I literally for the longest time have never felt good at anything.  In my head I couldn’t get it right, I couldn’t live up to expectations I’d made up in my own head & I just didn’t believe in myself. When you can’t figure it out or get started it seems like everyone around you is & you feel like something is wrong with you.
-
If you can take Small steps forwards & give yourself permission to get things wrong it opens up so many doors. Take everything as a learning opportunity & then congratulate yourself because you made it happen❤️

Happy Friday ❤️

HANDSTAND CONDITIONING 🔥
-
Get used to being upside down & build some endurance in your shoulders 💪🏼. All 4 exercises with no rest & complete 2 rounds 🙌🏼
-
10 shoulder taps
10 walkouts 
20 second L hold
10 shoulder shrugs

Learn to step away from immediate results of training 💪🏼
-
The reason we are bad at things, is probably because we haven’t spent a lot of time doing them. If you haven’t given your flexibility ANY attention for years , you aren’t going to have great flexibility because you haven’t been using it. You cannot then expect to undo years of not using a range of motion in a month or 2 through 1 ‘mobility flow’ a week.
-
If you want to IMPROVE something, you need to do it above the level you use it everyday & you need to do it consistently. So if you do want to improve your flexibility above your current level be honest with yourself about what your goals actually are, what your starting point is & how much time you can dedicate to achieving that goal.  With realistic expectations in check, start chipping away at it for a few months & then re asses.
-
It’s one thing I’ve had to drill into myself lately with my training & I had to ask myself ‘have I earned the right to be disappointed with my results’. i had to ask myself whether I was trying that hard & consistently showing up & sometimes i had to hold my hands up like nah I didn’t & that’s totally okay. Training should be for life &’it’s a process & some of it is ugly but consistency will always win🙌🏼
